    {"w":"with","ph":"/wɪð/","pos":"preposition","gr":"connector","rt":"with","fam":["without","within","withstand"],"pl":"","tn":[],"hi":"के साथ/सहित","en":"accompanied by or using","ds":"Indicates accompaniment, manner, or the use of something.","dd":"'With' is a preposition that expresses accompaniment ('come with me'), means or instrument ('cut with a knife'), manner ('with care'), and association. It forms many phrasal verbs and fixed expressions. Its antonym 'without' means lacking accompaniment.","ex":"She went to school with her younger brother.","exh":"वह अपने छोटे भाई के साथ स्कूल गई।","syl":["with"],"syn":["alongside","together with","using","by means of","including"],"ant":["without","apart from","excluding"],"rel":["alongside","together","among","within","beside","by"],"dif":"basic","fr":14,"ew":0.0,"it":"relational","rp":"high","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"general","spr":"preposition","dl":["noun","pronoun"],"co":["me","you","him","her","them","us","my","your","our"],"st":["accompaniment","instrument","manner","association"],"cv":["accompaniment use","instrument use","manner use","used in phrasal verbs"],"su":["preposition","connector"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"he","ph":"/hiː/","pos":"pronoun","gr":"subject","rt":"he","fam":["him","his","himself"],"pl":"","tn":[],"hi":"वह (पुल्लिंग)","en":"third-person singular masculine pronoun","ds":"Refers to a male person or animal previously mentioned.","dd":"'He' is the third-person singular masculine subject pronoun in English. It is used to refer to males (and sometimes animals when gender is known). Its related forms are 'him' (object), 'his' (possessive), and 'himself' (reflexive).","ex":"He is a very talented musician and composer.","exh":"वह एक बहुत प्रतिभाशाली संगीतकार और गायक है।","syl":["he"],"syn":["the man","the boy","that person"],"ant":["she","they"],"rel":["him","his","himself","man","boy","person"],"dif":"basic","fr":15,"ew":0.0,"it":"identity","rp":"high","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"person","spr":"subject","dl":["verb"],"co":["is","was","has","will","can","should","said","told","went","did"],"st":["masculine","third person","singular","reference"],"cv":["referring to male person","referring to male animal","used in generic sense (historical)"],"su":["subject"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"as","ph":"/æz/","pos":"conjunction","gr":"connector","rt":"as","fam":[],"pl":"","tn":[],"hi":"जैसे/जब/क्योंकि/उतना","en":"in the same way, manner, or degree; while; because","ds":"Used to express comparison, simultaneous actions, or reason.","dd":"'As' is a highly flexible word in English. It functions as a conjunction of comparison ('as fast as'), time ('as I was leaving'), reason ('as you know'), and manner ('do as I say'). It also works as a preposition in roles ('served as captain') and as an adverb in comparisons.","ex":"She spoke as clearly as she possibly could.","exh":"उसने जितना हो सके उतना स्पष्ट रूप से बोला।","syl":["as"],"syn":["like","while","since","because","equally","when"],"ant":["unlike","differently"],"rel":["like","while","since","when","because","though","although"],"dif":"basic","fr":16,"ew":0.0,"it":"relational","rp":"high","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"general","spr":"connector","dl":["verb","adjective","adverb","noun"],"co":["well","much","soon","long","far","good","bad","fast","known"],"st":["comparison","manner","simultaneity","reason"],"cv":["conjunction of comparison","conjunction of time","preposition of role","used in fixed expressions"],"su":["connector","modifier"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"you","ph":"/juː/","pos":"pronoun","gr":"subject","rt":"you","fam":["your","yours","yourself","yourselves"],"pl":"","tn":[],"hi":"तुम/आप","en":"second-person pronoun","ds":"Refers to the person or people being spoken to.","dd":"'You' is the second-person pronoun in English, used for both singular and plural, and for formal and informal registers. Unlike many languages, English uses a single form 'you' for all cases. Its related forms include 'your' (possessive), 'yours', and 'yourself/yourselves' (reflexive).","ex":"You should always believe in yourself.","exh":"तुम्हें हमेशा खुद पर विश्वास रखना चाहिए।","syl":["you"],"syn":["thou","thee","ye"],"ant":["I","me","we","they"],"rel":["your","yours","yourself","yourselves"],"dif":"basic","fr":17,"ew":0.2,"it":"conversational","rp":"high","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"person","spr":"subject","dl":["verb","adjective"],"co":["can","will","should","must","are","know","want","need","have"],"st":["second person","address","direct speech"],"cv":["singular use","plural use","formal address","informal address"],"su":["subject","object"],"wuc":["daily conversation","formal","informal","command"]},
    {"w":"do","ph":"/duː/","pos":"verb","gr":"predicate","rt":"do","fam":["does","did","done","doing","undo","redo"],"pl":"","tn":["do","does","did","done","doing"],"hi":"करना","en":"to perform an action; auxiliary for questions and negation","ds":"To perform or carry out an action; also used as auxiliary for questions.","dd":"'Do' is both a main verb meaning to perform or carry out an action, and an auxiliary verb used to form questions, negatives, and emphatic statements. As a main verb it is highly versatile. As an auxiliary it appears in constructions like 'Do you know?', 'She doesn't like', and 'I do agree'.","ex":"What do you do for work every day?","exh":"तुम हर दिन काम के लिए क्या करते हो?","syl":["do"],"syn":["perform","execute","carry out","accomplish","complete","act"],"ant":["undo","stop","avoid","neglect"],"rel":["make","act","perform","complete","finish","execute"],"dif":"basic","fr":18,"ew":0.0,"it":"action","rp":"high","cs":"any","dc":"question","td":"action","spr":"verb","dl":["subject","object"],"co":["you","we","they","not","well","better","more","what","how"],"st":["action","performance","auxiliary","question formation"],"cv":["main verb use","auxiliary use","emphatic use"],"su":["predicate","auxiliary"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"at","ph":"/æt/","pos":"preposition","gr":"connector","rt":"at","fam":[],"pl":"","tn":[],"hi":"पर/में (स्थान/समय)","en":"indicating a specific location or time","ds":"Used to indicate a precise location, time, or direction toward something.","dd":"'At' is a preposition primarily used for precise location ('at the corner'), specific times ('at 5 o'clock'), and direction ('look at me'). It appears in many fixed expressions and phrasal verbs. It contrasts with 'in' (enclosed spaces) and 'on' (surfaces).","ex":"We will meet at the library at three o'clock.","exh":"हम तीन बजे पुस्तकालय में मिलेंगे।","syl":["at"],"syn":["in","by","near","by the location of"],"ant":["from","away from"],"rel":["in","on","by","near","toward","around"],"dif":"basic","fr":19,"ew":0.0,"it":"relational","rp":"high","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"general","spr":"preposition","dl":["noun","time expression","place noun"],"co":["home","work","school","night","least","first","all","once"],"st":["location","time","direction","precision"],"cv":["location use","time use","direction use","used in fixed expressions"],"su":["preposition","connector"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"this","ph":"/ðɪs/","pos":"determiner","gr":"determiner","rt":"this","fam":["these","that","those","the"],"pl":"","tn":[],"hi":"यह/इस","en":"used to refer to something nearby or just mentioned","ds":"Points to a specific nearby person, thing, or idea just mentioned.","dd":"'This' is a demonstrative determiner and pronoun used to indicate something nearby in space or time, or something just mentioned. It contrasts with 'that', which refers to something farther away. In discourse it introduces new information or points back to what was just said.","ex":"This new technology will change the world.","exh":"यह नई तकनीक दुनिया बदल देगी।","syl":["this"],"syn":["the present","the current","such a","the mentioned"],"ant":["that","those","other"],"rel":["that","these","those","the","here","now"],"dif":"basic","fr":20,"ew":0.0,"it":"relational","rp":"high","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"general","spr":"determiner","dl":["noun"],"co":["is","was","means","shows","time","year","way","place"],"st":["proximity","demonstration","reference"],"cv":["demonstrative use","introductory use","referring to recent topic"],"su":["determiner","pronoun"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"but","ph":"/bʌt/","pos":"conjunction","gr":"connector","rt":"but","fam":[],"pl":"","tn":[],"hi":"लेकिन/परंतु/किन्तु","en":"introducing contrast or exception","ds":"Used to introduce a contrast, exception, or unexpected information.","dd":"'But' is a coordinating conjunction that introduces a contrasting idea, an exception, or something unexpected. It signals that what follows differs from or qualifies what came before. It can also mean 'except' ('everyone but me') or 'only' in formal contexts.","ex":"She tried hard, but she could not finish the test.","exh":"उसने बहुत कोशिश की, लेकिन वह परीक्षा खत्म नहीं कर सकी।","syl":["but"],"syn":["however","yet","still","nevertheless","although","except"],"ant":["and","so","therefore"],"rel":["however","yet","although","though","nevertheless","despite","still"],"dif":"basic","fr":21,"ew":0.1,"it":"logical","rp":"high","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"general","spr":"connector","dl":["clause","sentence"],"co":["I","he","she","we","they","you","it","not","also","still"],"st":["contrast","exception","adversative","qualification"],"cv":["conjunction of contrast","exception use","informal use"],"su":["connector"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"his","ph":"/hɪz/","pos":"pronoun","gr":"modifier","rt":"he","fam":["he","him","himself"],"pl":"","tn":[],"hi":"उसका (पुल्लिंग)","en":"belonging to a male person","ds":"Possessive determiner or pronoun referring to a male.","dd":"'His' serves as both a possessive determiner ('his book') and a possessive pronoun ('the book is his'). It is the masculine third-person singular possessive, related to 'he' and 'him'. It can refer to males or to animals of known male gender.","ex":"His performance in the exam was outstanding.","exh":"परीक्षा में उसका प्रदर्शन उत्कृष्ट था।","syl":["his"],"syn":["belonging to him","of him"],"ant":["her","their","my","your"],"rel":["he","him","himself","hers","theirs","mine"],"dif":"basic","fr":22,"ew":0.0,"it":"identity","rp":"high","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"person","spr":"modifier","dl":["noun"],"co":["name","work","life","family","father","mother","friend","voice"],"st":["possession","masculine","third person","singular"],"cv":["determiner use","pronoun use"],"su":["modifier","determiner"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"by","ph":"/baɪ/","pos":"preposition","gr":"connector","rt":"by","fam":["nearby","bypass","byline","bystander"],"pl":"","tn":[],"hi":"द्वारा/के पास/तक","en":"indicating agent, means, proximity, or deadline","ds":"Used to show who did something, how it was done, or nearness to a place or time.","dd":"'By' is a preposition with several uses: it indicates the agent in passive constructions ('written by her'), means or method ('travel by train'), proximity ('sit by the fire'), and deadline ('finish by Friday'). It also appears in many idiomatic expressions.","ex":"The novel was written by a famous author.","exh":"यह उपन्यास एक प्रसिद्ध लेखक द्वारा लिखा गया था।","syl":["by"],"syn":["through","via","near","beside","alongside"],"ant":["away from","far from"],"rel":["through","via","near","beside","alongside","past","using"],"dif":"basic","fr":23,"ew":0.0,"it":"relational","rp":"high","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"general","spr":"preposition","dl":["agent noun","method noun","time expression","place noun"],"co":["the","my","your","their","himself","herself","now","far"],"st":["agency","means","proximity","deadline","passive"],"cv":["passive agent use","means use","proximity use","deadline use"],"su":["preposition","connector"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"from","ph":"/frɒm/","pos":"preposition","gr":"connector","rt":"from","fam":[],"pl":"","tn":[],"hi":"से/की ओर से","en":"indicating origin, starting point, or source","ds":"Shows where something or someone originated or started.","dd":"'From' is a preposition indicating origin ('from India'), starting point in time or space ('from morning to night'), source or cause ('learn from experience'), and separation ('take from the shelf'). It expresses the beginning of a movement or range.","ex":"She traveled all the way from Paris to London.","exh":"वह पेरिस से लंदन तक की यात्रा की।","syl":["from"],"syn":["out of","originating in","coming from","starting at"],"ant":["to","toward","into"],"rel":["to","since","out of","away","off","toward"],"dif":"basic","fr":24,"ew":0.0,"it":"relational","rp":"high","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"general","spr":"preposition","dl":["place noun","source noun","time expression","person noun"],"co":["home","work","school","there","here","abroad","far","away","start"],"st":["origin","source","starting point","separation"],"cv":["origin use","starting point use","source use","separation use"],"su":["preposition","connector"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"they","ph":"/ðeɪ/","pos":"pronoun","gr":"subject","rt":"they","fam":["them","their","theirs","themselves"],"pl":"","tn":[],"hi":"वे/उन्होंने","en":"third-person plural pronoun or singular gender-neutral pronoun","ds":"Refers to multiple people or things previously mentioned; also used as a singular gender-neutral pronoun.","dd":"'They' is the third-person plural subject pronoun, referring to multiple people or things. In modern usage it is also increasingly accepted as a singular pronoun for non-binary individuals or when gender is unknown or irrelevant ('someone called — they left a message').","ex":"They decided to start the meeting early.","exh":"उन्होंने बैठक जल्दी शुरू करने का फैसला किया।","syl":["they"],"syn":["those people","the group","people"],"ant":["I","he","she","we"],"rel":["them","their","theirs","themselves","people","the group"],"dif":"basic","fr":25,"ew":0.0,"it":"relational","rp":"high","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"person","spr":"subject","dl":["verb"],"co":["are","were","have","said","went","will","can","should","did"],"st":["plural","third person","reference","gender-neutral"],"cv":["plural person reference","gender-neutral singular use"],"su":["subject"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"we","ph":"/wiː/","pos":"pronoun","gr":"subject","rt":"we","fam":["us","our","ours","ourselves"],"pl":"","tn":[],"hi":"हम","en":"first-person plural pronoun","ds":"Refers to the speaker and one or more other people.","dd":"'We' is the first-person plural subject pronoun, referring to the speaker and one or more other people. Its object form is 'us', its possessive is 'our/ours', and its reflexive is 'ourselves'. It expresses shared identity, community, or collective action.","ex":"We are planning a trip to the mountains.","exh":"हम पहाड़ों की यात्रा की योजना बना रहे हैं।","syl":["we"],"syn":["us","our group","all of us"],"ant":["they","you","I"],"rel":["us","our","ours","ourselves","people","together"],"dif":"basic","fr":26,"ew":0.2,"it":"conversational","rp":"high","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"person","spr":"subject","dl":["verb"],"co":["are","were","have","can","will","should","need","want","all"],"st":["first person","plural","community","collective"],"cv":["inclusive use (speaker + others)","exclusive use (speaker's group)"],"su":["subject"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"say","ph":"/seɪ/","pos":"verb","gr":"predicate","rt":"say","fam":["said","saying","says","unsaid","hearsay"],"pl":"","tn":["say","says","said","saying"],"hi":"कहना","en":"to speak or express in words","ds":"To speak words or express something verbally.","dd":"'Say' is a common verb of speech meaning to utter words, express a thought, or state something. It is used in direct speech ('She said hello'), indirect speech ('He said that he was tired'), and many idiomatic expressions ('say the word', 'I say'). It differs from 'tell', which requires an object.","ex":"She always says what she truly thinks.","exh":"वह हमेशा वही कहती है जो वह सच में सोचती है।","syl":["say"],"syn":["speak","utter","state","declare","express","mention","tell","remark"],"ant":["listen","hear","be silent","keep quiet"],"rel":["tell","speak","talk","mention","express","declare","utter","state"],"dif":"basic","fr":27,"ew":0.1,"it":"conversational","rp":"high","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"general","spr":"verb","dl":["subject","object","clause"],"co":["I","he","she","they","we","you","what","that","nothing","something"],"st":["speech","communication","expression","utterance"],"cv":["direct speech use","indirect speech use","reporting use","idiomatic use"],"su":["predicate"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"her","ph":"/hɜːr/","pos":"pronoun","gr":"object","rt":"she","fam":["she","hers","herself"],"pl":"","tn":[],"hi":"उसे/उसकी (स्त्रीलिंग)","en":"object form or possessive of she","ds":"Used as the object of a verb or as a possessive referring to a female.","dd":"'Her' serves as the object pronoun for 'she' ('I saw her') and as the possessive determiner ('her book'). It is the feminine third-person singular and is one of the most common pronouns in English. The possessive pronoun form is 'hers'.","ex":"I gave her the book she wanted to read.","exh":"मैंने उसे वह किताब दी जो वह पढ़ना चाहती थी।","syl":["her"],"syn":["the woman","the girl","that person"],"ant":["him","his","them"],"rel":["she","hers","herself","woman","girl","female"],"dif":"basic","fr":28,"ew":0.0,"it":"identity","rp":"high","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"person","spr":"object","dl":["verb","preposition"],"co":["gave","told","asked","saw","met","help","love","know","left"],"st":["feminine","third person","singular","object","possessive"],"cv":["object pronoun use","possessive determiner use"],"su":["object","modifier"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"she","ph":"/ʃiː/","pos":"pronoun","gr":"subject","rt":"she","fam":["her","hers","herself"],"pl":"","tn":[],"hi":"वह (स्त्रीलिंग)","en":"third-person singular feminine pronoun","ds":"Refers to a female person or animal previously mentioned.","dd":"'She' is the third-person singular feminine subject pronoun. It refers to female persons, animals of known female gender, and in poetic or traditional usage to ships, countries, and nature. Its related forms are 'her' (object/possessive), 'hers' (possessive pronoun), and 'herself' (reflexive).","ex":"She passed all her exams with excellent grades.","exh":"उसने सभी परीक्षाएं बहुत अच्छे अंकों से पास कीं।","syl":["she"],"syn":["the woman","the girl","that lady"],"ant":["he","they"],"rel":["her","hers","herself","woman","girl","lady"],"dif":"basic","fr":29,"ew":0.0,"it":"identity","rp":"high","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"person","spr":"subject","dl":["verb"],"co":["is","was","has","will","can","said","went","did","told","knew"],"st":["feminine","third person","singular","reference"],"cv":["referring to female person","referring to female animal","metaphorical use for ships/countries"],"su":["subject"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"or","ph":"/ɔːr/","pos":"conjunction","gr":"connector","rt":"or","fam":[],"pl":"","tn":[],"hi":"या/अथवा","en":"presenting an alternative or choice","ds":"Used to connect alternatives or indicate a choice between things.","dd":"'Or' is a coordinating conjunction that presents alternatives ('tea or coffee'), expresses uncertainty ('is it Monday or Tuesday?'), and introduces a consequence ('hurry or you'll be late'). In logic it functions as the inclusive disjunction operator.","ex":"Would you like tea or coffee this morning?","exh":"क्या आप इस सुबह चाय या कॉफी लेना चाहेंगे?","syl":["or"],"syn":["otherwise","alternatively","either","else","nor"],"ant":["and","both","neither"],"rel":["and","nor","either","neither","else","alternatively"],"dif":"basic","fr":30,"ew":0.0,"it":"logical","rp":"high","cs":"any","dc":"question","td":"general","spr":"connector","dl":["clause","phrase","noun"],"co":["either","not","more","less","good","bad","right","wrong","better"],"st":["disjunction","alternative","choice","logic"],"cv":["alternative use","consequential use","logical disjunction"],"su":["connector"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"an","ph":"/æn/","pos":"article","gr":"determiner","rt":"a","fam":["a","the"],"pl":"","tn":[],"hi":"एक (स्वर से पहले)","en":"indefinite article used before vowel sounds","ds":"Used before singular nouns that begin with a vowel sound.","dd":"'An' is the form of the indefinite article 'a' used before words that begin with a vowel sound. The choice between 'a' and 'an' depends on pronunciation, not spelling: 'an hour' (silent h), 'a university' (consonant sound). It indicates a non-specific single item.","ex":"She is an excellent teacher with years of experience.","exh":"वह एक उत्कृष्ट शिक्षिका है जिसके पास वर्षों का अनुभव है।","syl":["an"],"syn":["a","one","some"],"ant":["the","no"],"rel":["a","the","one","some","any"],"dif":"basic","fr":31,"ew":0.0,"it":"relational","rp":"high","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"general","spr":"determiner","dl":["noun starting with vowel sound"],"co":["hour","idea","apple","egg","old","open","easy","honest","urgent"],"st":["indefiniteness","introduction","vowel sound"],"cv":["before vowel-sound noun","used in expressions","variant of 'a'"],"su":["determiner"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"will","ph":"/wɪl/","pos":"auxiliary verb","gr":"predicate","rt":"will","fam":["willing","willpower","willfully","willingness"],"pl":"","tn":["will","would"],"hi":"करेगा/होगा (भविष्य काल)","en":"modal auxiliary expressing future or willingness","ds":"Used to express future actions, predictions, promises, or willingness.","dd":"'Will' is a modal auxiliary verb with several core uses: expressing future time ('I will go'), making predictions ('It will rain'), expressing willingness or determination ('I will do it'), and making promises or offers. Its past/conditional form is 'would'.","ex":"She will finish the project before the deadline.","exh":"वह समय सीमा से पहले प्रोजेक्ट खत्म कर लेगी।","syl":["will"],"syn":["shall","would","going to","intend to","plan to"],"ant":["won't","refuse","cannot"],"rel":["would","shall","going to","might","may","could","should"],"dif":"basic","fr":32,"ew":0.1,"it":"action","rp":"high","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"general","spr":"auxiliary","dl":["subject","verb"],"co":["be","do","have","go","come","help","need","want","try","make"],"st":["future","prediction","willingness","promise","modal"],"cv":["future tense use","willingness use","prediction use","offer use"],"su":["auxiliary","predicate"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"my","ph":"/maɪ/","pos":"pronoun","gr":"modifier","rt":"I","fam":["I","me","mine","myself"],"pl":"","tn":[],"hi":"मेरा/मेरी/मेरे","en":"belonging to the speaker","ds":"Possessive determiner indicating something belongs to the speaker.","dd":"'My' is the first-person singular possessive determiner. It indicates that the following noun belongs to or is associated with the speaker. Its related forms are 'mine' (possessive pronoun) and 'myself' (reflexive). It is one of the most frequent possessive words in English.","ex":"My family always gathers for dinner on Sundays.","exh":"मेरा परिवार रविवार को हमेशा रात के खाने के लिए इकट्ठा होता है।","syl":["my"],"syn":["mine","belonging to me","of mine"],"ant":["your","his","her","their","our"],"rel":["mine","myself","I","me","our","your"],"dif":"basic","fr":33,"ew":0.2,"it":"identity","rp":"high","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"person","spr":"modifier","dl":["noun"],"co":["name","friend","family","work","life","home","heart","mind","way"],"st":["possession","first person","singular","identity"],"cv":["determiner use","expressing personal relationship"],"su":["modifier","determiner"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"one","ph":"/wʌn/","pos":"numeral","gr":"modifier","rt":"one","fam":["once","only","alone","lone"],"pl":"","tn":[],"hi":"एक","en":"the number 1; a single person or thing","ds":"The number 1; also used as a pronoun meaning a person in general.","dd":"'One' is the cardinal number 1. It is used to count single items, refer to a particular person or thing ('one of them'), and as a generic pronoun in formal or impersonal statements ('one should be careful'). It is also used idiomatically in many expressions.","ex":"One good idea can change everything completely.","exh":"एक अच्छा विचार सब कुछ पूरी तरह बदल सकता है।","syl":["one"],"syn":["single","sole","individual","a","an"],"ant":["many","multiple","several","all"],"rel":["two","three","single","alone","only","first"],"dif":"basic","fr":34,"ew":0.0,"it":"informational","rp":"high","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"general","spr":"modifier","dl":["noun"],"co":["of","the","another","that","this","more","who","only","two","good"],"st":["number","singularity","individuality","quantity"],"cv":["numeral use","generic pronoun use","indefinite reference"],"su":["modifier","subject"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"all","ph":"/ɔːl/","pos":"determiner","gr":"modifier","rt":"all","fam":["altogether","already","always","almost","also"],"pl":"","tn":[],"hi":"सब/सभी/पूरा","en":"the whole amount, quantity, or extent","ds":"Refers to the whole of a group, quantity, or extent; every member included.","dd":"'All' is a predeterminer, determiner, and pronoun meaning the complete or whole amount of something. It can precede the, my, their etc. ('all the students'), function as a standalone pronoun ('all is well'), or precede adjectives as an intensifier ('all alone'). It emphasizes totality.","ex":"All students must attend the final examination.","exh":"सभी छात्रों को अंतिम परीक्षा में उपस्थित होना होगा।","syl":["all"],"syn":["every","each","whole","entire","complete","total","full"],"ant":["none","no","neither","some","partial"],"rel":["every","each","whole","entire","both","total","universal"],"dif":"basic","fr":35,"ew":0.0,"it":"informational","rp":"high","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"general","spr":"modifier","dl":["noun","pronoun"],"co":["the","of","my","your","our","their","this","that","day","year"],"st":["totality","universality","completeness"],"cv":["determiner use","pronoun use","adverb use (intensifier)"],"su":["modifier","determiner"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"would","ph":"/wʊd/","pos":"auxiliary verb","gr":"predicate","rt":"will","fam":["will","willing","willingness"],"pl":"","tn":[],"hi":"करेगा/चाहेगा (शर्त/विनम्रता)","en":"past tense of will; used for conditions and polite requests","ds":"Used for polite requests, hypothetical situations, or past habits.","dd":"'Would' is the past tense of 'will' and serves several functions: expressing conditional statements ('I would help if I could'), making polite requests ('Would you pass the salt?'), describing past habits ('We would visit every summer'), and expressing preference ('I would rather stay').","ex":"Would you like to join us for dinner tonight?","exh":"क्या आप आज रात हमारे साथ रात के खाने पर आना चाहेंगे?","syl":["would"],"syn":["will","should","might","could","shall","intend to"],"ant":["won't","wouldn't","refuse"],"rel":["will","should","could","might","shall","used to"],"dif":"basic","fr":36,"ew":0.1,"it":"conversational","rp":"high","cs":"any","dc":"question","td":"general","spr":"auxiliary","dl":["subject","verb"],"co":["you","I","he","she","we","they","like","love","be","have","do","go"],"st":["conditional","politeness","hypothetical","past habit","modal"],"cv":["conditional use","polite request","past habit use","hypothetical use"],"su":["auxiliary","predicate"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"there","ph":"/ðɛr/","pos":"adverb","gr":"modifier","rt":"there","fam":["therefore","thereafter","thereabout","therein"],"pl":"","tn":[],"hi":"वहाँ/उस जगह","en":"in, at, or to that place; also existential marker","ds":"Refers to a place or location; also used to introduce a sentence.","dd":"'There' functions as an adverb of place ('put it there'), a demonstrative pointing to something ('there it is'), and as the dummy subject in existential sentences ('There is a problem'). Its existential use is extremely common in English to introduce new information.","ex":"There is a beautiful park near our house.","exh":"हमारे घर के पास एक सुंदर पार्क है।","syl":["there"],"syn":["in that place","over there","yonder","at that point"],"ant":["here","this place","nearby"],"rel":["here","yonder","where","somewhere","nearby","that place"],"dif":"basic","fr":37,"ew":0.0,"it":"relational","rp":"high","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"place","spr":"modifier","dl":["verb","noun"],"co":["is","are","was","were","will be","have been","might be","a","no","some"],"st":["place","location","existential","demonstrative"],"cv":["place adverb use","existential subject use","demonstrative use"],"su":["modifier","dummy subject"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"their","ph":"/ðɛr/","pos":"pronoun","gr":"modifier","rt":"they","fam":["they","them","theirs","themselves"],"pl":"","tn":[],"hi":"उनका/उनकी","en":"possessive form of they","ds":"Belonging to or associated with the people or things mentioned.","dd":"'Their' is the third-person plural possessive determiner, indicating that something belongs to a group. In modern usage it is also used as a singular gender-neutral possessive ('everyone should do their best'). Its related pronoun form is 'theirs'.","ex":"Their team won the national championship last year.","exh":"उनकी टीम ने पिछले साल राष्ट्रीय चैम्पियनशिप जीती।","syl":["their"],"syn":["belonging to them","of them"],"ant":["my","your","his","her","our"],"rel":["they","them","theirs","themselves","our","your"],"dif":"basic","fr":38,"ew":0.0,"it":"relational","rp":"high","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"general","spr":"modifier","dl":["noun"],"co":["own","home","family","children","work","life","names","team"],"st":["possession","plural","third person","gender-neutral"],"cv":["plural possessive use","gender-neutral singular use"],"su":["modifier","determiner"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"what","ph":"/wɒt/","pos":"pronoun","gr":"subject","rt":"what","fam":[],"pl":"","tn":[],"hi":"क्या","en":"asking about or referring to something unknown","ds":"Used to ask questions about things or introduce indirect questions.","dd":"'What' is an interrogative pronoun and determiner used to ask about the identity or nature of things ('What is your name?'), to introduce indirect questions ('I don't know what happened'), and in exclamations ('What a beautiful day!'). It is one of the core question words in English.","ex":"What are you planning to do this weekend?","exh":"इस सप्ताहांत आप क्या करने की योजना बना रहे हैं?","syl":["what"],"syn":["which thing","which","that which"],"ant":[],"rel":["which","where","who","why","when","how","whatever"],"dif":"basic","fr":39,"ew":0.1,"it":"interrogative","rp":"high","cs":"clarification","dc":"question","td":"general","spr":"subject","dl":["verb","noun"],"co":["is","are","was","were","do","does","did","happened","means","kind"],"st":["question","interrogative","inquiry","thing-reference"],"cv":["question word use","indirect question use","exclamation use"],"su":["subject","object","determiner"],"wuc":["daily conversation","formal","informal","interrogative"]},
    {"w":"so","ph":"/soʊ/","pos":"adverb","gr":"connector","rt":"so","fam":[],"pl":"","tn":[],"hi":"इसलिए/तो/इतना","en":"to a great degree; therefore; introducing result","ds":"Used to show degree, result, or to continue a conversation.","dd":"'So' has multiple functions: as an adverb of degree ('so beautiful'), as a conjunction of result ('she worked hard, so she passed'), as an adverb meaning 'also' ('I do so'), and as an informal discourse marker ('So, what happened?'). It is extremely versatile in spoken English.","ex":"The weather was so cold that we stayed inside.","exh":"मौसम इतना ठंडा था कि हम घर के अंदर रहे।","syl":["so"],"syn":["therefore","thus","hence","consequently","very","extremely","as well"],"ant":["but","however","still"],"rel":["therefore","thus","hence","consequently","also","very","too","extremely"],"dif":"basic","fr":40,"ew":0.0,"it":"logical","rp":"high","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"general","spr":"connector","dl":["adjective","adverb","clause"],"co":["much","many","long","far","well","good","that","I","we","what"],"st":["degree","result","consequence","discourse"],"cv":["degree use","conjunction of result","discourse marker use","anaphoric use"],"su":["connector","modifier"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"up","ph":"/ʌp/","pos":"adverb","gr":"modifier","rt":"up","fam":["upon","upward","upset","upgrade","upcoming","uphold"],"pl":"","tn":[],"hi":"ऊपर/उठाना","en":"toward a higher position or level","ds":"Moving or directed toward a higher position; increasing or rising.","dd":"'Up' primarily indicates movement to a higher position or level. As an adverb it modifies verbs ('stand up', 'look up'). As a preposition it indicates movement along a surface upward ('up the stairs'). It is also used in phrasal verbs with a wide range of meanings ('give up', 'make up', 'pick up').","ex":"She looked up at the stars in the clear sky.","exh":"उसने साफ आसमान में तारों की ओर ऊपर देखा।","syl":["up"],"syn":["upward","higher","above","ascending","overhead"],"ant":["down","below","lower","descending"],"rel":["above","over","higher","overhead","upward","rise"],"dif":"basic","fr":41,"ew":0.0,"it":"descriptive","rp":"high","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"general","spr":"modifier","dl":["verb","noun"],"co":["stand","get","look","pick","give","make","come","go","wake","set"],"st":["direction","elevation","increase","completion"],"cv":["directional use","intensifier use","phrasal verb use"],"su":["modifier","preposition"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","informal","command"]},
    {"w":"out","ph":"/aʊt/","pos":"adverb","gr":"modifier","rt":"out","fam":["outside","outer","outlet","output","outcome","outward","outreach"],"pl":"","tn":[],"hi":"बाहर","en":"away from the inside or center","ds":"Away from a place, position, or state; away from the interior.","dd":"'Out' indicates movement away from inside to outside, visibility ('find out', 'come out'), removal ('take out'), and completion ('run out', 'work out'). It forms many phrasal verbs with very different meanings. As an adjective it means 'not in' or 'not available'.","ex":"She walked out of the office without saying a word.","exh":"वह बिना कुछ कहे कार्यालय से बाहर चली गई।","syl":["out"],"syn":["outside","outward","away","beyond","exterior","forth"],"ant":["in","inside","within","into","inward"],"rel":["outside","away","forth","beyond","outward","exterior"],"dif":"basic","fr":42,"ew":0.0,"it":"descriptive","rp":"high","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"general","spr":"modifier","dl":["verb","noun"],"co":["go","come","find","take","run","get","work","put","reach","point"],"st":["direction","exclusion","exterior","completion"],"cv":["directional use","phrasal verb use","exclusion use"],"su":["modifier","preposition"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","informal"]},
    {"w":"if","ph":"/ɪf/","pos":"conjunction","gr":"connector","rt":"if","fam":[],"pl":"","tn":[],"hi":"अगर/यदि/यदि","en":"introducing a condition or hypothesis","ds":"Used to introduce a conditional clause or a hypothetical situation.","dd":"'If' is a subordinating conjunction that introduces conditional clauses. It is used in real conditions ('If it rains, take an umbrella'), hypothetical conditions ('If I were rich, I would travel'), indirect questions ('Ask if she is coming'), and exclamations ('If only I had known!'). It is fundamental to conditional logic in English.","ex":"If you study hard, you will pass the exam.","exh":"अगर आप कड़ी मेहनत करते हैं, तो आप परीक्षा पास करेंगे।","syl":["if"],"syn":["provided that","supposing","assuming","in case","whether","should","when"],"ant":["unless","despite","regardless"],"rel":["unless","when","whether","provided","suppose","assume","condition"],"dif":"basic","fr":43,"ew":0.0,"it":"logical","rp":"high","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"general","spr":"connector","dl":["clause","verb"],"co":["you","I","he","she","we","they","not","want","need","have","can","could"],"st":["condition","hypothesis","logic","contingency"],"cv":["real condition use","hypothetical use","indirect question use","wish use"],"su":["connector"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"about","ph":"/əˈbaʊt/","pos":"preposition","gr":"connector","rt":"about","fam":[],"pl":"","tn":[],"hi":"के बारे में/लगभग","en":"on the subject of; approximately","ds":"Relating to a topic or roughly at a quantity.","dd":"'About' functions as a preposition ('talk about the problem'), an adverb meaning approximately ('about ten people'), and in expressions of concern ('what about me?'). It is commonly used to indicate the subject matter of a conversation, book, or thought.","ex":"The documentary is about climate change and its effects.","exh":"यह वृत्तचित्र जलवायु परिवर्तन और उसके प्रभावों के बारे में है।","syl":["a","bout"],"syn":["concerning","regarding","on the subject of","approximately","around","roughly"],"ant":[],"rel":["concerning","regarding","on","around","approximately","roughly","near"],"dif":"basic","fr":44,"ew":0.0,"it":"informational","rp":"high","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"general","spr":"preposition","dl":["noun","verb","clause"],"co":["talk","think","know","care","worry","ask","tell","hear","wonder","write"],"st":["topic","approximation","concern"],"cv":["subject-matter use","approximation use","movement use ('about to')"],"su":["preposition","connector"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"who","ph":"/huː/","pos":"pronoun","gr":"subject","rt":"who","fam":["whom","whose","whoever","whosoever"],"pl":"","tn":[],"hi":"कौन/जो (व्यक्ति)","en":"interrogative or relative pronoun referring to a person","ds":"Used to ask which person or to introduce a clause about a person.","dd":"'Who' is an interrogative pronoun used in questions about the identity of a person ('Who is calling?'), and a relative pronoun introducing relative clauses ('the person who helped me'). Its object form is 'whom' (formal), its possessive is 'whose', and its inclusive form is 'whoever'.","ex":"Who is the person responsible for this project?","exh":"इस परियोजना के लिए जिम्मेदार व्यक्ति कौन है?","syl":["who"],"syn":["which person","what person","whoever"],"ant":[],"rel":["whom","whose","whoever","which","what","where","when","person"],"dif":"basic","fr":45,"ew":0.0,"it":"interrogative","rp":"high","cs":"clarification","dc":"question","td":"person","spr":"subject","dl":["verb"],"co":["is","was","are","did","can","would","said","told","knows","needs"],"st":["person reference","question","relative clause","identity"],"cv":["interrogative use","relative pronoun use","indirect question use"],"su":["subject","object"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"get","ph":"/ɡɛt/","pos":"verb","gr":"predicate","rt":"get","fam":["got","gotten","getting","forget","beget"],"pl":"","tn":["get","gets","got","gotten","getting"],"hi":"प्राप्त करना/पाना/बनना","en":"to receive, obtain, or become","ds":"To receive, obtain, or become something; highly versatile verb.","dd":"'Get' is one of the most versatile verbs in English. It expresses receiving ('get a gift'), obtaining ('get help'), movement ('get home'), becoming ('get angry'), causation ('get someone to do something'), and is used in over 100 phrasal verbs. It is especially common in informal English.","ex":"She managed to get tickets for the concert.","exh":"वह संगीत समारोह के लिए टिकट प्राप्त करने में सफल रही।","syl":["get"],"syn":["obtain","receive","acquire","earn","gain","fetch","become","grow"],"ant":["give","lose","miss","avoid"],"rel":["receive","obtain","acquire","gain","fetch","take","find","become"],"dif":"basic","fr":46,"ew":0.0,"it":"action","rp":"high","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"action","spr":"verb","dl":["subject","object"],"co":["up","out","to","ready","better","worse","started","going","away","there"],"st":["acquisition","receipt","movement","change of state"],"cv":["obtain use","become use","movement use","causative use","phrasal verb use"],"su":["predicate"],"wuc":["daily conversation","informal","writing"]},
    {"w":"which","ph":"/wɪtʃ/","pos":"pronoun","gr":"subject","rt":"which","fam":["whichever"],"pl":"","tn":[],"hi":"कौन सा/जो","en":"asking which one or introducing a relative clause","ds":"Used to identify a specific item from a group or introduce a relative clause.","dd":"'Which' is both an interrogative pronoun/determiner ('Which road leads to the city?') and a relative pronoun ('the car which I bought'). As an interrogative it implies choosing between known options, unlike 'what' which is more open-ended. As a relative pronoun it typically refers to things rather than people.","ex":"Which of these books would you recommend reading first?","exh":"इनमें से कौन सी किताब आप पहले पढ़ने की सिफारिश करेंगे?","syl":["which"],"syn":["what","that","whichever"],"ant":[],"rel":["what","that","who","whom","whichever","any","either"],"dif":"basic","fr":47,"ew":0.0,"it":"interrogative","rp":"high","cs":"clarification","dc":"question","td":"general","spr":"subject","dl":["noun","verb"],"co":["one","of","is","was","the","means","best","first","way","option"],"st":["selection","question","relative","identification"],"cv":["interrogative use","relative pronoun use (non-restrictive)","relative pronoun use (restrictive)"],"su":["subject","object","determiner"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"go","ph":"/ɡoʊ/","pos":"verb","gr":"predicate","rt":"go","fam":["goes","went","gone","going","undergo","outgo","ago"],"pl":"","tn":["go","goes","went","gone","going"],"hi":"जाना","en":"to move from one place to another; to proceed","ds":"To move, travel, or proceed from one place to another.","dd":"'Go' is a highly common verb expressing movement away from a point, travel to a destination, and in many phrasal verbs and expressions. It also functions as a linking verb ('things go wrong') and as a future construction ('going to'). Its irregular past tense 'went' is noteworthy.","ex":"Let's go to the beach this Saturday afternoon.","exh":"इस शनिवार दोपहर समुद्र तट पर चलते हैं।","syl":["go"],"syn":["proceed","travel","move","depart","leave","head","journey"],"ant":["stay","stop","remain","arrive","come"],"rel":["come","move","travel","leave","depart","proceed","head"],"dif":"basic","fr":48,"ew":0.0,"it":"action","rp":"high","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"action","spr":"verb","dl":["subject","destination"],"co":["out","back","home","there","ahead","away","up","on","off","with"],"st":["movement","travel","departure","direction"],"cv":["movement use","future construction ('going to')","become use","phrasal verb use"],"su":["predicate"],"wuc":["daily conversation","informal","writing"]},
    {"w":"me","ph":"/miː/","pos":"pronoun","gr":"object","rt":"I","fam":["I","my","mine","myself"],"pl":"","tn":[],"hi":"मुझे/मुझको","en":"object form of I; referring to the speaker","ds":"Used as the object of a verb or preposition to refer to the speaker.","dd":"'Me' is the first-person singular object pronoun. It is used as the direct object ('She helped me'), indirect object ('Give me a chance'), object of a preposition ('for me'), and in informal constructions as a subject equivalent ('It's me'). As a reflexive, 'myself' is used.","ex":"Please give me a moment to think carefully.","exh":"कृपया मुझे सोचने के लिए एक पल दें।","syl":["me"],"syn":["I","myself"],"ant":["you","him","her","them"],"rel":["I","my","mine","myself","us"],"dif":"basic","fr":49,"ew":0.2,"it":"identity","rp":"high","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"person","spr":"object","dl":["verb","preposition"],"co":["tell","give","help","let","show","ask","call","know","see","find"],"st":["first person","object","singular","identity"],"cv":["direct object use","indirect object use","object of preposition use"],"su":["object"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","informal","formal"]},
    {"w":"when","ph":"/wɛn/","pos":"adverb","gr":"connector","rt":"when","fam":["whenever","then"],"pl":"","tn":[],"hi":"कब/जब","en":"at what time; at the time that","ds":"Used to ask about or state the time something happens.","dd":"'When' is an interrogative adverb ('When did you arrive?'), a relative adverb in relative clauses ('the day when we met'), and a subordinating conjunction in time clauses ('When she arrived, we started'). It is one of the core question words in English.","ex":"When will you be able to come to the party?","exh":"आप पार्टी में कब आ पाएंगे?","syl":["when"],"syn":["at what time","at the moment that","once","as soon as","at the time"],"ant":[],"rel":["where","why","how","once","while","as","after","before"],"dif":"basic","fr":50,"ew":0.0,"it":"interrogative","rp":"high","cs":"clarification","dc":"question","td":"time","spr":"connector","dl":["verb","clause"],"co":["did","do","does","will","was","were","can","should","have","I"],"st":["time","question","temporal clause"],"cv":["interrogative use","relative adverb use","subordinating conjunction use"],"su":["connector","modifier"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"make","ph":"/meɪk/","pos":"verb","gr":"predicate","rt":"make","fam":["made","making","makes","maker","remake","handmade"],"pl":"","tn":["make","makes","made","making"],"hi":"बनाना/करना","en":"to create, produce, or cause something","ds":"To create, produce, or cause something to happen.","dd":"'Make' is one of the most common verbs in English with many meanings: to create ('make a cake'), to cause ('make someone happy'), to earn ('make money'), and to perform ('make a decision'). It contrasts with 'do' — generally 'make' is used for creating or producing.","ex":"She makes delicious food for her family every day.","exh":"वह हर रोज़ अपने परिवार के लिए स्वादिष्ट खाना बनाती है।","syl":["make"],"syn":["create","produce","build","form","construct","craft","generate","prepare"],"ant":["destroy","break","demolish","ruin","undo"],"rel":["create","build","produce","form","construct","craft","design","shape"],"dif":"basic","fr":51,"ew":0.0,"it":"action","rp":"high","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"action","spr":"verb","dl":["subject","object"],"co":["sure","it","up","out","clear","good","better","sense","plan","decision"],"st":["creation","production","causation","performance"],"cv":["creation use","causation use","earning use","performance use"],"su":["predicate"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"can","ph":"/kæn/","pos":"auxiliary verb","gr":"predicate","rt":"can","fam":["cannot","can't","could"],"pl":"","tn":["can","could"],"hi":"सकता/सकती है (क्षमता)","en":"expressing ability or possibility","ds":"Used to express ability, permission, or possibility.","dd":"'Can' is a modal auxiliary verb expressing ability ('I can swim'), possibility ('That can happen'), permission in informal contexts ('Can I go?'), and general capacity. Its past tense is 'could'. It contrasts with 'may' which is more formal for permission.","ex":"She can speak three languages very fluently.","exh":"वह बहुत धाराप्रवाह तीन भाषाएं बोल सकती है।","syl":["can"],"syn":["be able to","could","may","might","be capable of"],"ant":["cannot","can't","be unable to"],"rel":["could","may","might","shall","able","capable","manage"],"dif":"basic","fr":52,"ew":0.0,"it":"informational","rp":"high","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"general","spr":"auxiliary","dl":["subject","verb"],"co":["you","I","we","they","he","she","do","see","be","go","find","help"],"st":["ability","possibility","permission","capacity"],"cv":["ability use","possibility use","permission use"],"su":["auxiliary","predicate"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"like","ph":"/laɪk/","pos":"verb","gr":"predicate","rt":"like","fam":["liked","liking","likes","alike","unlike","dislike","likely"],"pl":"","tn":["like","likes","liked","liking"],"hi":"पसंद करना/जैसा","en":"to find something pleasant; similar to something","ds":"To find something pleasant or enjoyable; also used for comparison.","dd":"'Like' as a verb expresses preference or enjoyment ('I like music'). As a preposition or conjunction it means 'similar to' ('runs like the wind'). In informal speech it serves as a discourse marker and quotative ('She was like, \'Wow\''). It is extremely common in everyday English.","ex":"She likes reading novels and listening to classical music.","exh":"वह उपन्यास पढ़ना और शास्त्रीय संगीत सुनना पसंद करती है।","syl":["like"],"syn":["enjoy","love","appreciate","admire","prefer","fancy","similar to","such as"],"ant":["dislike","hate","loathe","despise"],"rel":["love","enjoy","prefer","appreciate","similar","as","such as"],"dif":"basic","fr":53,"ew":0.5,"it":"emotional","rp":"high","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"general","spr":"verb","dl":["subject","object"],"co":["I","you","she","he","they","we","very much","to","music","food","the"],"st":["preference","enjoyment","similarity","comparison"],"cv":["verb of preference","preposition of comparison","discourse marker use"],"su":["predicate"],"wuc":["daily conversation","informal","formal","writing"]},
    {"w":"time","ph":"/taɪm/","pos":"noun","gr":"subject","rt":"time","fam":["times","timer","timely","overtime","daytime","lifetime","sometime","timetable"],"pl":"times","tn":[],"hi":"समय/वक्त","en":"the indefinite continued progress of events; a moment or period","ds":"The progress of events from past to future; a specific point or period.","dd":"'Time' refers to the continuous passing of events from the past through the present to the future. As a countable noun it refers to specific occasions ('many times'). It is one of the most conceptually important words in human language and appears in hundreds of expressions and compound words.","ex":"Time is the most valuable resource we have.","exh":"समय हमारे पास सबसे मूल्यवान संसाधन है।","syl":["time"],"syn":["period","moment","duration","era","occasion","age","hour","day"],"ant":[],"rel":["moment","period","hour","day","year","age","era","season","clock"],"dif":"basic","fr":54,"ew":0.1,"it":"informational","rp":"high","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"time","spr":"subject","dl":["verb","adjective","preposition"],"co":["all","first","long","short","spend","take","good","same","last","next"],"st":["time","duration","sequence","measurement","resource"],"cv":["abstract use","countable use","in phrases ('on time','in time')"],"su":["subject","object"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"no","ph":"/noʊ/","pos":"adverb","gr":"modifier","rt":"no","fam":["not","none","nothing","nobody","nowhere","nor","never"],"pl":"","tn":[],"hi":"नहीं/न","en":"used to deny, refuse, or express the negative","ds":"Used to express denial, disagreement, or the absence of something.","dd":"'No' functions as an adverb of negation ('No, I don't agree'), a determiner meaning 'not any' ('No time left'), and a noun in some constructions ('Give me a yes or a no'). It is one of the most fundamental response words in English.","ex":"No, I do not think that is the right answer.","exh":"नहीं, मुझे नहीं लगता कि यह सही उत्तर है।","syl":["no"],"syn":["not","nope","nay","negative","none","neither","never"],"ant":["yes","okay","sure","agreed","certainly","absolutely"],"rel":["not","never","none","nothing","nobody","nor","neither"],"dif":"basic","fr":55,"ew":0.2,"it":"logical","rp":"high","cs":"any","dc":"response","td":"general","spr":"modifier","dl":["verb","noun","clause"],"co":["one","thing","way","reason","longer","more","doubt","idea","other"],"st":["negation","refusal","denial","absence"],"cv":["response use","determiner use","noun use"],"su":["modifier","determiner"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"just","ph":"/dʒʌst/","pos":"adverb","gr":"modifier","rt":"just","fam":["justice","justify","unjust","justly","adjustment"],"pl":"","tn":[],"hi":"बस/सिर्फ/अभी-अभी","en":"exactly; only; very recently","ds":"Used to mean exactly, only, or that something happened very recently.","dd":"'Just' has several common uses: meaning 'exactly' ('just right'), 'only' ('just a moment'), 'very recently' ('I just arrived'), and as an intensifier in informal speech ('I just love it'). It can also express fairness as an adjective ('a just decision') from the same Latin root as 'justice'.","ex":"She just finished writing the report a moment ago.","exh":"उसने बस अभी कुछ देर पहले रिपोर्ट लिखना खत्म किया।","syl":["just"],"syn":["only","merely","simply","exactly","precisely","barely","recently","right"],"ant":["unjustly","far from","not nearly","excessively"],"rel":["only","merely","simply","exactly","barely","fair","right","recently"],"dif":"basic","fr":56,"ew":0.0,"it":"descriptive","rp":"high","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"general","spr":"modifier","dl":["verb","adjective","adverb"],"co":["now","yet","about","as","the","a","one","right","want","need","do"],"st":["precision","recency","limitation","fairness"],"cv":["recent past use","limitation use","intensifier use","adjective (fair)"],"su":["modifier"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","informal","formal"]},
    {"w":"him","ph":"/hɪm/","pos":"pronoun","gr":"object","rt":"he","fam":["he","his","himself"],"pl":"","tn":[],"hi":"उसे/उसको (पुल्लिंग)","en":"object form of he","ds":"Used as the object of a verb or preposition referring to a male.","dd":"'Him' is the third-person singular masculine object pronoun. It is used as the direct object ('I saw him'), indirect object ('I gave him the book'), and object of a preposition ('for him'). Its subject form is 'he' and its possessive is 'his'.","ex":"She told him the truth about what had happened.","exh":"उसने उसे बताया कि क्या हुआ था।","syl":["him"],"syn":["that man","the man","the boy"],"ant":["her","them","me"],"rel":["he","his","himself","man","person","boy"],"dif":"basic","fr":57,"ew":0.0,"it":"identity","rp":"high","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"person","spr":"object","dl":["verb","preposition"],"co":["told","gave","saw","met","helped","asked","called","knew","liked","needed"],"st":["masculine","third person","singular","object"],"cv":["direct object use","indirect object use","object of preposition"],"su":["object"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"know","ph":"/noʊ/","pos":"verb","gr":"predicate","rt":"know","fam":["known","knowing","knows","knew","unknown","knowledge","acknowledge"],"pl":"","tn":["know","knows","knew","known","knowing"],"hi":"जानना","en":"to have information or awareness about something","ds":"To have knowledge, awareness, or understanding of something.","dd":"'Know' means to have information ('I know the answer'), be acquainted with ('I know her'), recognize ('I know that smell'), and understand ('I know what you mean'). It is a stative verb, so it is not normally used in progressive tenses. Its irregular past tense is 'knew'.","ex":"She knows exactly how to solve this problem.","exh":"वह जानती है कि इस समस्या को कैसे हल करना है।","syl":["know"],"syn":["understand","realize","recognize","be aware of","be familiar with","comprehend"],"ant":["ignore","misunderstand","overlook","not know"],"rel":["understand","realize","learn","recognize","remember","discover","find out"],"dif":"basic","fr":58,"ew":0.1,"it":"informational","rp":"high","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"general","spr":"verb","dl":["subject","object","clause"],"co":["I","you","we","they","he","she","that","what","how","why","where","who"],"st":["knowledge","awareness","familiarity","understanding"],"cv":["factual knowledge use","acquaintance use","recognition use","understanding use"],"su":["predicate"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"take","ph":"/teɪk/","pos":"verb","gr":"predicate","rt":"take","fam":["takes","took","taken","taking","retake","intake","undertake","mistake"],"pl":"","tn":["take","takes","took","taken","taking"],"hi":"लेना/ले जाना","en":"to hold, carry, or move something; to require","ds":"To grasp and carry something away; to require time or effort.","dd":"'Take' is a highly versatile verb meaning to grasp ('take a pen'), carry away ('take it home'), require ('it takes time'), accept ('take advice'), travel by ('take the bus'), and perform ('take a photo'). It forms over 100 phrasal verbs and idioms in English.","ex":"It takes a lot of courage to admit your mistakes.","exh":"अपनी गलतियाँ स्वीकार करने में बहुत साहस चाहिए।","syl":["take"],"syn":["grab","grasp","carry","bring","require","need","accept","seize","get"],"ant":["give","return","release","surrender","leave"],"rel":["bring","carry","hold","get","have","accept","use","require","need"],"dif":"basic","fr":59,"ew":0.0,"it":"action","rp":"high","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"action","spr":"verb","dl":["subject","object"],"co":["time","care","place","part","long","away","back","out","over","on"],"st":["acquisition","movement","requirement","performance"],"cv":["carry use","require use","accept use","phrasal verb use"],"su":["predicate"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"people","ph":"/ˈpiːpəl/","pos":"noun","gr":"subject","rt":"person","fam":["person","persons","peoples","populate","population","populous"],"pl":"people","tn":[],"hi":"लोग/जनता","en":"human beings in general; a group of persons","ds":"Human beings collectively; a group of men, women, and children.","dd":"'People' is the plural of 'person' in most contexts and refers to human beings in general ('people are kind') or a specific group ('the people of France'). As a noun it can be preceded by numbers ('five people') and quantifiers. The form 'peoples' refers to distinct ethnic groups.","ex":"People from all over the world attended the conference.","exh":"दुनिया भर के लोगों ने सम्मेलन में भाग लिया।","syl":["peo","ple"],"syn":["persons","humans","individuals","folk","public","citizens","population"],"ant":[],"rel":["person","human","individual","crowd","population","society","community"],"dif":"basic","fr":60,"ew":0.2,"it":"informational","rp":"high","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"person","spr":"subject","dl":["verb","adjective"],"co":["many","all","some","most","young","old","rich","poor","other","different"],"st":["humanity","group","community","social"],"cv":["generic reference","specific group reference","countable use"],"su":["subject","object"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"into","ph":"/ˈɪntuː/","pos":"preposition","gr":"connector","rt":"in","fam":["in","inside","internal","within"],"pl":"","tn":[],"hi":"के अंदर/में (गति)","en":"to the inside of; in the direction of","ds":"Indicates movement to the interior of something or entry into a state.","dd":"'Into' indicates movement from outside to inside ('walked into the room'), change of state ('turned into a butterfly'), contact ('bumped into him'), or a point of entry. It always implies motion or change, unlike 'in' which indicates static position.","ex":"She walked into the room and turned on the light.","exh":"वह कमरे में आई और लाइट जलाई।","syl":["in","to"],"syn":["inside","within","toward","through","in"],"ant":["out of","from","away from"],"rel":["in","within","inside","toward","through","onto"],"dif":"basic","fr":61,"ew":0.0,"it":"relational","rp":"high","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"general","spr":"preposition","dl":["noun","verb of motion"],"co":["walked","ran","jumped","went","fell","looked","turned","changed","came"],"st":["movement","entry","change of state","direction"],"cv":["physical movement use","metaphorical entry use","change of state use"],"su":["preposition","connector"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"year","ph":"/jɪr/","pos":"noun","gr":"subject","rt":"year","fam":["yearly","years","yearlong","yearbook"],"pl":"years","tn":[],"hi":"वर्ष/साल","en":"a period of 12 months","ds":"A period of 365 or 366 days; twelve calendar months.","dd":"'Year' refers to the period of approximately 365 days it takes Earth to orbit the Sun, or any 12-month period. It is used to measure duration ('for five years'), denote periods in time ('the year 2000'), and in many temporal expressions. The plural 'years' indicates extended duration.","ex":"She has been working at the same company for ten years.","exh":"वह दस सालों से एक ही कंपनी में काम कर रही है।","syl":["year"],"syn":["annual period","twelve months","annum","calendar year"],"ant":[],"rel":["month","week","day","decade","century","time","annual","period"],"dif":"basic","fr":62,"ew":0.0,"it":"informational","rp":"high","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"time","spr":"subject","dl":["verb","adjective","numeral"],"co":["this","last","next","every","past","new","old","for","in","each"],"st":["time","duration","calendar","annual"],"cv":["calendar year use","duration use","era use"],"su":["subject","object"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"your","ph":"/jʊr/","pos":"pronoun","gr":"modifier","rt":"you","fam":["you","yours","yourself","yourselves"],"pl":"","tn":[],"hi":"तुम्हारा/आपका","en":"belonging to or associated with the person being spoken to","ds":"Possessive determiner referring to what belongs to the person being addressed.","dd":"'Your' is the second-person possessive determiner, indicating that something belongs to or is associated with the person being spoken to. It works for both singular and plural 'you'. The corresponding possessive pronoun is 'yours' and reflexive is 'yourself/yourselves'.","ex":"Your dedication and hard work will bring great results.","exh":"आपकी लगन और कड़ी मेहनत अच्छे परिणाम लाएगी।","syl":["your"],"syn":["belonging to you","of yours"],"ant":["my","his","her","their","our"],"rel":["yours","yourself","you","our","my","their"],"dif":"basic","fr":63,"ew":0.1,"it":"identity","rp":"high","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"person","spr":"modifier","dl":["noun"],"co":["name","work","life","family","home","friend","time","way","own","right"],"st":["possession","second person","address"],"cv":["determiner use","generic address use"],"su":["modifier","determiner"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"good","ph":"/ɡʊd/","pos":"adjective","gr":"modifier","rt":"good","fam":["better","best","goodness","goods","goodwill","goody"],"pl":"","tn":[],"hi":"अच्छा/भला","en":"of a favorable quality or character","ds":"Of a positive quality; right, suitable, or beneficial.","dd":"'Good' is one of the most common adjectives in English, expressing positive quality ('good food'), moral virtue ('a good person'), skill ('good at math'), benefit ('good for you'), and used as an exclamation ('Good!'). Its comparative is 'better' and superlative is 'best', both irregular.","ex":"She gave a very good performance in the school play.","exh":"उसने स्कूल के नाटक में बहुत अच्छा प्रदर्शन किया।","syl":["good"],"syn":["great","excellent","fine","wonderful","superb","positive","beneficial","kind"],"ant":["bad","poor","terrible","awful","evil","wicked","inferior"],"rel":["great","fine","excellent","better","best","right","nice","wonderful"],"dif":"basic","fr":64,"ew":0.4,"it":"descriptive","rp":"high","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"general","spr":"modifier","dl":["noun","verb"],"co":["very","so","really","quite","pretty","bad","better","more","always"],"st":["quality","virtue","benefit","approval"],"cv":["quality adjective","moral adjective","skill adjective","exclamation use"],"su":["modifier"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"some","ph":"/sʌm/","pos":"determiner","gr":"modifier","rt":"some","fam":["something","someone","somewhere","somewhat","somehow","sometime"],"pl":"","tn":[],"hi":"कुछ/कोई","en":"an unspecified amount or number","ds":"An unspecified quantity; a part of a whole.","dd":"'Some' indicates an unspecified but positive quantity ('some water', 'some people'). As a determiner it precedes uncountable or plural nouns. As a pronoun it stands alone ('Can I have some?'). It contrasts with 'any', which is used in questions and negatives.","ex":"She brought some flowers from the garden for the table.","exh":"वह बगीचे से मेज के लिए कुछ फूल लाई।","syl":["some"],"syn":["a few","a little","several","certain","a number of","part of"],"ant":["none","no","all","every","each","zero"],"rel":["any","few","several","many","more","certain","little","much","various"],"dif":"basic","fr":65,"ew":0.0,"it":"informational","rp":"high","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"general","spr":"modifier","dl":["noun","adjective"],"co":["of","the","people","time","way","help","food","water","money","work"],"st":["quantity","indefiniteness","partial"],"cv":["affirmative context use","contrast with 'any' in negatives"],"su":["modifier","determiner"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"could","ph":"/kʊd/","pos":"auxiliary verb","gr":"predicate","rt":"can","fam":["can","cannot","couldn't","ability"],"pl":"","tn":[],"hi":"सक सकता था/सकती थी","en":"past tense of can; used for possibility or polite request","ds":"Past tense of can; expresses past ability, polite requests, or possibility.","dd":"'Could' is the past tense of 'can' and serves several functions: expressing past ability ('I could run fast as a child'), possibility ('It could rain'), polite requests ('Could you help me?'), conditional ('If I could, I would'), and suggestions ('You could try again').","ex":"She could speak French when she was in Paris.","exh":"जब वह पेरिस में थी तो वह फ्रेंच बोल सकती थी।","syl":["could"],"syn":["was able to","might","may","would be able to","would"],"ant":["couldn't","was unable to"],"rel":["can","would","might","should","may","able","capable"],"dif":"basic","fr":66,"ew":0.1,"it":"informational","rp":"high","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"general","spr":"auxiliary","dl":["subject","verb"],"co":["be","do","have","see","go","find","help","understand","not","also"],"st":["past ability","possibility","politeness","conditional"],"cv":["past ability use","polite request use","possibility use","conditional use"],"su":["auxiliary","predicate"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"them","ph":"/ðɛm/","pos":"pronoun","gr":"object","rt":"they","fam":["they","their","theirs","themselves"],"pl":"","tn":[],"hi":"उन्हें/उनको","en":"object form of they","ds":"Object pronoun for they; referring to multiple people or things.","dd":"'Them' is the third-person plural object pronoun, used as the direct object ('I saw them'), indirect object ('I gave them the book'), and object of a preposition ('for them'). In modern usage it also serves as a singular gender-neutral object pronoun.","ex":"She introduced them to her parents last evening.","exh":"उसने कल शाम उन्हें अपने माता-पिता से मिलवाया।","syl":["them"],"syn":["those people","the group","these persons"],"ant":["us","me","him","her"],"rel":["they","their","theirs","themselves","people","group"],"dif":"basic","fr":67,"ew":0.0,"it":"relational","rp":"high","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"person","spr":"object","dl":["verb","preposition"],"co":["told","gave","saw","met","helped","asked","called","knew","showed","needed"],"st":["plural","third person","object","reference"],"cv":["direct object use","indirect object use","gender-neutral use"],"su":["object"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"see","ph":"/siː/","pos":"verb","gr":"predicate","rt":"see","fam":["sees","saw","seen","seeing","sight","foresee","oversee"],"pl":"","tn":["see","sees","saw","seen","seeing"],"hi":"देखना/समझना","en":"to perceive with the eyes; to understand","ds":"To perceive visually; also to understand or encounter.","dd":"'See' primarily means to perceive with the eyes ('I can see the mountains'), and also means to understand ('I see what you mean'), to meet ('I'll see you tomorrow'), to find out ('Let's see what happens'), and to escort ('I'll see you to the door'). Its irregular past tense is 'saw'.","ex":"Can you see the mountains from your window today?","exh":"क्या आप आज अपनी खिड़की से पहाड़ देख सकते हैं?","syl":["see"],"syn":["observe","watch","notice","perceive","view","witness","understand","grasp"],"ant":["miss","overlook","ignore","be blind to"],"rel":["look","watch","observe","notice","view","understand","meet","find"],"dif":"basic","fr":68,"ew":0.0,"it":"action","rp":"high","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"action","spr":"verb","dl":["subject","object"],"co":["can","could","I","you","we","what","how","why","clearly","now","later"],"st":["vision","perception","understanding","encounter"],"cv":["visual perception use","understanding use","meeting use","finding out use"],"su":["predicate"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"other","ph":"/ˈʌðər/","pos":"adjective","gr":"modifier","rt":"other","fam":["others","otherwise","another","each other","other's"],"pl":"","tn":[],"hi":"दूसरा/अन्य","en":"different from the one already mentioned; additional","ds":"Not the same as the one mentioned; additional or alternative.","dd":"'Other' means different from or additional to what has been mentioned. As a determiner ('the other day'), pronoun ('the others'), and adjective ('other options'), it indicates something distinct from what is already specified. 'Another' is the singular form and 'others' the plural pronoun.","ex":"She found a completely different solution from the other team.","exh":"उसने दूसरी टीम से बिल्कुल अलग समाधान खोजा।","syl":["oth","er"],"syn":["another","different","alternative","additional","further","extra","remaining"],"ant":["same","identical","this","identical","the first"],"rel":["another","else","additional","different","further","various","alternative"],"dif":"basic","fr":69,"ew":0.0,"it":"descriptive","rp":"high","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"general","spr":"modifier","dl":["noun"],"co":["each","the","on the other hand","many","some","no","any","every"],"st":["distinction","addition","contrast","alternative"],"cv":["determiner use","pronoun use","adjective use"],"su":["modifier","determiner"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"than","ph":"/ðæn/","pos":"conjunction","gr":"connector","rt":"than","fam":[],"pl":"","tn":[],"hi":"से (तुलना में)","en":"used in comparisons to introduce the second element","ds":"Used after comparative adjectives or adverbs to introduce what is being compared.","dd":"'Than' is a conjunction or preposition used in comparisons after comparative adjectives and adverbs ('faster than', 'more beautiful than'). It signals the second element of a comparison. It should not be confused with 'then' which relates to time.","ex":"She runs much faster than anyone else in the class.","exh":"वह कक्षा में किसी से भी बहुत तेज दौड़ती है।","syl":["than"],"syn":["compared to","in contrast to","rather than","relative to"],"ant":[],"rel":["then","as","compared to","versus","rather","relative to"],"dif":"basic","fr":70,"ew":0.0,"it":"relational","rp":"high","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"general","spr":"connector","dl":["comparative adjective","comparative adverb"],"co":["more","less","better","worse","faster","slower","bigger","smaller","rather"],"st":["comparison","contrast","relative degree"],"cv":["comparative use","as comparison with 'as'"],"su":["connector"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"then","ph":"/ðɛn/","pos":"adverb","gr":"connector","rt":"then","fam":["than","when"],"pl":"","tn":[],"hi":"तब/फिर/उसके बाद","en":"at that time; next in sequence","ds":"At that time; after that; as a consequence.","dd":"'Then' functions as a temporal adverb ('I was young then'), a sequential connector ('do this, then that'), and a logical connector indicating consequence ('If you study, then you will pass'). It is essential in storytelling, instruction-giving, and logical reasoning.","ex":"She finished her homework and then went to the park.","exh":"उसने अपना होमवर्क पूरा किया और फिर पार्क चली गई।","syl":["then"],"syn":["at that time","afterward","next","subsequently","later","consequently","therefore","in that case"],"ant":["now","before","previously","earlier"],"rel":["when","after","next","soon","later","afterward","subsequently","consequently"],"dif":"basic","fr":71,"ew":0.0,"it":"logical","rp":"high","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"time","spr":"connector","dl":["clause","verb"],"co":["and","if","but","what","by","right","just","well","do","again"],"st":["time","sequence","consequence","logic"],"cv":["temporal use","sequential use","consequential use"],"su":["connector","modifier"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"now","ph":"/naʊ/","pos":"adverb","gr":"modifier","rt":"now","fam":["nowadays","nowhere","nowhen"],"pl":"","tn":[],"hi":"अभी/अब","en":"at the present moment; immediately","ds":"At the present time or moment; immediately.","dd":"'Now' refers to the present moment ('do it now'), serves as a discourse marker ('Now, let me explain'), and can indicate an immediate consequence ('Now that you mention it'). It contrasts with 'then' (past or future moment) and 'before' (earlier).","ex":"She needs to finish her project right now, urgently.","exh":"उसे अभी तुरंत अपना प्रोजेक्ट खत्म करना है।","syl":["now"],"syn":["currently","at present","immediately","at once","right away","today","presently"],"ant":["then","later","before","previously","in the past","in the future"],"rel":["today","currently","immediately","presently","at present","already","yet"],"dif":"basic","fr":72,"ew":0.0,"it":"informational","rp":"high","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"time","spr":"modifier","dl":["verb"],"co":["right","just","and","but","so","what","I","we","do","can","need"],"st":["present time","immediacy","current moment","discourse"],"cv":["temporal use","discourse marker use","emphasis use"],"su":["modifier"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","informal","formal"]},
    {"w":"look","ph":"/lʊk/","pos":"verb","gr":"predicate","rt":"look","fam":["looks","looked","looking","lookout","outlook","overlook","look-alike"],"pl":"","tn":["look","looks","looked","looking"],"hi":"देखना/दिखना","en":"to direct eyes toward something; to appear","ds":"To direct the eyes at something in order to see it; to seem or appear.","dd":"'Look' means to direct the eyes ('look at the board'), to appear ('you look tired'), to search ('look for your keys'), and to expect ('I look forward to it'). It forms many phrasal verbs ('look after', 'look up', 'look into'). It differs from 'see' in implying deliberate attention.","ex":"Look at the beautiful sunset over the mountains tonight.","exh":"आज रात पहाड़ों के ऊपर सुंदर सूर्यास्त देखो।","syl":["look"],"syn":["glance","gaze","stare","watch","observe","view","appear","seem","eye"],"ant":["ignore","avoid","miss","overlook","disregard"],"rel":["see","watch","observe","gaze","glance","stare","appear","seem","notice"],"dif":"basic","fr":73,"ew":0.1,"it":"action","rp":"high","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"action","spr":"verb","dl":["subject","object","preposition"],"co":["at","for","into","up","after","like","good","out","around","forward"],"st":["vision","attention","appearance","search"],"cv":["deliberate vision use","appearance use","phrasal verb use"],"su":["predicate"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","informal","command"]},
    {"w":"only","ph":"/ˈoʊnli/","pos":"adverb","gr":"modifier","rt":"only","fam":["lone","alone","lonely","sole","solely"],"pl":"","tn":[],"hi":"केवल/सिर्फ/मात्र","en":"and no one or nothing more; solely","ds":"No more than; exclusively; just.","dd":"'Only' is an adverb meaning 'no more than' ('only one'), 'exclusively' ('only you know'), and 'just recently' ('I only just arrived'). As an adjective it means 'single' ('the only one'). Its placement in a sentence can change the meaning significantly: 'I only saw her yesterday' vs. 'I saw only her yesterday'.","ex":"She is the only person who truly understands the problem.","exh":"वह एकमात्र व्यक्ति है जो सच में समस्या को समझती है।","syl":["on","ly"],"syn":["just","merely","solely","exclusively","alone","simply","nothing but"],"ant":["also","as well","additionally","too","moreover"],"rel":["just","merely","solely","simply","alone","exclusively","hardly","barely"],"dif":"basic","fr":74,"ew":0.0,"it":"descriptive","rp":"high","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"general","spr":"modifier","dl":["verb","adjective","adverb","noun"],"co":["one","way","if","time","you","I","he","she","when","the"],"st":["exclusivity","limitation","singularity"],"cv":["limiter use","sole entity use","recency use"],"su":["modifier","adjective"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"come","ph":"/kʌm/","pos":"verb","gr":"predicate","rt":"come","fam":["comes","came","come","coming","outcome","become","newcomer","welcome"],"pl":"","tn":["come","comes","came","coming"],"hi":"आना","en":"to move toward a place or person","ds":"To move toward the speaker or to arrive at a place.","dd":"'Come' indicates movement toward the speaker or the point of reference ('come here'), arrival ('she has come'), and origin ('she comes from India'). It contrasts with 'go' which indicates movement away. It forms many phrasal verbs and idioms ('come up with', 'come across', 'come out').","ex":"Please come to my office at ten o'clock tomorrow.","exh":"कृपया कल सुबह दस बजे मेरे कार्यालय में आएं।","syl":["come"],"syn":["arrive","approach","reach","get to","appear","enter","turn up"],"ant":["go","leave","depart","exit","retreat","withdraw"],"rel":["go","arrive","reach","approach","return","appear","enter","visit"],"dif":"basic","fr":75,"ew":0.1,"it":"action","rp":"high","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"action","spr":"verb","dl":["subject","destination"],"co":["back","out","in","up","down","home","here","along","together","true"],"st":["movement","arrival","approach","origin"],"cv":["approach use","arrival use","origin use","phrasal verb use"],"su":["predicate"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","informal","command"]},
    {"w":"its","ph":"/ɪts/","pos":"pronoun","gr":"modifier","rt":"it","fam":["it","itself"],"pl":"","tn":[],"hi":"इसका/उसका (निर्जीव)","en":"belonging to or associated with a thing","ds":"Possessive form of it; belonging to a thing or animal.","dd":"'Its' is the possessive determiner of the neuter pronoun 'it', indicating that something belongs to or is associated with a non-human entity, thing, animal, or idea. Note: it should not be confused with 'it's' (the contraction of 'it is' or 'it has').","ex":"The company changed its strategy for the new market.","exh":"कंपनी ने नए बाजार के लिए अपनी रणनीति बदली।","syl":["its"],"syn":["belonging to it","of it"],"ant":["his","her","their","my","your"],"rel":["it","itself","his","her","their","our"],"dif":"basic","fr":76,"ew":0.0,"it":"relational","rp":"high","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"general","spr":"modifier","dl":["noun"],"co":["own","way","time","place","name","role","impact","effects","value","use"],"st":["neuter possession","third person","reference"],"cv":["possessive determiner use","referring to things","referring to animals","referring to ideas"],"su":["modifier","determiner"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"over","ph":"/ˈoʊvər/","pos":"preposition","gr":"connector","rt":"over","fam":["overcome","overlook","overall","overdue","overhaul","moreover","turnover"],"pl":"","tn":[],"hi":"के ऊपर/से अधिक/खत्म","en":"above or across; more than; finished","ds":"Above a surface; more than a quantity; completed or finished.","dd":"'Over' is a preposition and adverb with many meanings: above ('the bridge over the river'), across ('jump over the fence'), more than ('over a hundred'), finished ('the game is over'), and in phrasal verbs ('think it over', 'get over it'). It is one of the most productive words for forming compounds.","ex":"The plane flew over the city during the afternoon.","exh":"दोपहर में विमान शहर के ऊपर से उड़ा।","syl":["o","ver"],"syn":["above","across","beyond","more than","finished","done","past","upon","throughout"],"ant":["under","below","beneath","less than","unfinished","incomplete"],"rel":["above","across","beyond","upon","through","throughout","past","more than"],"dif":"basic","fr":77,"ew":0.0,"it":"relational","rp":"high","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"general","spr":"preposition","dl":["noun","verb"],"co":["the","all","turn","come","get","go","think","look","talk","time","here"],"st":["position","excess","completion","movement"],"cv":["position use","excess use","completion use","phrasal verb use"],"su":["preposition","connector"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"think","ph":"/θɪŋk/","pos":"verb","gr":"predicate","rt":"think","fam":["thinks","thought","thinking","thinker","rethink","overthink","unthinkable"],"pl":"","tn":["think","thinks","thought","thinking"],"hi":"सोचना/मानना","en":"to have thoughts or an opinion about something","ds":"To use the mind to consider or form opinions about something.","dd":"'Think' means to use one's mind to reason ('think about a problem'), to believe or consider ('I think it's right'), to remember ('can't think of her name'), and to expect ('I think it will rain'). It is a stative verb in some uses but can appear in progressive for deliberate thinking.","ex":"She needs time to think about the important decision.","exh":"उसे महत्वपूर्ण निर्णय के बारे में सोचने के लिए समय चाहिए।","syl":["think"],"syn":["believe","consider","reflect","ponder","reason","judge","suppose","feel","reckon"],"ant":[],"rel":["believe","consider","feel","know","imagine","wonder","suppose","reflect","reason"],"dif":"basic","fr":78,"ew":0.2,"it":"informational","rp":"high","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"general","spr":"verb","dl":["subject","object","clause"],"co":["about","of","I","you","we","so","not","carefully","hard","clearly","over"],"st":["cognition","belief","reasoning","opinion"],"cv":["deliberate thinking use","belief use","memory use","expectation use"],"su":["predicate"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"also","ph":"/ˈɔːlsoʊ/","pos":"adverb","gr":"connector","rt":"also","fam":["and","plus","too","as well"],"pl":"","tn":[],"hi":"भी/इसके अलावा","en":"in addition; besides; too","ds":"Used to indicate something additional; as well.","dd":"'Also' is an adverb meaning 'in addition' or 'too'. It adds information that relates to what was already said ('She is smart; she is also kind'). In more formal writing 'moreover' or 'furthermore' are used, while informally 'too' and 'as well' appear at the end of sentences.","ex":"She also wants to learn how to play the piano.","exh":"वह पियानो बजाना भी सीखना चाहती है।","syl":["al","so"],"syn":["too","as well","in addition","besides","furthermore","moreover","additionally"],"ant":["only","exclusively","instead","rather"],"rel":["too","as well","additionally","furthermore","moreover","besides","plus","and"],"dif":"basic","fr":79,"ew":0.0,"it":"relational","rp":"high","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"general","spr":"connector","dl":["verb","clause"],"co":["I","she","he","we","they","want","need","have","be","do","can","like"],"st":["addition","continuation","coordination"],"cv":["additive use in middle","additive use before verb","formal context use"],"su":["connector","modifier"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"back","ph":"/bæk/","pos":"adverb","gr":"modifier","rt":"back","fam":["backward","setback","flashback","feedback","backtrack","comeback","drawback"],"pl":"","tn":[],"hi":"वापस/पीछे/पीठ","en":"toward the rear; to a former position; the rear part","ds":"In or toward the rear; to a former place or state.","dd":"'Back' functions as an adverb ('go back'), noun ('the back of the chair'), adjective ('back door'), and verb ('to back a car'). It indicates return ('come back'), direction toward the rear ('step back'), past time ('back in 1990'), and appears in many phrasal verbs ('back up', 'look back', 'hold back').","ex":"She went back to her hometown after many years abroad.","exh":"वह कई साल विदेश में रहने के बाद अपने गृहनगर वापस गई।","syl":["back"],"syn":["rear","behind","backward","rearward","return","again","previously"],"ant":["front","forward","ahead","in front"],"rel":["behind","rear","return","again","previous","toward","backward"],"dif":"basic","fr":80,"ew":0.0,"it":"relational","rp":"high","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"general","spr":"modifier","dl":["verb"],"co":["go","come","get","be","give","take","look","turn","step","get","hold"],"st":["direction","return","position","history"],"cv":["directional use","return use","temporal use","noun use (rear)"],"su":["modifier","noun"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","informal"]},
    {"w":"after","ph":"/ˈæftər/","pos":"preposition","gr":"connector","rt":"after","fam":["afterward","thereafter","afterthought","afternoon","aftermath","afterword"],"pl":"","tn":[],"hi":"के बाद/बाद में","en":"following in time or order","ds":"Later in time than something; following in sequence.","dd":"'After' is a preposition ('after dinner'), conjunction ('after she left'), and adverb ('soon after') indicating time or sequence. It shows that one event follows another. As a prefix it forms words like 'aftermath', 'afternoon', and 'afterthought'.","ex":"She always exercises after she finishes her morning coffee.","exh":"वह सुबह की कॉफी खत्म करने के बाद हमेशा व्यायाम करती है।","syl":["af","ter"],"syn":["following","subsequent to","later than","once","behind","next","in the wake of"],"ant":["before","prior to","earlier than","ahead of"],"rel":["before","then","later","following","subsequent","next","when","once"],"dif":"basic","fr":81,"ew":0.0,"it":"relational","rp":"high","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"time","spr":"connector","dl":["noun","clause","time expression"],"co":["all","that","this","the","school","work","dinner","she","he","they"],"st":["sequence","time","posteriority","following"],"cv":["preposition of time","conjunction of time","adverb use"],"su":["preposition","connector"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"use","ph":"/juːz/","pos":"verb","gr":"predicate","rt":"use","fam":["uses","used","using","useful","useless","user","reuse","misuse","usage"],"pl":"","tn":["use","uses","used","using"],"hi":"उपयोग करना/इस्तेमाल करना","en":"to employ something for a purpose","ds":"To employ or apply something for a purpose or advantage.","dd":"'Use' as a verb means to employ something ('use a tool'), take advantage of ('use an opportunity'), or consume ('use electricity'). As a noun ('use') it refers to the act of using or its purpose. The phrase 'used to' expresses past habits or states.","ex":"She uses modern technology to improve her productivity.","exh":"वह अपनी उत्पादकता बढ़ाने के लिए आधुनिक तकनीक का उपयोग करती है।","syl":["use"],"syn":["employ","apply","utilize","work","exercise","operate","practice","consume"],"ant":["misuse","abuse","waste","ignore","neglect"],"rel":["apply","employ","utilize","operate","handle","work","practice","deploy"],"dif":"basic","fr":82,"ew":0.0,"it":"action","rp":"high","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"action","spr":"verb","dl":["subject","object"],"co":["to","can","could","need","want","have","make","help","give","the"],"st":["employment","application","utilization","purpose"],"cv":["employment use","consumption use","'used to' (past habit)"],"su":["predicate"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"two","ph":"/tuː/","pos":"numeral","gr":"modifier","rt":"two","fam":["twice","double","couple","twin","between"],"pl":"","tn":[],"hi":"दो","en":"the number 2","ds":"The number 2; one more than one.","dd":"'Two' is the cardinal number 2. It counts a pair of items, appears in many expressions ('two-faced', 'in two minds'), and is fundamental to mathematics and language. The adjective form is 'second', and the adverb 'twice' means 'two times'.","ex":"She has two younger brothers who live nearby.","exh":"उसके दो छोटे भाई हैं जो पास में रहते हैं।","syl":["two"],"syn":["a pair","a couple","twice one","dual"],"ant":["one","three"],"rel":["one","three","four","twice","double","pair","couple","second","both"],"dif":"basic","fr":83,"ew":0.0,"it":"informational","rp":"high","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"general","spr":"modifier","dl":["noun"],"co":["of","the","my","her","his","their","times","ways","sides","years","people"],"st":["number","quantity","pair","duality"],"cv":["counting use","ordinal (second)","compound use"],"su":["modifier","subject"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"how","ph":"/haʊ/","pos":"adverb","gr":"connector","rt":"how","fam":["however","somehow","howsoever"],"pl":"","tn":[],"hi":"कैसे/कितना","en":"in what way or manner; to what degree","ds":"In what manner, way, or degree; used to ask questions about process.","dd":"'How' is an interrogative adverb asking about manner ('How did you do it?'), degree ('How tall are you?'), and used in indirect questions ('Tell me how it works'). It is also a relative adverb ('the way how'), an exclamation ('How wonderful!'), and used in greetings ('How are you?').","ex":"She explained exactly how the machine works to us.","exh":"उसने हमें बताया कि मशीन ठीक कैसे काम करती है।","syl":["how"],"syn":["in what way","by what means","in what manner","to what extent","how much"],"ant":[],"rel":["why","what","where","when","which","whom","however","somehow"],"dif":"basic","fr":84,"ew":0.0,"it":"interrogative","rp":"high","cs":"clarification","dc":"question","td":"general","spr":"connector","dl":["verb","clause","adjective"],"co":["are","do","does","did","much","many","long","far","often","well","can"],"st":["manner","degree","process","question"],"cv":["manner interrogative","degree interrogative","indirect question use","greeting use"],"su":["connector","modifier"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"our","ph":"/aʊr/","pos":"pronoun","gr":"modifier","rt":"we","fam":["we","us","ours","ourselves"],"pl":"","tn":[],"hi":"हमारा/हमारी","en":"belonging to or associated with the speaker and others","ds":"Possessive determiner for the speaker and one or more others.","dd":"'Our' is the first-person plural possessive determiner. It indicates that something belongs to the speaker and at least one other person. The corresponding possessive pronoun is 'ours' and the reflexive is 'ourselves'. It expresses shared ownership or collective identity.","ex":"Our team worked hard to finish the project on time.","exh":"हमारी टीम ने समय पर प्रोजेक्ट खत्म करने के लिए कड़ी मेहनत की।","syl":["our"],"syn":["belonging to us","shared","of ours","collective"],"ant":["their","your","my","his","her"],"rel":["ours","ourselves","we","us","shared","collective","mutual"],"dif":"basic","fr":85,"ew":0.1,"it":"identity","rp":"high","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"person","spr":"modifier","dl":["noun"],"co":["own","team","family","home","country","work","goal","plan","life","school"],"st":["possession","first person","plural","collective","community"],"cv":["possessive determiner use","collective identity use"],"su":["modifier","determiner"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"work","ph":"/wɜːrk/","pos":"verb","gr":"predicate","rt":"work","fam":["works","worked","working","worker","rework","overwork","network","teamwork","workplace","framework"],"pl":"","tn":["work","works","worked","working"],"hi":"काम करना/काम","en":"to do a job or task; employment or labor","ds":"To do a job, task, or activity; to function properly.","dd":"'Work' as a verb means to do a job ('work at a hospital'), to function ('the machine works'), or to be effective ('the medicine works'). As a noun it refers to employment ('looking for work'), a task ('the work is done'), and creations ('works of art'). It is central to English vocabulary for labor and effort.","ex":"She works very hard to achieve her professional goals.","exh":"वह अपने पेशेवर लक्ष्य हासिल करने के लिए बहुत मेहनत करती है।","syl":["work"],"syn":["labor","toil","operate","function","run","job","employment","task","effort"],"ant":["rest","play","relax","idle","malfunction","break"],"rel":["job","task","labor","effort","employment","function","operate","practice"],"dif":"basic","fr":86,"ew":0.1,"it":"action","rp":"high","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"action","spr":"verb","dl":["subject","object","preposition"],"co":["hard","well","together","out","on","at","through","long","fast","team"],"st":["labor","employment","function","effort","productivity"],"cv":["employment use","function use","effort use","noun use"],"su":["predicate"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"first","ph":"/fɜːrst/","pos":"adjective","gr":"modifier","rt":"first","fam":["firstly","first-class","firsthand","at first","at first sight"],"pl":"","tn":[],"hi":"पहला/प्रथम","en":"coming before all others in time or order","ds":"The ordinal number 1; coming before everything else.","dd":"'First' is the ordinal form of 'one', indicating the position before all others in time, order, or rank. As an adverb it means 'before anything else' ('first, let me explain') or 'for the first time' ('I first met him in Paris'). It is also used in compound expressions like 'first-class' and 'first aid'.","ex":"She was the first person to arrive at the meeting.","exh":"वह बैठक में पहुँचने वाली पहली व्यक्ति थी।","syl":["first"],"syn":["primary","foremost","initial","earliest","leading","top","premier","chief"],"ant":["last","final","ultimate","latest","worst"],"rel":["second","third","last","initial","primary","original","beginning","early"],"dif":"basic","fr":87,"ew":0.0,"it":"descriptive","rp":"high","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"general","spr":"modifier","dl":["noun"],"co":["the","time","day","year","place","class","name","step","priority","at"],"st":["ordinal","priority","sequence","rank"],"cv":["ordinal use","adverb of sequence use","compound adjective use"],"su":["modifier","adverb"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"well","ph":"/wɛl/","pos":"adverb","gr":"modifier","rt":"well","fam":["wellness","well-being","farewell","wellbeing","welfare","as well"],"pl":"","tn":[],"hi":"अच्छे से/अच्छी तरह/ठीक","en":"in a good or satisfactory manner; also a noun for a water source","ds":"In a good or satisfactory way; also used as an interjection.","dd":"'Well' as an adverb means 'in a good manner' ('she works well'), 'thoroughly' ('mix it well'), or 'considerably' ('well over a hundred'). As an adjective it means 'healthy' ('Are you well?'). As an interjection it introduces or resumes speech ('Well, let me think'). As a noun it is a deep hole for water.","ex":"She plays the violin extremely well for a beginner.","exh":"वह एक शुरुआती के लिए बेहद अच्छे से वायलिन बजाती है।","syl":["well"],"syn":["skillfully","properly","effectively","thoroughly","favorably","nicely","fully","very","considerably"],"ant":["badly","poorly","inadequately","ineffectively","ill"],"rel":["good","fine","properly","correctly","skillfully","healthy","okay","nicely"],"dif":"basic","fr":88,"ew":0.2,"it":"descriptive","rp":"high","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"general","spr":"modifier","dl":["verb","adjective"],"co":["done","known","off","over","as","quite","very","pretty","may","just"],"st":["quality","manner","health","degree"],"cv":["adverb of manner","adjective (healthy)","interjection use","noun (water well)"],"su":["modifier"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"way","ph":"/weɪ/","pos":"noun","gr":"subject","rt":"way","fam":["ways","always","anyway","pathway","gateway","halfway","wayward","waypoint"],"pl":"ways","tn":[],"hi":"रास्ता/तरीका/ढंग","en":"a method, path, or route","ds":"A method of doing something; a road or path; a direction.","dd":"'Way' means a method or manner ('the best way to learn'), a road or path ('way to the station'), a direction ('which way?'), and distance ('a long way off'). It appears in many idiomatic expressions ('by the way', 'no way', 'on the way', 'in the way').","ex":"There is always a way to solve every difficult problem.","exh":"हर मुश्किल समस्या को हल करने का कोई न कोई रास्ता होता है।","syl":["way"],"syn":["method","manner","path","route","approach","means","style","direction","road"],"ant":[],"rel":["path","route","method","manner","road","means","approach","style","direction"],"dif":"basic","fr":89,"ew":0.0,"it":"informational","rp":"high","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"general","spr":"subject","dl":["verb","adjective","preposition"],"co":["best","right","this","that","long","short","all","any","no","the","your"],"st":["method","path","direction","manner"],"cv":["method use","path use","direction use","idiomatic use"],"su":["subject","object"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"even","ph":"/ˈiːvən/","pos":"adverb","gr":"modifier","rt":"even","fam":["evening","event","eventual","unevenness","even-tempered"],"pl":"","tn":[],"hi":"भी/यहाँ तक कि/सम","en":"used for emphasis; also meaning flat or equal","ds":"Used to emphasize something surprising; flat, level, or equal.","dd":"'Even' as an adverb emphasizes something unexpected ('even a child knows this') or adds force ('even better'). As an adjective it means flat ('an even surface'), equal ('an even score'), or calm ('an even temper'). In mathematics it denotes numbers divisible by two.","ex":"She didn't give up even when things became very difficult.","exh":"जब हालात बहुत मुश्किल हो गए तब भी उसने हार नहीं मानी।","syl":["e","ven"],"syn":["also","too","still","yet","flat","level","equal","balanced","smooth","furthermore"],"ant":["uneven","odd","rough","tilted","not even"],"rel":["still","yet","also","though","although","flat","smooth","level","equal"],"dif":"basic","fr":90,"ew":0.1,"it":"logical","rp":"high","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"general","spr":"modifier","dl":["verb","adjective","adverb"],"co":["if","though","more","better","when","worse","though","though","so","now"],"st":["emphasis","surprise","equality","flatness"],"cv":["emphatic adverb","adjective (flat/equal)","concession use"],"su":["modifier"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"new","ph":"/njuː/","pos":"adjective","gr":"modifier","rt":"new","fam":["newly","newness","news","anew","renew","brand-new","newfound"],"pl":"","tn":[],"hi":"नया/नई","en":"recently made, discovered, or invented; unfamiliar","ds":"Recently made, created, or arrived; not seen before.","dd":"'New' describes something recently made ('new product'), recently acquired ('new job'), not used before ('new car'), recently learned ('new information'), or currently in a position ('new teacher'). Its antonym is 'old' and comparative is 'newer'. It forms many compound words.","ex":"She started a new job at a different company last month.","exh":"उसने पिछले महीने एक अलग कंपनी में नई नौकरी शुरू की।","syl":["new"],"syn":["fresh","recent","novel","modern","latest","innovative","original","young","brand-new"],"ant":["old","ancient","outdated","stale","used","former","past","previous"],"rel":["fresh","modern","recent","original","latest","young","current","novel","innovative"],"dif":"basic","fr":91,"ew":0.3,"it":"descriptive","rp":"high","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"general","spr":"modifier","dl":["noun"],"co":["a","the","very","brand","my","her","his","their","our","year","job","home"],"st":["novelty","recency","freshness","innovation"],"cv":["newness adjective","'new to' (unfamiliarity)","compound use"],"su":["modifier"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"want","ph":"/wɒnt/","pos":"verb","gr":"predicate","rt":"want","fam":["wants","wanted","wanting","unwanted","want-ad"],"pl":"","tn":["want","wants","wanted","wanting"],"hi":"चाहना","en":"to have a desire for something","ds":"To feel a desire or wish for something.","dd":"'Want' expresses desire ('I want coffee'), need ('the job wants skill'), and in formal English means to lack ('in want of guidance'). It is commonly followed by a noun or an infinitive ('want to go'). It is a stative verb and not typically used in progressive form, though informally 'wanting' does occur.","ex":"She wants to become a successful doctor in the future.","exh":"वह भविष्य में एक सफल डॉक्टर बनना चाहती है।","syl":["want"],"syn":["desire","wish","crave","need","long for","yearn","require","hope for"],"ant":["have","reject","refuse","dislike","hate","detest","not need"],"rel":["need","wish","desire","like","hope","prefer","expect","require","long for"],"dif":"basic","fr":92,"ew":0.5,"it":"emotional","rp":"high","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"general","spr":"verb","dl":["subject","object","infinitive"],"co":["to","I","you","we","they","he","she","more","this","that","what","just"],"st":["desire","wish","need","motivation"],"cv":["desire use","need use","'want someone to do' (causative)"],"su":["predicate"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","informal","formal"]},
    {"w":"because","ph":"/bɪˈkɒz/","pos":"conjunction","gr":"connector","rt":"because","fam":["cause","reason","for"],"pl":"","tn":[],"hi":"क्योंकि/इसलिए","en":"for the reason that; since","ds":"Used to give the reason for something.","dd":"'Because' is a subordinating conjunction that introduces a clause explaining the reason for the main clause ('She left because she was tired'). It answers the question 'why?'. It should not begin a sentence in formal writing according to traditional style guides, though this rule is widely relaxed in modern English.","ex":"She stayed home because she was feeling very unwell.","exh":"वह घर पर रही क्योंकि वह बहुत अस्वस्थ महसूस कर रही थी।","syl":["be","cause"],"syn":["since","as","for","due to","given that","owing to","inasmuch as","seeing that"],"ant":["despite","although","though","even though","regardless"],"rel":["since","as","for","so","therefore","thus","hence","consequently","due to","given"],"dif":"basic","fr":93,"ew":0.0,"it":"logical","rp":"high","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"general","spr":"connector","dl":["clause","verb"],"co":["of","she","he","they","I","we","it","this","that","the","not","want","need"],"st":["causation","reason","explanation","logic"],"cv":["causal clause use","informal sentence-initial use","'because of' (preposition)"],"su":["connector"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"any","ph":"/ˈɛni/","pos":"determiner","gr":"modifier","rt":"any","fam":["anyone","anything","anywhere","anyway","anytime","anyhow","anymore"],"pl":"","tn":[],"hi":"कोई भी/किसी भी","en":"used in questions and negatives; one or some of whatever kind","ds":"Used to refer to one or some of whatever type, often in questions or negatives.","dd":"'Any' is used in questions ('Do you have any questions?'), negatives ('I don't have any'), and affirmative sentences with special meaning ('Take any seat you like'). It expresses indifference to which specific item or person. As an adverb it emphasizes comparison ('not any better').","ex":"She couldn't find any good restaurants near the hotel.","exh":"उसे होटल के पास कोई भी अच्छा रेस्टोरेंट नहीं मिला।","syl":["an","y"],"syn":["some","whatever","whichever","every","a single","at all"],"ant":["no","none","not one","nothing"],"rel":["some","every","each","all","no","either","neither","a","whichever"],"dif":"basic","fr":94,"ew":0.0,"it":"informational","rp":"high","cs":"any","dc":"question","td":"general","spr":"modifier","dl":["noun","verb"],"co":["more","better","other","time","good","idea","way","reason","else"],"st":["indefiniteness","question context","negation context","free choice"],"cv":["question use","negative use","free choice use","emphasis use"],"su":["modifier","determiner"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"these","ph":"/ðiːz/","pos":"determiner","gr":"modifier","rt":"this","fam":["this","those","that","the"],"pl":"","tn":[],"hi":"ये/इन","en":"plural form of this; referring to nearby things","ds":"Refers to multiple specific things or people nearby or just mentioned.","dd":"'These' is the plural of 'this', used as a demonstrative determiner ('these books') and pronoun ('I'll take these'). It indicates items that are physically close to the speaker or have just been mentioned. It contrasts with 'those', which refers to things farther away.","ex":"These new ideas could help improve our current system.","exh":"ये नए विचार हमारी मौजूदा प्रणाली को बेहतर बनाने में मदद कर सकते हैं।","syl":["these"],"syn":["the following","the nearby","such","the mentioned","the current"],"ant":["those","that","the other"],"rel":["this","those","that","the","such","here","now"],"dif":"basic","fr":95,"ew":0.0,"it":"relational","rp":"high","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"general","spr":"modifier","dl":["noun"],"co":["are","were","days","ideas","people","things","words","issues","problems"],"st":["proximity","plural","demonstration","reference"],"cv":["near proximity use","just-mentioned reference use","plural demonstrative use"],"su":["modifier","pronoun"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"give","ph":"/ɡɪv/","pos":"verb","gr":"predicate","rt":"give","fam":["gives","gave","given","giving","giver","forgive","given","given"],"pl":"","tn":["give","gives","gave","given","giving"],"hi":"देना","en":"to transfer something to someone","ds":"To transfer possession of something to another person.","dd":"'Give' means to transfer something to someone ('give a gift'), to produce or provide ('give a speech', 'give light'), and to yield or concede ('give way'). It is one of the most common ditransitive verbs in English (taking both direct and indirect objects). Its irregular past tense is 'gave'.","ex":"She gave her younger sister a beautiful birthday gift.","exh":"उसने अपनी छोटी बहन को एक सुंदर जन्मदिन का उपहार दिया।","syl":["give"],"syn":["offer","provide","present","donate","grant","award","hand","supply","bestow"],"ant":["take","receive","keep","withhold","deny","refuse","take back"],"rel":["offer","provide","send","hand","deliver","present","donate","award","grant"],"dif":"basic","fr":96,"ew":0.3,"it":"action","rp":"high","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"action","spr":"verb","dl":["subject","direct object","indirect object"],"co":["me","him","her","them","us","you","back","away","up","out","in"],"st":["transfer","provision","donation","gift"],"cv":["physical transfer use","abstract provision use","speech act use"],"su":["predicate"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"day","ph":"/deɪ/","pos":"noun","gr":"subject","rt":"day","fam":["days","daily","daylight","daytime","today","everyday","birthday","holiday","midday","weekday","daybreak"],"pl":"days","tn":[],"hi":"दिन","en":"a period of 24 hours; the time of light","ds":"A period of 24 hours; the time between sunrise and sunset.","dd":"'Day' refers to the 24-hour period ('three days'), the period of daylight (contrasted with night), a specific date ('on that day'), and an era or period ('in my day'). It is fundamental to measuring time and appears in countless compound words and expressions.","ex":"She spends every day trying to learn something new.","exh":"वह हर दिन कुछ नया सीखने की कोशिश करती है।","syl":["day"],"syn":["daytime","daylight","date","24 hours","period","workday"],"ant":["night","darkness","nighttime"],"rel":["night","week","month","year","morning","evening","hour","time","daily"],"dif":"basic","fr":97,"ew":0.1,"it":"informational","rp":"high","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"time","spr":"subject","dl":["verb","adjective"],"co":["every","all","one","this","that","good","long","whole","working","next"],"st":["time","light","calendar","duration"],"cv":["24-hour use","daytime use","date reference","era use"],"su":["subject","object"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"most","ph":"/moʊst/","pos":"determiner","gr":"modifier","rt":"most","fam":["mostly","almost","more","utmost","foremost","topmost","at most","innermost"],"pl":"","tn":[],"hi":"सबसे/अधिकांश/अधिकतम","en":"the greatest in amount or degree; the majority","ds":"The greatest quantity, extent, or degree; the majority.","dd":"'Most' is the superlative of 'many' and 'much'. As a determiner it indicates the greatest quantity ('most people'). As an adverb it forms superlatives ('most beautiful'). As a noun it means the greatest part ('most of the work'). The phrase 'at most' means not more than; 'for the most part' means mainly.","ex":"Most students passed the difficult exam with good grades.","exh":"अधिकांश छात्रों ने अच्छे अंकों से कठिन परीक्षा पास की।","syl":["most"],"syn":["majority","greatest","maximum","primarily","largely","chiefly","mainly"],"ant":["least","fewest","minimum","few","smallest"],"rel":["more","many","much","all","majority","largely","mainly","typically"],"dif":"basic","fr":98,"ew":0.0,"it":"informational","rp":"high","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"general","spr":"modifier","dl":["noun","adjective"],"co":["of","the","people","students","likely","important","common","effective"],"st":["superlative","majority","maximum","degree"],"cv":["superlative determiner use","superlative adverb use","pronoun use"],"su":["modifier","determiner"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"us","ph":"/ʌs/","pos":"pronoun","gr":"object","rt":"we","fam":["we","our","ours","ourselves"],"pl":"","tn":[],"hi":"हमें/हम को","en":"object form of we","ds":"Used as the object of a verb or preposition to refer to the speaker and others.","dd":"'Us' is the first-person plural object pronoun. It is used as the direct object ('She helped us'), indirect object ('She gave us the news'), and object of a preposition ('for us'). In informal speech it sometimes replaces 'we' as subject, though this is non-standard.","ex":"She invited all of us to her graduation celebration.","exh":"उसने हम सभी को अपने स्नातक समारोह में आमंत्रित किया।","syl":["us"],"syn":["we","ourselves","our group"],"ant":["them","you","him","her"],"rel":["we","our","ours","ourselves","together","all"],"dif":"basic","fr":99,"ew":0.2,"it":"identity","rp":"high","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"person","spr":"object","dl":["verb","preposition"],"co":["help","tell","give","let","show","join","teach","allow","invite","lead"],"st":["first person","plural","object","community"],"cv":["direct object use","indirect object use","object of preposition"],"su":["object"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"great","ph":"/ɡreɪt/","pos":"adjective","gr":"modifier","rt":"great","fam":["greatly","greatness","great-grandfather","great-grandmother"],"pl":"","tn":[],"hi":"महान/शानदार/बड़ा","en":"of an exceptionally high quality; large in size or extent","ds":"Of a very high quality or importance; large in scale or significance.","dd":"'Great' means very good ('a great idea'), large ('a great distance'), important ('a great moment'), and skillful ('a great artist'). It is also used in family relationships ('great-grandfather') and as an enthusiastic affirmation. Historically it also meant 'physically large'.","ex":"She has a great passion for music and creative arts.","exh":"उसे संगीत और रचनात्मक कलाओं के प्रति बहुत जुनून है।","syl":["great"],"syn":["excellent","wonderful","fantastic","superb","magnificent","outstanding","large","huge","major","important"],"ant":["terrible","awful","poor","small","minor","insignificant","mediocre"],"rel":["good","excellent","fine","large","big","important","significant","major","wonderful"],"dif":"basic","fr":100,"ew":0.6,"it":"descriptive","rp":"high","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"general","spr":"modifier","dl":["noun","verb"],"co":["a","very","so","quite","truly","job","idea","way","opportunity","success"],"st":["excellence","size","importance","enthusiasm"],"cv":["quality adjective","size adjective","enthusiastic exclamation","family relation prefix"],"su":["modifier"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    # ── SET 2: words 101-200 ────────────────────────────────────────────────
    {"w":"between","ph":"/bɪˈtwiːn/","pos":"preposition","gr":"connector","rt":"between","fam":["betwixt","middle","amid"],"pl":"","tn":[],"hi":"के बीच में","en":"in the space separating two things","ds":"In the space, time, or gap that separates two things or people.","dd":"'Between' is a preposition indicating position or time separating two distinct entities ('between the chairs', 'between Monday and Friday'). It can also show connection or relationship ('an agreement between them'). For more than two items 'among' is traditionally preferred, though this distinction is relaxing.","ex":"She sat between her two best friends during the lunch break.","exh":"लंच ब्रेक में वह अपने दो सबसे अच्छे दोस्तों के बीच बैठी।","syl":["be","tween"],"syn":["amid","in the middle of","among","in between","separating","linking"],"ant":["outside","beyond","apart from","away from"],"rel":["among","amid","in the middle","through","across","within","separating"],"dif":"basic","fr":101,"ew":0.0,"it":"relational","rp":"high","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"general","spr":"preposition","dl":["two nouns"],"co":["the","you","me","him","her","them","us","now","and","or"],"st":["position","separation","relationship","interval"],"cv":["spatial use","temporal use","relational use"],"su":["preposition","connector"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"need","ph":"/niːd/","pos":"verb","gr":"predicate","rt":"need","fam":["needs","needed","needing","needy","needless","needful"],"pl":"","tn":["need","needs","needed","needing"],"hi":"जरूरत होना/चाहिए","en":"to require something as necessary","ds":"To require something as essential or necessary.","dd":"'Need' as a main verb means to require ('I need water'). As a modal it negates obligation ('you needn't go'). As a noun it refers to necessity ('a basic need'). Unlike 'want', 'need' implies necessity rather than desire. It can be used with or without 'to' in negative and question contexts.","ex":"She needs to practice every day to improve her skills.","exh":"अपने कौशल को सुधारने के लिए उसे हर रोज अभ्यास करना चाहिए।","syl":["need"],"syn":["require","want","lack","demand","have to","must","call for","be in need of"],"ant":["have","own","possess","be satisfied with"],"rel":["require","want","must","have to","demand","lack","call for","rely on"],"dif":"basic","fr":102,"ew":0.2,"it":"informational","rp":"high","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"general","spr":"verb","dl":["subject","object","infinitive"],"co":["to","I","you","we","they","he","she","more","help","time","money"],"st":["necessity","requirement","lack","obligation"],"cv":["main verb use","modal use","noun use"],"su":["predicate"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"large","ph":"/lɑːrdʒ/","pos":"adjective","gr":"modifier","rt":"large","fam":["largely","largest","larger","enlarge","large-scale","at large"],"pl":"","tn":[],"hi":"बड़ा/विशाल","en":"of more than average size, amount, or extent","ds":"Greater than normal in size, extent, or amount.","dd":"'Large' describes size ('a large room'), amount ('a large number'), or scale ('a large organization'). It is generally synonymous with 'big' but 'large' is preferred in formal contexts and 'big' in informal ones. 'At large' means free or unconstrained; 'by and large' means generally.","ex":"She lives in a large house with a beautiful garden.","exh":"वह एक बड़े घर में रहती है जिसमें एक सुंदर बगीचा है।","syl":["large"],"syn":["big","huge","great","vast","enormous","sizable","substantial","extensive","wide"],"ant":["small","tiny","little","minor","narrow","limited"],"rel":["big","huge","great","vast","wide","broad","massive","extensive","significant"],"dif":"basic","fr":103,"ew":0.0,"it":"descriptive","rp":"medium","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"general","spr":"modifier","dl":["noun"],"co":["a","very","quite","fairly","rather","number","amount","part","area","room"],"st":["size","extent","scale","quantity"],"cv":["size adjective","'at large' (free)","'by and large' (generally)"],"su":["modifier"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"often","ph":"/ˈɒfən/","pos":"adverb","gr":"modifier","rt":"often","fam":["oftentimes","more often","oft","frequently"],"pl":"","tn":[],"hi":"अक्सर/बार-बार","en":"many times; frequently","ds":"Happening many times; with regularity.","dd":"'Often' means 'frequently' or 'many times'. It indicates regularity in occurrence and typically appears before the main verb or after auxiliaries. It contrasts with 'sometimes' (occasionally), 'rarely' (seldom), and 'never'. The comparative form is 'more often' and superlative 'most often'.","ex":"She often visits the local library to read new books.","exh":"वह नई किताबें पढ़ने के लिए अक्सर स्थानीय पुस्तकालय जाती है।","syl":["of","ten"],"syn":["frequently","regularly","repeatedly","commonly","generally","usually","habitually","time and again"],"ant":["rarely","seldom","never","infrequently","occasionally","sometimes"],"rel":["usually","regularly","frequently","sometimes","always","repeatedly","commonly","generally"],"dif":"basic","fr":104,"ew":0.0,"it":"descriptive","rp":"medium","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"time","spr":"modifier","dl":["verb","adjective"],"co":["I","she","he","we","they","do","go","see","get","come","very","quite","so"],"st":["frequency","regularity","habit","time"],"cv":["before main verb","after auxiliary verb","in questions"],"su":["modifier"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"hand","ph":"/hænd/","pos":"noun","gr":"subject","rt":"hand","fam":["hands","handful","handmade","handsome","handle","handout","handshake","handy","firsthand"],"pl":"hands","tn":[],"hi":"हाथ","en":"the end part of the arm with fingers","ds":"The body part at the end of the arm used for grasping and touching.","dd":"'Hand' is primarily the body part at the end of the human arm used for grasping and manipulation. As a verb it means to give ('hand me the book'). It appears in dozens of idioms ('hand in hand', 'out of hand', 'first-hand', 'give a hand'). The plural 'hands' often means workers or crew members.","ex":"She raised her hand to ask the teacher a question.","exh":"उसने शिक्षक से एक प्रश्न पूछने के लिए हाथ उठाया।","syl":["hand"],"syn":["palm","fist","paw","limb","help","worker","pointer"],"ant":[],"rel":["arm","finger","palm","wrist","touch","grip","grasp","hold","give"],"dif":"basic","fr":105,"ew":0.1,"it":"informational","rp":"medium","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"person","spr":"subject","dl":["verb","adjective","possessive"],"co":["right","left","raise","shake","hold","give","take","upper","free","helping"],"st":["body part","appendage","tool","help","writing"],"cv":["body part use","verb use (give)","idiomatic use"],"su":["subject","object"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"high","ph":"/haɪ/","pos":"adjective","gr":"modifier","rt":"high","fam":["highly","height","higher","highest","highland","highlight","high-rise","highway"],"pl":"","tn":[],"hi":"ऊँचा/उच्च","en":"of great vertical extent; elevated in position or level","ds":"At or to a great height; of a level greater than normal.","dd":"'High' describes vertical extent ('a high mountain'), level ('high temperature'), rank ('high office'), quality ('high standard'), or intensity ('high hopes'). As an adverb it means 'to a great height'. Its comparative is 'higher' and superlative 'highest'. The noun form is 'height'.","ex":"She climbed to a very high point on the mountain trail.","exh":"वह पहाड़ी रास्ते पर बहुत ऊँचे बिंदु तक चढ़ी।","syl":["high"],"syn":["tall","elevated","lofty","towering","upper","great","advanced","superior","intense"],"ant":["low","short","deep","inferior","minimal","reduced"],"rel":["tall","elevated","top","upper","above","peak","mountain","sky","level","grade"],"dif":"basic","fr":106,"ew":0.0,"it":"descriptive","rp":"medium","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"general","spr":"modifier","dl":["noun"],"co":["very","sky","school","road","pressure","standard","quality","level","risk"],"st":["elevation","level","intensity","superiority"],"cv":["elevation adjective","level adjective","intensity adjective","adverb use"],"su":["modifier"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"place","ph":"/pleɪs/","pos":"noun","gr":"subject","rt":"place","fam":["places","placement","misplace","replace","displaced","workplace","birthplace","marketplace"],"pl":"places","tn":["place","places","placed","placing"],"hi":"स्थान/जगह/रखना","en":"a particular position or area; to put something somewhere","ds":"A specific location or area; to put something in a position.","dd":"'Place' as a noun means a specific location ('a quiet place'), a position in a sequence ('second place'), or a role ('in place of'). As a verb it means to put something in position ('place the book here'). It appears in many expressions ('take place', 'in the first place', 'out of place').","ex":"This is a beautiful place to relax on a quiet afternoon.","exh":"यह शांत दोपहर में आराम करने के लिए एक सुंदर जगह है।","syl":["place"],"syn":["location","spot","site","area","position","put","set","arrange","situate"],"ant":["remove","displace","take away"],"rel":["location","spot","site","area","position","region","space","point","home"],"dif":"basic","fr":107,"ew":0.0,"it":"informational","rp":"medium","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"place","spr":"subject","dl":["verb","adjective","preposition"],"co":["take","right","first","special","safe","quiet","good","beautiful","in"],"st":["location","position","setting","space"],"cv":["noun use (location)","verb use (put)","idiomatic use"],"su":["subject","object"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"hold","ph":"/hoʊld/","pos":"verb","gr":"predicate","rt":"hold","fam":["holds","held","holding","holder","stronghold","household","behold","uphold","withhold","foothold"],"pl":"","tn":["hold","holds","held","holding"],"hi":"पकड़ना/रखना","en":"to keep in one's grasp; to contain","ds":"To keep or carry in one's hand or arms; to keep something in a position.","dd":"'Hold' means to grasp ('hold a cup'), contain ('the bag holds ten items'), organize ('hold a meeting'), remain valid ('the rule holds'), and wait ('hold on'). Its irregular past tense is 'held'. It forms many phrasal verbs ('hold back', 'hold on', 'hold up') and appears in many idioms.","ex":"She held her little daughter's hand as they crossed the road.","exh":"सड़क पार करते समय उसने अपनी छोटी बेटी का हाथ थामे रखा।","syl":["hold"],"syn":["grasp","grip","clutch","carry","keep","support","contain","maintain","detain"],"ant":["release","let go","drop","surrender","free","relinquish"],"rel":["keep","carry","grasp","grip","contain","support","maintain","secure","embrace"],"dif":"basic","fr":108,"ew":0.1,"it":"action","rp":"medium","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"action","spr":"verb","dl":["subject","object"],"co":["on","up","back","tight","still","meeting","event","responsible","position"],"st":["grasp","containment","organization","maintenance"],"cv":["physical grasp use","containment use","event organization use","phrasal verb use"],"su":["predicate"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"turn","ph":"/tɜːrn/","pos":"verb","gr":"predicate","rt":"turn","fam":["turns","turned","turning","turnover","return","overturn","downturn","upturn","turnaround"],"pl":"","tn":["turn","turns","turned","turning"],"hi":"मुड़ना/बदलना/बारी","en":"to rotate or change direction; a rotation or opportunity","ds":"To move in a circle or change direction; an opportunity or chance.","dd":"'Turn' as a verb means to rotate ('turn the wheel'), change direction ('turn left'), change state ('turn cold'), or transform ('turn into'). As a noun it means a rotation, a person's opportunity ('your turn'), and a bend in a road. It forms many phrasal verbs ('turn up', 'turn down', 'turn into').","ex":"Please turn left at the traffic light on the main road.","exh":"मुख्य सड़क पर ट्रैफिक लाइट पर बाईं ओर मुड़ें।","syl":["turn"],"syn":["rotate","spin","revolve","pivot","change","shift","transform","go around","bend"],"ant":["stay","remain still","keep straight","hold steady"],"rel":["rotate","spin","change","shift","twist","revolve","pivot","return","bend","corner"],"dif":"basic","fr":109,"ew":0.0,"it":"action","rp":"medium","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"action","spr":"verb","dl":["subject","direction","object"],"co":["right","left","back","around","over","into","on","off","out","away","up","down"],"st":["rotation","direction change","transformation","opportunity","sequence"],"cv":["directional use","transformation use","opportunity noun use","phrasal verb use"],"su":["predicate"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"few","ph":"/fjuː/","pos":"determiner","gr":"modifier","rt":"few","fam":["fewer","fewest","a few","quite a few"],"pl":"","tn":[],"hi":"कुछ/थोड़े से","en":"a small number of; not many","ds":"A small number of things; not many but more than one or two.","dd":"'Few' as a determiner means 'a small number' ('few people came'). 'A few' means 'some but not many' and is positive, while 'few' without the article implies less than expected. In formal contexts 'fewer' (countable) contrasts with 'less' (uncountable). 'Quite a few' means 'a fairly large number'.","ex":"Only a few students managed to complete the project early.","exh":"केवल कुछ छात्र ही परियोजना को जल्दी पूरा कर पाए।","syl":["few"],"syn":["a small number","not many","a handful","some","a couple","scarce","limited","rare"],"ant":["many","much","lots","numerous","plenty","abundant","countless"],"rel":["some","little","several","couple","handful","scarce","limited","not many"],"dif":"basic","fr":110,"ew":0.0,"it":"informational","rp":"medium","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"general","spr":"modifier","dl":["noun"],"co":["a","the","very","only","just","people","days","words","more","remaining"],"st":["small quantity","scarcity","limited number"],"cv":["'few' (negative)","'a few' (positive)","'quite a few' (fairly many)"],"su":["modifier","determiner"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"never","ph":"/ˈnɛvər/","pos":"adverb","gr":"modifier","rt":"never","fam":["ever","never-ending","never-before","nevertheless"],"pl":"","tn":[],"hi":"कभी नहीं","en":"at no time; not ever","ds":"At no time in the past, present, or future; not ever.","dd":"'Never' is a strong negation adverb meaning 'at no time'. It is stronger than 'not' and 'hardly ever'. 'Never' is placed before the main verb but after auxiliaries. It is used for absolute denial ('I never lie'), strong advice ('never give up'), and emphasis ('never in my life').","ex":"She never gives up on her goals, no matter how hard they seem.","exh":"वह कभी हार नहीं मानती, चाहे उसके लक्ष्य कितने भी कठिन क्यों न लगें।","syl":["nev","er"],"syn":["not ever","at no time","not once","under no circumstances","on no occasion","not at all"],"ant":["always","ever","sometimes","often","forever","continuously"],"rel":["ever","always","sometimes","hardly","rarely","forever","not","no","nothing"],"dif":"basic","fr":111,"ew":0.3,"it":"logical","rp":"high","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"time","spr":"modifier","dl":["verb","auxiliary verb"],"co":["I","you","we","will","would","have","do","say","know","give","forget","mind"],"st":["negation","time","absolute denial","frequency"],"cv":["negation of time","emphatic use","in 'never mind' idiom"],"su":["modifier","negator"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"old","ph":"/oʊld/","pos":"adjective","gr":"modifier","rt":"old","fam":["older","oldest","olden","age","aged","antiquated","elder"],"pl":"","tn":[],"hi":"पुराना/बूढ़ा","en":"having lived or existed for a long time; not new","ds":"Having existed or been in use for a long time; advanced in age.","dd":"'Old' describes age ('an old man'), duration ('an old tradition'), and familiar connection ('an old friend'). Its comparative is 'older' (or formally 'elder' for family relations) and superlative is 'oldest/eldest'. It contrasts with 'new' (things) and 'young' (people).","ex":"She learned a lot from talking to the old villagers.","exh":"उसने पुराने गाँव वालों से बात करके बहुत कुछ सीखा।","syl":["old"],"syn":["aged","elderly","ancient","mature","long-standing","worn","former","past","veteran"],"ant":["new","young","recent","fresh","modern","latest","youthful"],"rel":["aged","ancient","mature","elder","former","past","vintage","classic","traditional"],"dif":"basic","fr":112,"ew":0.2,"it":"descriptive","rp":"medium","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"general","spr":"modifier","dl":["noun"],"co":["very","quite","too","enough","man","woman","house","friend","days","age"],"st":["age","duration","familiarity","history"],"cv":["age adjective","duration adjective","'old friend' (familiar)"],"su":["modifier"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"found","ph":"/faʊnd/","pos":"verb","gr":"predicate","rt":"find","fam":["find","finds","finding","found","founder","foundation","refund","unfound"],"pl":"","tn":["find","finds","found","finding"],"hi":"मिला/स्थापित किया","en":"past tense of find; or to establish an institution","ds":"Past tense of 'find'; also means to establish or start an institution.","dd":"'Found' is the past tense and past participle of 'find' ('I found my keys'). It is also a separate verb meaning to establish or create an institution ('found a company'). These two verbs have different pronunciations in some dialects but are spelled the same in the past tense.","ex":"She finally found the answer she had been looking for so long.","exh":"आखिरकार उसे वह जवाब मिल गया जिसे वह इतने समय से ढूंढ रही थी।","syl":["found"],"syn":["discovered","located","came across","detected","established","created","built","started"],"ant":["lost","missed","overlooked","dissolved","ended","closed"],"rel":["find","discover","locate","detect","see","come across","establish","create","start"],"dif":"basic","fr":113,"ew":0.2,"it":"action","rp":"medium","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"action","spr":"verb","dl":["subject","object"],"co":["I","she","he","they","we","have","had","just","finally","never","something","it"],"st":["discovery","location","establishment","realization"],"cv":["past tense of 'find'","'found' (establish) use"],"su":["predicate"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"long","ph":"/lɒŋ/","pos":"adjective","gr":"modifier","rt":"long","fam":["longer","longest","along","belong","length","lengthen","longtime","long-term","prolong"],"pl":"","tn":[],"hi":"लंबा/लंबे समय तक","en":"of great length or duration","ds":"Extending for a great distance or a great amount of time.","dd":"'Long' as an adjective describes physical length ('a long road') or duration ('a long time'). As an adverb it means 'for a long time' ('She waited long'). As a verb it means 'to yearn' ('I long to travel'). The noun form is 'length'. Many compounds exist: 'long-term', 'long-distance', 'lifelong'.","ex":"She has been waiting for this long-awaited opportunity for years.","exh":"वह इस बहुप्रतीक्षित अवसर का वर्षों से इंतजार कर रही थी।","syl":["long"],"syn":["lengthy","extended","prolonged","extensive","tall","stretched","far-reaching"],"ant":["short","brief","quick","small","compact","narrow"],"rel":["length","duration","tall","extended","far","wide","stretch","distant","time"],"dif":"basic","fr":114,"ew":0.0,"it":"descriptive","rp":"medium","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"general","spr":"modifier","dl":["noun","time expression"],"co":["very","too","a","so","how","for","ago","time","way","road","hair","arm"],"st":["length","duration","distance","yearning"],"cv":["physical length use","duration use","verb use (yearn)"],"su":["modifier"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"big","ph":"/bɪɡ/","pos":"adjective","gr":"modifier","rt":"big","fam":["bigger","biggest","bigness","big-time","big-picture","outbig"],"pl":"","tn":[],"hi":"बड़ा","en":"of great size; important or significant","ds":"Of a large size; important or having a great impact.","dd":"'Big' is the informal counterpart of 'large' or 'great'. It describes size ('a big house'), importance ('a big decision'), scale ('a big company'), and emotional intensity ('a big hug'). It is more common in informal speech, while 'large' is preferred in formal writing.","ex":"She has big dreams and works hard every single day.","exh":"उसके बड़े सपने हैं और वह हर एक दिन मेहनत करती है।","syl":["big"],"syn":["large","great","huge","enormous","significant","important","major","vast"],"ant":["small","little","tiny","minor","insignificant","trivial"],"rel":["large","great","huge","enormous","important","major","wide","broad","vast"],"dif":"basic","fr":115,"ew":0.2,"it":"descriptive","rp":"medium","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"general","spr":"modifier","dl":["noun"],"co":["very","so","too","really","the","a","deal","picture","day","city","part"],"st":["size","importance","scale","significance"],"cv":["size adjective","importance adjective","informal use"],"su":["modifier"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","informal"]},
    {"w":"down","ph":"/daʊn/","pos":"adverb","gr":"modifier","rt":"down","fam":["downward","download","downfall","downtown","downside","countdown","breakdown","markdown","sundown"],"pl":"","tn":[],"hi":"नीचे","en":"toward or in a lower position","ds":"Moving or directed toward a lower position or level.","dd":"'Down' indicates movement to a lower position, reduction in level, or failure. It forms many phrasal verbs ('sit down', 'write down', 'break down', 'come down'). As a preposition it means 'along' ('down the street'). As an adjective it means 'sad' or 'not working'. As a noun it refers to soft feathers.","ex":"She walked slowly down the stairs to the kitchen below.","exh":"वह धीरे-धीरे नीचे रसोई तक सीढ़ियाँ उतरी।","syl":["down"],"syn":["downward","below","lower","beneath","fallen","descended","reduced","sad","upset"],"ant":["up","above","higher","upward","raised","ascending"],"rel":["below","under","lower","beneath","descend","fall","drop","reduce","decrease"],"dif":"basic","fr":116,"ew":0.1,"it":"descriptive","rp":"medium","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"general","spr":"modifier","dl":["verb"],"co":["sit","put","go","come","write","slow","break","cut","turn","run","fall","let"],"st":["direction","descent","reduction","failure","sadness"],"cv":["directional use","phrasal verb use","adjective use (sad)","noun use (feathers)"],"su":["modifier","preposition"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","informal"]},
    {"w":"may","ph":"/meɪ/","pos":"auxiliary verb","gr":"predicate","rt":"may","fam":["maybe","might","possible","perhaps"],"pl":"","tn":["may","might"],"hi":"शायद/हो सकता है","en":"expressing possibility or permission","ds":"Used to express possibility, permission, or wishes.","dd":"'May' is a modal auxiliary expressing possibility ('it may rain'), permission in formal contexts ('may I come in?'), and wishes ('may you be well'). It is more formal than 'can' for permission. Its past tense is 'might'. In formal writing 'may' is preferred over 'can' for permission.","ex":"You may leave the room when you have finished your work.","exh":"जब आप अपना काम पूरा कर लें तो आप कमरे से जा सकते हैं।","syl":["may"],"syn":["might","could","possibly","perhaps","be allowed to","be permitted to"],"ant":["cannot","must not","may not"],"rel":["might","can","could","perhaps","possibly","probably","allow","permit"],"dif":"basic","fr":117,"ew":0.0,"it":"informational","rp":"high","cs":"any","dc":"question","td":"general","spr":"auxiliary","dl":["subject","verb"],"co":["I","you","we","they","he","she","be","have","go","come","need","want"],"st":["possibility","permission","wish","modal"],"cv":["possibility use","permission use","wish use"],"su":["auxiliary","predicate"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"still","ph":"/stɪl/","pos":"adverb","gr":"modifier","rt":"still","fam":["stillness","still-life","distill","instill","standstill","stillwater"],"pl":"","tn":[],"hi":"अभी भी/फिर भी/शांत","en":"continuing to be; up to this time; motionless","ds":"Up to and including this moment; without movement; even so.","dd":"'Still' as an adverb means 'continuing up to the present' ('she is still here'), 'even so' ('still, I believe it'), and 'even more' ('still better'). As an adjective it means motionless or calm. As a noun it refers to a device for distilling liquids. In comparisons 'still' emphasizes the comparative.","ex":"She is still working at the same company after ten years.","exh":"दस साल बाद भी वह उसी कंपनी में काम कर रही है।","syl":["still"],"syn":["yet","even now","up to now","continuing","calm","motionless","silent","quiet","nevertheless"],"ant":["already","moving","noisy","changed","no longer","gone","done"],"rel":["yet","even","however","nevertheless","calm","quiet","motionless","continue","remain"],"dif":"basic","fr":118,"ew":0.1,"it":"relational","rp":"high","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"general","spr":"modifier","dl":["verb","adjective"],"co":["I","she","he","we","they","am","is","are","have","can","going","not"],"st":["continuity","persistence","calm","emphasis"],"cv":["temporal continuity use","concessive use","adjective use (calm)"],"su":["modifier"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"own","ph":"/oʊn/","pos":"adjective","gr":"modifier","rt":"own","fam":["owned","owner","ownership","disown","home-grown","self-owned"],"pl":"","tn":["own","owns","owned","owning"],"hi":"खुद का/अपना","en":"belonging to a specified person; to possess","ds":"Belonging to oneself; to have as property.","dd":"'Own' as an adjective emphasizes that something belongs to the person mentioned ('my own idea'). As a verb it means to possess ('I own a car'). 'On your own' means alone. 'Come into one's own' means to demonstrate one's abilities. 'Hold your own' means to maintain your position.","ex":"She started her own business after years of experience.","exh":"वह वर्षों के अनुभव के बाद अपना खुद का व्यवसाय शुरू किया।","syl":["own"],"syn":["possess","have","hold","belonging","personal","private","individual","one's"],"ant":["others'","shared","common","public","borrow","rent"],"rel":["possess","have","keep","mine","personal","private","self","individual","property"],"dif":"basic","fr":119,"ew":0.2,"it":"identity","rp":"medium","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"general","spr":"modifier","dl":["pronoun","noun"],"co":["my","your","her","his","their","our","on your own","home","car","business","life"],"st":["possession","individuality","ownership","personal"],"cv":["possessive adjective use","verb use (possess)","'on your own' (alone)"],"su":["modifier","predicate"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"right","ph":"/raɪt/","pos":"adjective","gr":"modifier","rt":"right","fam":["rights","rightly","righteous","rightful","upright","outright","straighten","right-hand","copyright"],"pl":"","tn":[],"hi":"सही/दाहिना/अधिकार","en":"morally good; correct; the opposite of left","ds":"Correct or true; the opposite of left; morally acceptable.","dd":"'Right' serves as an adjective ('the right answer'), noun ('human rights', 'the right side'), adverb ('turn right', 'right away'), and interjection ('Right!', agreeing). It has two main meanings: correctness/morality and the direction opposite to left. These meanings are etymologically distinct.","ex":"She made the right decision by choosing to study abroad.","exh":"उसने विदेश में पढ़ाई करने का सही निर्णय लिया।","syl":["right"],"syn":["correct","accurate","true","proper","just","fair","moral","suitable","appropriate","lawful"],"ant":["wrong","incorrect","false","left","unjust","improper","unsuitable"],"rel":["correct","true","proper","good","fair","accurate","just","left","moral","lawful"],"dif":"basic","fr":120,"ew":0.3,"it":"logical","rp":"high","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"general","spr":"modifier","dl":["noun","verb","adverb"],"co":["the","all","you","that","is","away","now","very","turn","have","just","here"],"st":["correctness","direction","rights","morality"],"cv":["correctness adjective","direction adjective","noun (entitlement)","adverb use"],"su":["modifier"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"should","ph":"/ʃʊd/","pos":"auxiliary verb","gr":"predicate","rt":"shall","fam":["shall","should've","shouldn't"],"pl":"","tn":[],"hi":"चाहिए","en":"used to express obligation, expectation, or advice","ds":"Used to express duty, expectation, or advice about what is right.","dd":"'Should' is the past tense of 'shall' but functions mainly as a modal auxiliary expressing obligation or duty ('you should work hard'), expectation ('it should be ready by now'), advice ('you should see a doctor'), and conditional ('if you should see her'). It is less strong than 'must'.","ex":"You should always be honest with people around you.","exh":"आपको हमेशा अपने आस-पास के लोगों के साथ ईमानदार रहना चाहिए।","syl":["should"],"syn":["ought to","must","have to","need to","be expected to","be advised to"],"ant":["shouldn't","need not","must not","are not required to"],"rel":["must","ought to","have to","need to","may","might","could","would","shall"],"dif":"basic","fr":121,"ew":0.1,"it":"action","rp":"high","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"general","spr":"auxiliary","dl":["subject","verb"],"co":["I","you","we","they","he","she","be","do","have","go","know","try","always"],"st":["obligation","duty","advice","expectation","recommendation"],"cv":["obligation use","advice use","expectation use","conditional use"],"su":["auxiliary","predicate"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"while","ph":"/waɪl/","pos":"conjunction","gr":"connector","rt":"while","fam":["meanwhile","worthwhile","awhile","while-away"],"pl":"","tn":[],"hi":"जबकि/जब/समय के दौरान","en":"during the time that; at the same time as; although","ds":"During a period of time; at the same time as something else.","dd":"'While' as a conjunction indicates simultaneous events ('she sang while she cooked'), contrast ('while I understand, I disagree'), and duration ('wait a while'). As a noun it refers to a period of time. As a verb it means to pass time idly ('while away the hours').","ex":"She listened to music while completing her morning exercise routine.","exh":"उसने अपनी सुबह की व्यायाम दिनचर्या पूरी करते हुए संगीत सुना।","syl":["while"],"syn":["during","as","when","at the same time","although","whereas","whilst","meantime"],"ant":["then","after","later","not at the same time"],"rel":["during","as","when","meanwhile","although","whereas","although","at the same time"],"dif":"basic","fr":122,"ew":0.0,"it":"relational","rp":"medium","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"time","spr":"connector","dl":["clause","verb"],"co":["I","she","he","we","they","wait","still","some","a","this","away"],"st":["simultaneity","duration","contrast","time"],"cv":["simultaneous events use","contrast use","noun use (a while)"],"su":["connector"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"those","ph":"/ðoʊz/","pos":"determiner","gr":"modifier","rt":"that","fam":["this","these","that","the"],"pl":"","tn":[],"hi":"वे/वह (दूर)","en":"plural form of that; referring to distant things","ds":"Refers to multiple specific people or things farther away or previously mentioned.","dd":"'Those' is the plural of 'that', used as a demonstrative determiner ('those books') and pronoun ('I prefer those'). It indicates items that are farther from the speaker or have been previously discussed, contrasting with 'these' which indicates items nearby.","ex":"Those were the best years of her entire professional life.","exh":"वे उसके पूरे पेशेवर जीवन के सबसे अच्छे साल थे।","syl":["those"],"syn":["the former","the mentioned","the distant","such","that group"],"ant":["these","this","here","nearby"],"rel":["that","these","this","the","such","there","then","others"],"dif":"basic","fr":123,"ew":0.0,"it":"relational","rp":"medium","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"general","spr":"modifier","dl":["noun"],"co":["are","were","days","people","who","that","the","my","years","early","times"],"st":["distance","plurality","demonstration","reference"],"cv":["far proximity use","previously mentioned reference use","plural demonstrative"],"su":["modifier","pronoun"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"both","ph":"/boʊθ/","pos":"determiner","gr":"modifier","rt":"both","fam":[],"pl":"","tn":[],"hi":"दोनों","en":"the one and the other; the two","ds":"Used to refer to two people or things, considered together.","dd":"'Both' indicates two people or things together ('both students passed'). As a conjunction in 'both...and', it emphasizes that each of two things is true ('both clever and kind'). It is used with plural nouns and verbs. It contrasts with 'either' (one or the other) and 'neither' (not one or the other).","ex":"Both candidates presented very strong arguments in the debate.","exh":"दोनों उम्मीदवारों ने बहस में बहुत मजबूत तर्क प्रस्तुत किए।","syl":["both"],"syn":["the two","each","the pair","one and the other","the duo"],"ant":["neither","one","only one"],"rel":["each","either","neither","two","pair","together","all","everyone"],"dif":"basic","fr":124,"ew":0.0,"it":"informational","rp":"medium","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"general","spr":"modifier","dl":["noun","clause"],"co":["of","them","sides","parties","you","we","can","have","are","were"],"st":["pair","totality","two","coordination"],"cv":["determiner use","'both...and' conjunction use","pronoun use"],"su":["modifier","determiner"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"however","ph":"/haʊˈɛvər/","pos":"adverb","gr":"connector","rt":"however","fam":["how","whatever","wherever","whenever","whoever"],"pl":"","tn":[],"hi":"हालाँकि/फिर भी","en":"despite that; in whatever way","ds":"Used to introduce a contrast or exception to what has just been said.","dd":"'However' is a conjunctive adverb introducing contrast ('She was tired; however, she kept working') and a relative adverb meaning 'in whatever way' ('Do it however you like'). As a sentence connector it is separated by semicolons or periods, unlike 'but' which connects within a sentence.","ex":"The task was difficult; however, she completed it on time.","exh":"काम मुश्किल था; हालाँकि, उसने इसे समय पर पूरा किया।","syl":["how","ev","er"],"syn":["nevertheless","nonetheless","yet","still","but","despite that","although","that said","all the same"],"ant":["therefore","consequently","so","thus","as a result"],"rel":["but","yet","still","nevertheless","nonetheless","despite","although","though","even so"],"dif":"intermediate","fr":125,"ew":0.0,"it":"logical","rp":"high","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"general","spr":"connector","dl":["clause","sentence"],"co":["I","she","he","we","they","it","this","that","the","always","seems"],"st":["contrast","concession","qualification","discourse"],"cv":["contrast connector","'however you like' (relative)","formal contrast use"],"su":["connector"],"wuc":["writing","formal","informal","daily conversation"]},
    {"w":"three","ph":"/θriː/","pos":"numeral","gr":"modifier","rt":"three","fam":["triple","trio","third","thrice","thirteen","thirty","triangle"],"pl":"","tn":[],"hi":"तीन","en":"the number 3","ds":"The number 3; one more than two.","dd":"'Three' is the cardinal number 3. It counts three items and appears in many cultural and symbolic uses: 'three-dimensional', 'the rule of three' in writing, 'three strikes'. The ordinal form is 'third' and the adverb form is 'thrice' (three times).","ex":"She has three older siblings who all live in different cities.","exh":"उसके तीन बड़े भाई-बहन हैं जो सभी अलग-अलग शहरों में रहते हैं।","syl":["three"],"syn":["trio","triple","triad","threesome"],"ant":["one","two","four"],"rel":["one","two","four","five","triple","third","thrice","trio","triangle"],"dif":"basic","fr":126,"ew":0.0,"it":"informational","rp":"medium","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"general","spr":"modifier","dl":["noun"],"co":["of","the","days","years","times","hours","people","more","than","over"],"st":["number","quantity","trio","third"],"cv":["counting use","ordinal (third)","compound use"],"su":["modifier","subject"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"off","ph":"/ɒf/","pos":"adverb","gr":"modifier","rt":"off","fam":["offset","offshore","offline","offside","offload","offhand","off-topic","turnoff"],"pl":"","tn":[],"hi":"बंद/दूर/अलग","en":"away from a place or position; not functioning","ds":"Away from a surface or position; not operating or functioning.","dd":"'Off' indicates separation ('take off your shoes'), removal ('off the hook'), distance ('far off'), inactivity ('switch off'), cancellation ('the event is off'), and is extremely productive in phrasal verbs ('put off', 'take off', 'turn off', 'set off', 'go off'). Its antonym is 'on'.","ex":"She turned off the lights before leaving the room tonight.","exh":"आज रात कमरा छोड़ने से पहले उसने लाइटें बंद कर दीं।","syl":["off"],"syn":["away","aside","discontinued","separated","removed","absent","inactive","not on"],"ant":["on","functioning","active","attached","near","present"],"rel":["on","away","apart","removed","absent","inactive","distant","outside","disconnected"],"dif":"basic","fr":127,"ew":0.0,"it":"descriptive","rp":"medium","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"general","spr":"modifier","dl":["verb","noun"],"co":["turn","put","take","go","set","cut","drop","keep","fall","stay","switch","run"],"st":["separation","inactivity","distance","removal","cancellation"],"cv":["separation use","inactivity use","phrasal verb use"],"su":["modifier","preposition"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","informal"]},
    {"w":"always","ph":"/ˈɔːlweɪz/","pos":"adverb","gr":"modifier","rt":"always","fam":["all","ever","forever","every","usually","whenever"],"pl":"","tn":[],"hi":"हमेशा","en":"at all times; on every occasion; repeatedly","ds":"On every occasion; all the time; constantly.","dd":"'Always' is the strongest frequency adverb, meaning 'on all occasions' or 'at all times'. It appears before the main verb ('I always eat breakfast') but after auxiliaries ('She has always worked hard'). It expresses habit, certainty, and permanence. Its antonym is 'never' and it contrasts with 'usually', 'sometimes'.","ex":"She always arrives at work before anyone else in the office.","exh":"वह हमेशा दफ्तर में किसी भी और से पहले काम पर पहुँचती है।","syl":["al","ways"],"syn":["forever","constantly","perpetually","every time","invariably","ever","continuously","at all times"],"ant":["never","rarely","seldom","occasionally","sometimes"],"rel":["ever","constantly","forever","usually","often","habitually","regularly","invariably"],"dif":"basic","fr":128,"ew":0.1,"it":"informational","rp":"high","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"time","spr":"modifier","dl":["verb"],"co":["I","she","he","we","they","have","will","be","do","try","want","remember"],"st":["frequency","habit","permanence","certainty"],"cv":["frequency adverb use","emphasis use"],"su":["modifier"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"seem","ph":"/siːm/","pos":"verb","gr":"predicate","rt":"seem","fam":["seems","seemed","seeming","seemingly","seemly"],"pl":"","tn":["seem","seems","seemed","seeming"],"hi":"लगना/प्रतीत होना","en":"to give the impression of being something","ds":"To give the impression or appearance of having a certain quality.","dd":"'Seem' is a linking verb expressing appearance or impression ('she seems happy', 'it seems like rain'). Unlike 'be', 'seem' implies the speaker is not certain of the true state. It is followed by an adjective ('seems tired'), a noun phrase ('seems a good idea'), or an infinitive ('seems to be working').","ex":"Everything seems to be working perfectly in the new system.","exh":"नई प्रणाली में सब कुछ बिल्कुल ठीक काम करता लगता है।","syl":["seem"],"syn":["appear","look","feel","sound","come across as","strike one as","be apparently","look like"],"ant":["be definitely","actually be","certainly is"],"rel":["appear","look","feel","sound","strike","prove","turn out","suggest","indicate"],"dif":"basic","fr":129,"ew":0.1,"it":"descriptive","rp":"medium","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"general","spr":"verb","dl":["subject","adjective","infinitive","clause"],"co":["to","be","like","a","good","clear","right","obvious","strange","happy","fine"],"st":["appearance","impression","uncertainty","linking verb"],"cv":["linking verb use","impersonal use ('it seems')","with infinitive"],"su":["predicate"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"since","ph":"/sɪns/","pos":"preposition","gr":"connector","rt":"since","fam":[],"pl":"","tn":[],"hi":"से (तब से)/क्योंकि","en":"from a past time until now; because","ds":"From a point in the past until now; as a result of the fact that.","dd":"'Since' as a preposition marks a starting point continuing to now ('since 2010'). As a conjunction it introduces a time clause ('since she left') or a causal clause ('since you insist'). It is used with perfect tenses when marking duration from the past. It contrasts with 'for' which marks duration only.","ex":"She has been learning Spanish since she was a young child.","exh":"वह बचपन से स्पैनिश सीख रही है।","syl":["since"],"syn":["from","ever since","because","as","given that","seeing as","ever after","ago"],"ant":["until","till","before","up to"],"rel":["because","as","from","after","ago","ever since","for","during","when"],"dif":"basic","fr":130,"ew":0.0,"it":"relational","rp":"medium","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"time","spr":"connector","dl":["time expression","clause","noun"],"co":["then","I","she","he","we","they","last","the","long","recently","early"],"st":["time duration","causation","reference point"],"cv":["time use (with present perfect)","causal use"],"su":["preposition","connector"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"show","ph":"/ʃoʊ/","pos":"verb","gr":"predicate","rt":"show","fam":["shows","showed","shown","showing","showcase","showroom","showtime","showdown"],"pl":"","tn":["show","shows","showed","shown","showing"],"hi":"दिखाना/प्रदर्शन","en":"to make visible; to demonstrate or prove","ds":"To make something visible or known; to demonstrate or prove.","dd":"'Show' as a verb means to make visible ('show your work'), demonstrate ('show how it works'), prove ('evidence shows'), and lead ('show someone around'). As a noun it refers to a performance or presentation. Its irregular past participle is 'shown' (also 'showed' as past participle).","ex":"She will show the new students around the campus tomorrow.","exh":"वह कल नए छात्रों को परिसर में घुमाएगी।","syl":["show"],"syn":["display","demonstrate","exhibit","reveal","present","prove","indicate","guide","lead"],"ant":["hide","conceal","cover","obscure","disguise","suppress"],"rel":["display","demonstrate","reveal","exhibit","prove","indicate","point","guide","present"],"dif":"basic","fr":131,"ew":0.1,"it":"action","rp":"medium","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"action","spr":"verb","dl":["subject","object","indirect object"],"co":["me","you","him","her","them","us","how","where","what","around","up","off"],"st":["visibility","demonstration","proof","performance"],"cv":["make visible use","demonstrate use","performance noun use"],"su":["predicate"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"side","ph":"/saɪd/","pos":"noun","gr":"subject","rt":"side","fam":["sides","sideline","alongside","insider","outside","sidewalk","sideway","broadside","alongside"],"pl":"sides","tn":[],"hi":"पक्ष/तरफ/किनारा","en":"a surface of an object; a position or perspective","ds":"One of the surfaces, edges, or aspects of something; a perspective.","dd":"'Side' means a surface ('the side of the box'), position ('the left side'), team or party ('whose side are you on?'), an aspect ('the funny side'), and in math/geometry a line of a shape. In idioms: 'on the safe side', 'take sides', 'side by side'.","ex":"She always looks at both sides of every argument carefully.","exh":"वह हमेशा हर तर्क के दोनों पक्षों को ध्यान से देखती है।","syl":["side"],"syn":["edge","face","aspect","perspective","part","section","flank","party","faction","direction"],"ant":["center","middle","front","back","top","bottom","whole"],"rel":["face","edge","surface","aspect","part","position","direction","team","perspective"],"dif":"basic","fr":132,"ew":0.0,"it":"informational","rp":"medium","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"general","spr":"subject","dl":["verb","adjective","preposition"],"co":["both","each","other","bright","funny","dark","right","left","positive","negative"],"st":["geometry","position","perspective","party","surface"],"cv":["physical surface use","perspective use","team use","idiomatic use"],"su":["subject","object"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"being","ph":"/ˈbiːɪŋ/","pos":"verb","gr":"predicate","rt":"be","fam":["be","am","is","are","was","were","been"],"pl":"","tn":[],"hi":"होना/प्राणी","en":"present participle of be; existence; a living thing","ds":"The present participle of 'be'; existence; a living creature.","dd":"'Being' is the present participle of 'be', used in continuous tenses ('she is being careful') and passive constructions ('being chosen'). As a noun it refers to existence ('the nature of being') or a living creature ('a human being'). In gerund use: 'being late is rude'.","ex":"Being kind to others is one of the most important values.","exh":"दूसरों के प्रति दयालु होना सबसे महत्वपूर्ण मूल्यों में से एक है।","syl":["be","ing"],"syn":["existence","creature","entity","living thing","nature","person","organism"],"ant":["non-existence","nothing","void","nothingness"],"rel":["existence","entity","creature","person","soul","self","living","consciousness"],"dif":"basic","fr":133,"ew":0.2,"it":"relational","rp":"medium","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"general","spr":"verb","dl":["subject","adjective","noun"],"co":["human","well","kind","aware","careful","able","part of","good","honest"],"st":["existence","state","gerund","present participle"],"cv":["present participle use","gerund use","noun use (entity)"],"su":["predicate","subject (gerund)"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"late","ph":"/leɪt/","pos":"adjective","gr":"modifier","rt":"late","fam":["later","latest","lately","belated","overdue","latecomer"],"pl":"","tn":[],"hi":"देर/देर से","en":"after the expected or proper time; toward the end of a period","ds":"After the expected time; happening or arriving after the usual time.","dd":"'Late' as an adjective means after the expected time ('late arrival'), toward the end of a period ('late afternoon', 'late 19th century'), or recently deceased ('the late president'). As an adverb it means after the scheduled time ('she arrived late'). The comparative is 'later' and superlative 'latest'.","ex":"She arrived late to the meeting because of heavy traffic.","exh":"भारी यातायात के कारण वह बैठक में देर से पहुँची।","syl":["late"],"syn":["delayed","overdue","tardy","belated","behind schedule","past due","slow","toward the end"],"ant":["early","on time","punctual","prompt","ahead","timely"],"rel":["early","later","overdue","delayed","behind","afternoon","evening","night","recent"],"dif":"basic","fr":134,"ew":0.1,"it":"descriptive","rp":"medium","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"time","spr":"modifier","dl":["noun","verb"],"co":["too","very","rather","quite","a little","stay up","work","come","arrive","home"],"st":["time","delay","lateness","end period","deceased"],"cv":["delay adjective","time period use","deceased use","adverb use"],"su":["modifier"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"next","ph":"/nɛkst/","pos":"adjective","gr":"modifier","rt":"next","fam":["nearest"],"pl":"","tn":[],"hi":"अगला/अगले","en":"immediately following in time, order, or space","ds":"Coming immediately after in sequence, time, or space.","dd":"'Next' indicates the item immediately following in a sequence ('the next page'), in time ('next week'), or in space ('the next house'). It can also mean 'nearest' ('the next town'). The expression 'next to' means 'beside' or 'almost' ('next to nothing'). As an adverb it means 'after this'.","ex":"She will start her new course next Monday morning.","exh":"वह अगले सोमवार सुबह अपना नया पाठ्यक्रम शुरू करेगी।","syl":["next"],"syn":["following","subsequent","coming","upcoming","succeeding","nearest","closest","adjoining"],"ant":["previous","last","prior","preceding","former","past"],"rel":["following","previous","last","after","then","upcoming","coming","adjacent","beside"],"dif":"basic","fr":135,"ew":0.0,"it":"relational","rp":"medium","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"time","spr":"modifier","dl":["noun","time expression"],"co":["to","week","year","day","month","time","step","one","door","move","turn"],"st":["sequence","proximity","time","adjacency"],"cv":["sequential adjective","temporal adjective","'next to' (beside)"],"su":["modifier"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"open","ph":"/ˈoʊpən/","pos":"adjective","gr":"modifier","rt":"open","fam":["opens","opened","opening","openly","openly","reopen","openness","open-minded","open-ended"],"pl":"","tn":["open","opens","opened","opening"],"hi":"खुला/खोलना","en":"not closed; accessible; to make accessible","ds":"Not closed or sealed; accessible; to make something accessible.","dd":"'Open' as an adjective means not closed ('open door'), accessible ('open to ideas'), frank ('open discussion'), and unsettled ('open question'). As a verb it means to make accessible ('open a window'). Many expressions: 'open-minded', 'in the open', 'open to interpretation', 'an open secret'.","ex":"She opened the window to let in some fresh morning air.","exh":"उसने सुबह की ताजी हवा लेने के लिए खिड़की खोली।","syl":["o","pen"],"syn":["unlocked","accessible","available","frank","candid","clear","public","free","unfastened"],"ant":["closed","shut","locked","restricted","secret","hidden","unavailable","blocked"],"rel":["unlock","accessible","clear","free","public","frank","available","start","begin"],"dif":"basic","fr":136,"ew":0.2,"it":"action","rp":"medium","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"general","spr":"modifier","dl":["noun","verb"],"co":["door","window","eyes","mind","heart","up","book","business","arms","question"],"st":["accessibility","openness","honesty","beginning"],"cv":["physical open adjective","metaphorical open (frank)","verb use","compound adjective use"],"su":["modifier","predicate"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"stand","ph":"/stænd/","pos":"verb","gr":"predicate","rt":"stand","fam":["stands","stood","standing","standout","standoff","standard","understand","bystander","withstand","grandstand"],"pl":"","tn":["stand","stands","stood","standing"],"hi":"खड़े होना/सहना","en":"to be in an upright position; to tolerate","ds":"To be on one's feet in an upright position; to tolerate or endure.","dd":"'Stand' means to be upright on one's feet ('stand up'), to remain stationary ('stand aside'), to tolerate ('I can't stand the noise'), to be valid ('the rule still stands'), and to represent ('the letters stand for'). Its irregular past tense is 'stood'. Many phrasal verbs: 'stand up', 'stand for', 'stand out'.","ex":"She stood at the podium and delivered a powerful speech.","exh":"वह मंच पर खड़ी हुई और एक शक्तिशाली भाषण दिया।","syl":["stand"],"syn":["rise","be upright","get up","remain","endure","tolerate","withstand","represent","exist"],"ant":["sit","lie down","fall","kneel","refuse to tolerate","collapse"],"rel":["sit","lie","rise","stay","remain","upright","position","tolerate","resist","endure"],"dif":"basic","fr":137,"ew":0.1,"it":"action","rp":"medium","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"action","spr":"verb","dl":["subject","object","preposition"],"co":["up","out","for","by","against","firm","still","tall","a chance","in line"],"st":["posture","resistance","validity","representation"],"cv":["physical posture use","toleration use","validity use","representation use"],"su":["predicate"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"read","ph":"/riːd/","pos":"verb","gr":"predicate","rt":"read","fam":["reads","read","reading","reader","readable","reread","proofreader","well-read"],"pl":"","tn":["read","reads","read","reading"],"hi":"पढ़ना","en":"to look at and comprehend written text","ds":"To look at and understand written or printed words.","dd":"'Read' means to comprehend written text ('read a book'), interpret ('read a situation'), recite aloud ('read to children'), and register on a device ('the meter reads 100'). Its past tense and past participle 'read' is pronounced /rɛd/ — the same spelling but different pronunciation. 'Well-read' means widely educated through books.","ex":"She reads at least one new book every week without fail.","exh":"वह बिना नागा किए हर हफ्ते कम से कम एक नई किताब पढ़ती है।","syl":["read"],"syn":["peruse","study","scan","browse","skim","comprehend","decipher","interpret","go through"],"ant":["write","ignore","illiterate","skip"],"rel":["write","study","learn","understand","book","text","letter","comprehend","interpret"],"dif":"basic","fr":138,"ew":0.3,"it":"action","rp":"medium","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"action","spr":"verb","dl":["subject","object"],"co":["book","article","story","paper","news","aloud","carefully","quickly","well","through"],"st":["comprehension","literacy","interpretation","learning"],"cv":["text comprehension use","aloud reading use","interpretation use"],"su":["predicate"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"hear","ph":"/hɪr/","pos":"verb","gr":"predicate","rt":"hear","fam":["hears","heard","hearing","hearer","overhear","unheard","earshot"],"pl":"","tn":["hear","hears","heard","hearing"],"hi":"सुनना","en":"to perceive sound with the ears","ds":"To perceive sounds with the ears; to receive information.","dd":"'Hear' means to perceive sound ('I can hear music'), to receive information ('I hear she's leaving'), to listen to and consider ('the judge heard the case'), and to understand ('I hear you'). Unlike 'listen', 'hear' is involuntary. Its irregular past tense is 'heard'.","ex":"She heard a strange noise coming from outside the house.","exh":"उसने घर के बाहर से एक अजीब आवाज़ सुनी।","syl":["hear"],"syn":["listen","perceive","catch","pick up","overhear","learn","discover","understand"],"ant":["miss","ignore","be deaf to","overlook","disregard"],"rel":["listen","perceive","sound","understand","notice","learn","receive","overhear"],"dif":"basic","fr":139,"ew":0.1,"it":"action","rp":"medium","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"action","spr":"verb","dl":["subject","object","clause"],"co":["can","could","I","you","we","from","about","that","saying","music","voice"],"st":["perception","sound","information","involuntary listening"],"cv":["auditory perception use","information receipt use","understand use"],"su":["predicate"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"part","ph":"/pɑːrt/","pos":"noun","gr":"subject","rt":"part","fam":["parts","partial","partly","particle","partner","partition","apartment","department","part-time","counterpart"],"pl":"parts","tn":["part","parts","parted","parting"],"hi":"भाग/हिस्सा/अलग होना","en":"a portion of something; to separate","ds":"A portion or piece of a whole; to separate or divide.","dd":"'Part' as a noun means a portion ('part of the plan'), a role ('play a part'), or a region ('the northern part'). As a verb it means to separate ('they parted ways'). 'Part-time' means less than full hours. Many expressions: 'take part', 'for the most part', 'in part', 'part with'.","ex":"She played an important part in the success of the project.","exh":"उसने परियोजना की सफलता में एक महत्वपूर्ण भूमिका निभाई।","syl":["part"],"syn":["portion","piece","section","segment","component","element","role","share","fraction"],"ant":["whole","all","entirety","total","complete"],"rel":["piece","section","portion","role","share","element","component","fraction","region"],"dif":"basic","fr":140,"ew":0.0,"it":"informational","rp":"medium","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"general","spr":"subject","dl":["verb","adjective","preposition","noun"],"co":["take","the","a","best","large","small","important","greater","major","of"],"st":["portion","role","division","component"],"cv":["portion use","role use","verb use (separate)","'part of' use"],"su":["subject","object"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"much","ph":"/mʌtʃ/","pos":"determiner","gr":"modifier","rt":"much","fam":["more","most","inasmuch","very much"],"pl":"","tn":[],"hi":"बहुत/अधिक (बेशुमार के लिए)","en":"a large amount of; to a great degree","ds":"A large quantity of (uncountable); to a great degree or extent.","dd":"'Much' is used with uncountable nouns ('much water', 'much effort') and as an adverb meaning 'to a great degree' ('much better', 'much appreciated'). In positive sentences it is often replaced by 'a lot', while 'much' is preferred in questions and negatives. Its comparative is 'more' and superlative 'most'.","ex":"She didn't have much time to prepare for the final presentation.","exh":"उसके पास अंतिम प्रस्तुति की तैयारी के लिए ज़्यादा समय नहीं था।","syl":["much"],"syn":["a lot","greatly","a great deal","considerably","extensively","very","to a great degree","substantially"],"ant":["little","a little","slightly","barely","hardly","not much","not very"],"rel":["many","more","most","very","greatly","considerably","a lot","too","so","that"],"dif":"basic","fr":141,"ew":0.0,"it":"informational","rp":"high","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"general","spr":"modifier","dl":["uncountable noun","adjective","adverb"],"co":["so","very","too","how","as","more","better","worse","time","money","work"],"st":["quantity","degree","extent","uncountable"],"cv":["determiner use","adverb use","intensifier use","in questions/negatives"],"su":["modifier","determiner"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"different","ph":"/ˈdɪfrənt/","pos":"adjective","gr":"modifier","rt":"differ","fam":["differently","difference","differ","differing","indifferent","differentiate","differential"],"pl":"","tn":[],"hi":"अलग/भिन्न","en":"not the same as another; unlike in nature or quality","ds":"Not the same; having distinct qualities or nature.","dd":"'Different' means not alike ('a different approach'). It is followed by 'from' in standard English ('different from'), though 'different than' is common in American English and 'different to' in British English. The adverb is 'differently' and the noun 'difference'.","ex":"She uses a completely different approach to solve each problem.","exh":"वह हर समस्या को हल करने के लिए बिल्कुल अलग तरीके का उपयोग करती है।","syl":["dif","fer","ent"],"syn":["unlike","distinct","dissimilar","contrasting","varied","diverse","separate","unique","individual"],"ant":["same","identical","alike","similar","equal","uniform","common"],"rel":["various","diverse","unique","distinct","separate","contrasting","unlike","special","individual"],"dif":"basic","fr":142,"ew":0.0,"it":"descriptive","rp":"medium","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"general","spr":"modifier","dl":["noun","from/than/to"],"co":["very","quite","completely","slightly","very","from","ways","people","views"],"st":["distinction","diversity","contrast","uniqueness"],"cv":["'different from' (standard)","'different than' (AmE)","'different to' (BrE)"],"su":["modifier"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"away","ph":"/əˈweɪ/","pos":"adverb","gr":"modifier","rt":"away","fam":["giveaway","runaway","takeaway","getaway","faraway","gateway"],"pl":"","tn":[],"hi":"दूर/चले जाना","en":"to or at a distance from a place or person","ds":"At a distance; in another direction; from this place.","dd":"'Away' indicates distance or departure from a place ('walked away'), absence ('she is away this week'), removal ('throw away'), and continuing action ('working away'). As an adjective in sports it describes a match played at the opponent's venue ('an away game'). Many phrasal verbs use 'away'.","ex":"She moved away from the city to live in the countryside.","exh":"वह शहर से दूर जाकर ग्रामीण क्षेत्र में रहने लगी।","syl":["a","way"],"syn":["elsewhere","off","gone","distant","far","absent","removed","aside","departing"],"ant":["here","near","close","present","nearby","home","toward","approaching"],"rel":["far","distant","gone","absent","off","leave","depart","move","out","elsewhere"],"dif":"basic","fr":143,"ew":0.0,"it":"descriptive","rp":"medium","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"general","spr":"modifier","dl":["verb"],"co":["go","come","move","run","take","give","throw","put","fly","walk","far","right"],"st":["distance","departure","removal","absence"],"cv":["distance use","departure use","phrasal verb use"],"su":["modifier"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","informal"]},
    {"w":"change","ph":"/tʃeɪndʒ/","pos":"verb","gr":"predicate","rt":"change","fam":["changes","changed","changing","changeable","unchanged","exchange","interchangeable","rearrange","climate change"],"pl":"","tn":["change","changes","changed","changing"],"hi":"बदलना/परिवर्तन","en":"to make or become different; an alteration","ds":"To make or become different; an instance of becoming different.","dd":"'Change' as a verb means to make different ('change a plan'), to become different ('weather changes'), or to replace ('change clothes'). As a noun it refers to the act of becoming different, a substitution, or coins as small currency. 'Change' is central to concepts of transformation and progress.","ex":"She changed her career path after years of careful thinking.","exh":"वर्षों की सोच के बाद उसने अपने करियर का रास्ता बदला।","syl":["change"],"syn":["alter","modify","transform","shift","vary","switch","convert","adjust","amend","revise"],"ant":["keep","maintain","preserve","stay","remain","fix","stabilize","resist"],"rel":["alter","modify","transform","shift","convert","adjust","update","develop","evolve"],"dif":"basic","fr":144,"ew":0.3,"it":"action","rp":"high","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"general","spr":"verb","dl":["subject","object"],"co":["your","the","this","major","big","something","mind","direction","plans","course"],"st":["transformation","alteration","modification","progress"],"cv":["make different use","become different use","noun use (alteration)","money noun use"],"su":["predicate"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"together","ph":"/təˈɡɛðər/","pos":"adverb","gr":"modifier","rt":"together","fam":["altogether","get-together","togetherness"],"pl":"","tn":[],"hi":"साथ में/मिलकर","en":"with each other; in combination; at the same place or time","ds":"With or in proximity to another person or thing; jointly.","dd":"'Together' indicates joint action ('work together'), simultaneous occurrence ('they arrived together'), combined ('tied together'), and as an adjective it means organized and calm ('she's very together'). Many idioms: 'get-together', 'pull together', 'put together', 'together with'.","ex":"They worked together to complete the challenging project on time.","exh":"उन्होंने मिलकर चुनौतीपूर्ण परियोजना को समय पर पूरा किया।","syl":["to","geth","er"],"syn":["jointly","collectively","simultaneously","in unison","as one","combined","cooperatively","unitedly"],"ant":["separately","apart","individually","alone","independently","singularly"],"rel":["jointly","cooperatively","united","with","combined","collective","jointly","as one","team"],"dif":"basic","fr":145,"ew":0.3,"it":"relational","rp":"medium","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"general","spr":"modifier","dl":["verb"],"co":["work","come","go","live","play","stay","pull","put","all","we","let's"],"st":["cooperation","unity","community","combination"],"cv":["joint action use","simultaneous use","'together with' (preposition)"],"su":["modifier"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"keep","ph":"/kiːp/","pos":"verb","gr":"predicate","rt":"keep","fam":["keeps","kept","keeping","keeper","upkeep","bookkeeper","goalkeeper","keep-fit"],"pl":"","tn":["keep","keeps","kept","keeping"],"hi":"रखना/बनाए रखना","en":"to retain or maintain possession of; to continue","ds":"To retain; to continue a state or action; to store.","dd":"'Keep' means to retain ('keep a secret'), maintain a state ('keep clean'), continue ('keep going'), cause to remain ('keep someone waiting'), and store ('keep files'). Its irregular past tense is 'kept'. Many phrasal verbs: 'keep up', 'keep on', 'keep away', 'keep to'. 'Keep' also means a fortress tower.","ex":"She always keeps her promises and never lets people down.","exh":"वह हमेशा अपने वादे निभाती है और कभी लोगों को निराश नहीं करती।","syl":["keep"],"syn":["retain","hold","maintain","continue","preserve","store","save","guard","sustain","manage"],"ant":["lose","release","give up","discard","abandon","relinquish","stop"],"rel":["hold","maintain","preserve","retain","save","guard","store","continue","protect"],"dif":"basic","fr":146,"ew":0.1,"it":"action","rp":"high","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"action","spr":"verb","dl":["subject","object"],"co":["on","up","going","trying","doing","in mind","a secret","promise","record","track"],"st":["retention","maintenance","continuity","storage"],"cv":["retain use","continue use","maintain state use","phrasal verb use"],"su":["predicate"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"word","ph":"/wɜːrd/","pos":"noun","gr":"subject","rt":"word","fam":["words","wordy","wording","wordplay","keyword","password","wordsmith","byword","crossword","password"],"pl":"words","tn":[],"hi":"शब्द","en":"a unit of language; speech or talk","ds":"A unit of language that has meaning; something said.","dd":"'Word' primarily means a unit of spoken or written language ('a three-letter word'). It also refers to speech or communication ('have a word'), a promise ('give your word'), news ('word spread'), and a command ('give the word'). In religious contexts, 'the Word' refers to sacred scripture.","ex":"She chose every word carefully when writing her speech.","exh":"उसने अपना भाषण लिखते समय हर शब्द सावधानी से चुना।","syl":["word"],"syn":["term","expression","utterance","language","statement","promise","news","message","report"],"ant":[],"rel":["language","term","phrase","sentence","text","speech","vocabulary","expression","saying"],"dif":"basic","fr":147,"ew":0.1,"it":"informational","rp":"medium","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"general","spr":"subject","dl":["verb","adjective"],"co":["the","a","good","last","kind","right","hard","key","every","for","in","spread"],"st":["language","unit","communication","promise"],"cv":["language unit use","'a word' (brief conversation)","'give your word' (promise)"],"su":["subject","object"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"put","ph":"/pʊt/","pos":"verb","gr":"predicate","rt":"put","fam":["puts","put","putting","input","output","output","putaway","putdown","throughput"],"pl":"","tn":["put","puts","putting"],"hi":"रखना/डालना","en":"to place something in a position","ds":"To place something in a particular location or position.","dd":"'Put' means to place in a position ('put the book down'), cause to be in a state ('put at risk'), express ('how to put it'), and invest effort ('put in work'). Its past tense is 'put' (unchanged). Extremely productive in phrasal verbs: 'put on', 'put off', 'put up', 'put down', 'put forward'.","ex":"She put all her effort into preparing for the big exam.","exh":"उसने बड़ी परीक्षा की तैयारी में अपनी पूरी मेहनत लगा दी।","syl":["put"],"syn":["place","set","lay","position","locate","arrange","situate","deposit","insert"],"ant":["remove","take out","pick up","extract","withdraw"],"rel":["place","lay","set","position","leave","drop","arrange","insert","push"],"dif":"basic","fr":148,"ew":0.0,"it":"action","rp":"medium","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"action","spr":"verb","dl":["subject","object","destination"],"co":["on","in","up","down","away","forward","off","together","back","out","effort"],"st":["placement","position","expression","investment"],"cv":["physical placement use","state use","expression use","phrasal verb use"],"su":["predicate"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"four","ph":"/fɔːr/","pos":"numeral","gr":"modifier","rt":"four","fam":["fourth","forty","fourteen","foursome","four-wheel"],"pl":"","tn":[],"hi":"चार","en":"the number 4","ds":"The number 4; one more than three.","dd":"'Four' is the cardinal number 4. The ordinal form is 'fourth'. It appears in many expressions and compounds: 'four-leaf clover', 'four-wheel drive', 'on all fours'. 'Forty' and 'fourteen' are derived from 'four'. Many cultures have special significance for the number four.","ex":"She needs to buy four more chairs for her new dining room.","exh":"उसे अपने नए डाइनिंग रूम के लिए चार और कुर्सियाँ खरीदनी हैं।","syl":["four"],"syn":["quartet","foursome","quadruple","tetrad"],"ant":["one","two","three","five"],"rel":["three","five","fourth","forty","fourteen","quarter","quadruple"],"dif":"basic","fr":149,"ew":0.0,"it":"informational","rp":"medium","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"general","spr":"modifier","dl":["noun"],"co":["of","the","days","years","times","hours","people","over","under","than"],"st":["number","quantity","fourth","quadruple"],"cv":["counting use","ordinal (fourth)","compound use"],"su":["modifier","subject"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"help","ph":"/hɛlp/","pos":"verb","gr":"predicate","rt":"help","fam":["helps","helped","helping","helper","helpful","helpless","helpfulness","self-help","helpful"],"pl":"","tn":["help","helps","helped","helping"],"hi":"मदद करना/सहायता","en":"to make it easier for someone to do something","ds":"To assist or support someone in doing something.","dd":"'Help' as a verb means to assist ('help a friend'), make easier ('this will help'), and in informal English can be followed by an infinitive with or without 'to' ('help do' or 'help to do'). As a noun it means assistance ('I need help'). 'Help yourself' means to take what you want. 'Can't help' means unable to control.","ex":"She always helps her younger classmates when they have difficulty.","exh":"वह हमेशा अपने छोटे सहपाठियों की मदद करती है जब उन्हें कठिनाई होती है।","syl":["help"],"syn":["assist","aid","support","guide","facilitate","contribute","enable","serve","back","bolster"],"ant":["hinder","harm","obstruct","prevent","hurt","impede","block","damage"],"rel":["assist","support","aid","guide","serve","contribute","facilitate","encourage","cooperate"],"dif":"basic","fr":150,"ew":0.5,"it":"action","rp":"high","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"action","spr":"verb","dl":["subject","object"],"co":["me","you","him","her","them","us","each other","out","with","I need","can I"],"st":["assistance","support","benefit","service"],"cv":["assist use","'help yourself' (take freely)","'can't help' (unable to avoid)"],"su":["predicate"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"call","ph":"/kɔːl/","pos":"verb","gr":"predicate","rt":"call","fam":["calls","called","calling","caller","callback","recall","outcall","callout","callover","roll call"],"pl":"","tn":["call","calls","called","calling"],"hi":"बुलाना/कहना/फोन करना","en":"to name something; to telephone; to summon","ds":"To give a name to; to telephone; to shout to get attention.","dd":"'Call' means to name ('she is called Anna'), to telephone ('call me tonight'), to shout ('call for help'), to summon ('call a meeting'), and to visit briefly ('call in'). As a noun it refers to a phone call, a shout, or a demand ('a call for action'). 'Call it a day' means to stop working.","ex":"She called her mother every evening after arriving home from work.","exh":"वह हर शाम काम से घर आने के बाद अपनी माँ को फोन करती थी।","syl":["call"],"syn":["name","telephone","phone","ring","shout","summon","designate","title","contact","invite"],"ant":["dismiss","silence","ignore","be silent","whisper"],"rel":["phone","ring","name","shout","summon","contact","invite","address","title"],"dif":"basic","fr":151,"ew":0.2,"it":"action","rp":"high","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"action","spr":"verb","dl":["subject","object","complement"],"co":["me","you","him","her","them","by","the","up","out","back","for","it","phone"],"st":["naming","telephone","summons","vocal communication"],"cv":["naming use","telephone use","summons use","brief visit use"],"su":["predicate"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","informal","command"]},
    {"w":"under","ph":"/ˈʌndər/","pos":"preposition","gr":"connector","rt":"under","fam":["underneath","underway","underground","underline","understand","undermine","underdog","undercover","fundamental"],"pl":"","tn":[],"hi":"के नीचे/में","en":"below or beneath; less than a number or level","ds":"Below the surface or level of something; less than a number.","dd":"'Under' indicates position below something ('under the table'), less than a number ('under thirty'), subordination ('under management'), and ongoing process ('under construction'). Contrasts with 'over' for position and 'above' for level. Many compounds: 'understand', 'underline', 'undermine'.","ex":"She kept her important documents safely under the wooden desk.","exh":"उसने अपने महत्वपूर्ण दस्तावेज लकड़ी की मेज के नीचे सुरक्षित रखे।","syl":["un","der"],"syn":["below","beneath","underneath","less than","subordinate to","subject to","within","during"],"ant":["over","above","more than","beyond","on top of","superior"],"rel":["below","beneath","underneath","down","lower","subordinate","less than","within"],"dif":"basic","fr":152,"ew":0.0,"it":"relational","rp":"medium","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"general","spr":"preposition","dl":["noun","number"],"co":["the","a","this","construction","control","pressure","law","way","contract","cover"],"st":["position","subordination","quantity","process"],"cv":["position use","quantity use","subordination use","process use"],"su":["preposition","connector"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"against","ph":"/əˈɡɛnst/","pos":"preposition","gr":"connector","rt":"against","fam":[],"pl":"","tn":[],"hi":"के खिलाफ/के विरुद्ध","en":"in opposition to; in contact with","ds":"In opposition to; leaning or pressing on the surface of.","dd":"'Against' expresses opposition ('vote against'), physical contact with ('lean against'), contrast ('bright against dark'), comparison ('judged against'), and protection ('insured against'). It always implies some kind of opposition, resistance, or confrontation — physical, competitive, or ideological.","ex":"She always fights against injustice wherever she finds it.","exh":"वह जहाँ भी अन्याय पाती है, उसके विरुद्ध हमेशा लड़ती है।","syl":["a","gainst"],"syn":["opposed to","versus","contrary to","in opposition","in conflict with","in contact with","counter to"],"ant":["for","in support of","in favor of","with","alongside"],"rel":["versus","opposing","contrary to","resist","oppose","compete","fight","confront"],"dif":"basic","fr":153,"ew":0.3,"it":"logical","rp":"medium","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"general","spr":"preposition","dl":["noun","pronoun","opposition verb"],"co":["the","a","vote","fight","lean","push","play","win","work","protest"],"st":["opposition","conflict","contact","resistance"],"cv":["opposition use","physical contact use","contrast use","protection use"],"su":["preposition","connector"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"before","ph":"/bɪˈfɔːr/","pos":"preposition","gr":"connector","rt":"before","fam":["formerly","beforehand","before-mentioned"],"pl":"","tn":[],"hi":"पहले/से पहले","en":"earlier than; in front of; in advance of","ds":"Earlier in time; in front of something; already.","dd":"'Before' as a preposition means earlier than ('before Monday'), in front of ('before the judge'), and in preference to ('honor before wealth'). As a conjunction it introduces a time clause ('before she left'). As an adverb it means 'at a previous time' ('I've seen it before'). Contrasts with 'after'.","ex":"She always reads the instructions before starting any new task.","exh":"वह कोई भी नया काम शुरू करने से पहले हमेशा निर्देश पढ़ती है।","syl":["be","fore"],"syn":["prior to","previously","earlier than","ahead of","in front of","formerly","in advance"],"ant":["after","following","subsequent to","later","behind","past"],"rel":["after","earlier","previous","ahead","prior","formerly","front","advance","already"],"dif":"basic","fr":154,"ew":0.0,"it":"relational","rp":"high","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"time","spr":"connector","dl":["noun","time expression","clause","verb"],"co":["long","I","she","he","we","the","this","that","do","go","leaving","starting"],"st":["time","sequence","anteriority","front position"],"cv":["preposition of time","conjunction of time","adverb use"],"su":["preposition","connector"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"home","ph":"/hoʊm/","pos":"noun","gr":"subject","rt":"home","fam":["homeless","homely","homemade","homecoming","homework","hometown","homeland","homeward","at home"],"pl":"homes","tn":[],"hi":"घर/आवास","en":"the place where one lives; one's country or origin","ds":"The place where a person lives; a place of belonging.","dd":"'Home' refers to the place where one lives ('come home'), one's native land ('home country'), a place of origin for a sports team ('home game'), and metaphorically a comfortable familiar place ('feel at home'). As an adjective 'home' modifies nouns ('home cooking', 'home game'). Many compounds exist.","ex":"She finally returned home after many years working abroad.","exh":"कई साल विदेश में काम करने के बाद वह आखिरकार घर लौट आई।","syl":["home"],"syn":["house","residence","dwelling","abode","household","native land","origin","base","birthplace"],"ant":["away","abroad","foreign","exile","homeless","outside"],"rel":["house","family","place","land","country","city","town","room","shelter","base"],"dif":"basic","fr":155,"ew":0.7,"it":"emotional","rp":"high","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"place","spr":"subject","dl":["verb","adjective"],"co":["come","go","stay","return","leave","at","away from","feel","make","own"],"st":["residence","belonging","origin","family","safety"],"cv":["physical dwelling use","emotional belonging use","'at home' (comfortable)","adjective use"],"su":["subject","object"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"live","ph":"/lɪv/","pos":"verb","gr":"predicate","rt":"live","fam":["lives","lived","living","alive","lively","livelihood","live-in","livestock","outlook","lifelong"],"pl":"","tn":["live","lives","lived","living"],"hi":"जीना/रहना","en":"to be alive; to reside in a place","ds":"To be alive; to reside in a particular place.","dd":"'Live' as a verb (/lɪv/) means to be alive ('every being that lives'), to reside ('she lives in London'), and to experience ('live in fear'). As an adjective (/laɪv/) it means 'not recorded, happening now' ('a live concert') or 'not yet used' ('a live wire'). The pronunciation distinguishes these two meanings.","ex":"She has lived in this city for most of her entire life.","exh":"वह अपने अधिकांश जीवन के लिए इस शहर में रही है।","syl":["live"],"syn":["reside","dwell","stay","inhabit","exist","be alive","experience","breathe","abide"],"ant":["die","move away","depart","leave"],"rel":["life","exist","reside","stay","survive","breathe","experience","inhabit","dwell"],"dif":"basic","fr":156,"ew":0.4,"it":"action","rp":"high","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"action","spr":"verb","dl":["subject","place noun"],"co":["in","here","there","alone","together","long","always","life","nearby","far"],"st":["life","residence","existence","experience"],"cv":["be alive use","reside use","adjective use (live broadcast)"],"su":["predicate"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"small","ph":"/smɔːl/","pos":"adjective","gr":"modifier","rt":"small","fam":["smaller","smallest","smallness","smallish","small-scale","small-minded","small-time"],"pl":"","tn":[],"hi":"छोटा","en":"of limited size; minor or unimportant","ds":"Of a limited size, extent, or amount; not large.","dd":"'Small' describes limited size ('a small room'), minor scale ('a small problem'), and insignificant amount ('a small difference'). It is the informal counterpart of 'little' (with an emotional connotation) and the antonym of 'large' or 'big'. Many compounds: 'small-scale', 'small talk', 'smallpox'.","ex":"She made a small mistake but quickly corrected it herself.","exh":"उसने एक छोटी गलती की लेकिन जल्दी ही उसे खुद सुधार लिया।","syl":["small"],"syn":["little","tiny","minor","limited","compact","slight","petite","narrow","miniature"],"ant":["large","big","great","huge","enormous","significant","major","wide"],"rel":["little","tiny","minor","slight","limited","compact","narrow","short","thin"],"dif":"basic","fr":157,"ew":0.0,"it":"descriptive","rp":"medium","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"general","spr":"modifier","dl":["noun"],"co":["a","very","quite","too","rather","town","business","step","talk","amount"],"st":["size","scale","insignificance","limitation"],"cv":["size adjective","scale adjective","'small talk' (chitchat)"],"su":["modifier"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"number","ph":"/ˈnʌmbər/","pos":"noun","gr":"subject","rt":"number","fam":["numbers","numbered","numbering","numerous","innumerable","enumerable","numeral","numerical"],"pl":"numbers","tn":["number","numbers","numbered","numbering"],"hi":"संख्या/नंबर","en":"a mathematical value; a quantity; an issue of a publication","ds":"A mathematical quantity used to count or measure; a figure.","dd":"'Number' as a noun means a mathematical value ('the number five'), a quantity ('a number of people'), a numeral symbol, and a particular issue of a magazine ('the latest number'). As a verb it means to give numbers to ('numbered the pages') or to amount to ('they numbered fifty').","ex":"She wrote down the exact number of items on her shopping list.","exh":"उसने अपनी शॉपिंग सूची में वस्तुओं की सटीक संख्या लिखी।","syl":["num","ber"],"syn":["figure","digit","numeral","total","count","quantity","amount","tally","integer"],"ant":[],"rel":["figure","digit","count","total","amount","quantity","statistics","numeral","value"],"dif":"basic","fr":158,"ew":0.0,"it":"informational","rp":"medium","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"general","spr":"subject","dl":["verb","adjective"],"co":["large","small","great","total","phone","a","the","growing","limited","increasing"],"st":["quantity","mathematics","numeral","count"],"cv":["mathematical use","quantity use","serial number use","verb use (enumerate)"],"su":["subject","object"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"set","ph":"/sɛt/","pos":"verb","gr":"predicate","rt":"set","fam":["sets","set","setting","reset","setup","offset","onset","mindset","subset","setback","dataset"],"pl":"","tn":["set","sets","setting"],"hi":"रखना/स्थापित करना/समूह","en":"to put in place; a group of things; hardened","ds":"To place or arrange; a collection of related items; to become solid.","dd":"'Set' as a verb means to place ('set the table'), establish ('set a rule'), adjust ('set the alarm'), and harden ('the cement sets'). As a noun it is a collection ('a set of tools'). Note: 'set' is one of the verbs with the same form in present and past tense. Many compounds and phrasal verbs.","ex":"She set a new record in the school's annual athletics competition.","exh":"उसने स्कूल की वार्षिक एथलेटिक्स प्रतियोगिता में एक नया रिकॉर्ड स्थापित किया।","syl":["set"],"syn":["place","put","position","establish","arrange","fix","assign","adjust","determine","solidify"],"ant":["remove","displace","take","cancel","soften"],"rel":["put","place","arrange","establish","fix","adjust","prepare","configure","organize"],"dif":"basic","fr":159,"ew":0.0,"it":"action","rp":"medium","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"action","spr":"verb","dl":["subject","object","destination"],"co":["up","out","aside","back","off","free","record","example","goal","plan","table"],"st":["placement","establishment","collection","hardening"],"cv":["placement use","establishment use","collection noun use","hardening use"],"su":["predicate"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"family","ph":"/ˈfæməli/","pos":"noun","gr":"subject","rt":"family","fam":["families","familial","familiar","family-oriented","extended family"],"pl":"families","tn":[],"hi":"परिवार","en":"a group of related people; parents and children","ds":"A group of people related by blood, marriage, or adoption; parents and children.","dd":"'Family' refers to the basic social unit of parents and children, extended relatives ('the whole family'), groups of related species ('the cat family'), or any close-knit group ('we're like family'). Family can be nuclear (parents + children) or extended (including grandparents, aunts, uncles, etc.).","ex":"Her family always gathers for a big meal on important holidays.","exh":"उसका परिवार हमेशा महत्वपूर्ण त्योहारों पर एक बड़े भोजन के लिए इकट्ठा होता है।","syl":["fam","i","ly"],"syn":["relatives","kin","household","relations","clan","tribe","parents","children","loved ones"],"ant":["strangers","outsiders","non-relatives"],"rel":["parents","children","relatives","home","love","together","bond","support","ancestors"],"dif":"basic","fr":160,"ew":0.8,"it":"emotional","rp":"high","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"person","spr":"subject","dl":["verb","adjective"],"co":["my","her","his","their","our","whole","immediate","extended","close","loving"],"st":["kinship","community","love","social unit","support"],"cv":["nuclear family use","extended family use","metaphorical family (group)"],"su":["subject","object"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"body","ph":"/ˈbɒdi/","pos":"noun","gr":"subject","rt":"body","fam":["bodies","bodily","bodyguard","embodiment","everybody","somebody","nobody","anybody","nobody"],"pl":"bodies","tn":[],"hi":"शरीर/मृतक/समूह","en":"the physical structure of a person or animal","ds":"The complete physical structure of a living organism.","dd":"'Body' refers to the physical structure ('the human body'), a corpse ('a body was found'), a main part ('the body of the document'), a group ('a body of people'), and a celestial object ('a body in space'). As an adjective 'bodily' means relating to the body. Many compounds: 'bodyguard', 'body language'.","ex":"She takes excellent care of her body through exercise and nutrition.","exh":"वह व्यायाम और पोषण के माध्यम से अपने शरीर की बहुत अच्छी देखभाल करती है।","syl":["bod","y"],"syn":["physique","form","figure","frame","torso","person","corpse","group","substance","organization"],"ant":["mind","soul","spirit"],"rel":["mind","soul","spirit","person","health","physical","human","strength","form","fitness"],"dif":"basic","fr":161,"ew":0.2,"it":"informational","rp":"medium","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"person","spr":"subject","dl":["verb","adjective"],"co":["the","human","my","her","his","whole","language","temperature","weight","healthy"],"st":["physical form","organism","group","corpse","substance"],"cv":["human body use","group/organization use","document body use","corpse use"],"su":["subject","object"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"music","ph":"/ˈmjuːzɪk/","pos":"noun","gr":"subject","rt":"music","fam":["musical","musician","musically","musicality","music-lover","classical music","background music"],"pl":"","tn":[],"hi":"संगीत","en":"vocal or instrumental sounds organized in a pleasing way","ds":"Sound organized in a pleasing pattern with melody, rhythm, and harmony.","dd":"'Music' is the art of organizing sound to create pleasing patterns with elements like melody, rhythm, and harmony. It encompasses all genres and traditions from classical to pop. As an uncountable noun it doesn't take a plural. The adjective is 'musical', the person 'musician', and 'musical' can also be a noun (a musical show).","ex":"She listens to classical music every morning while drinking coffee.","exh":"वह हर सुबह कॉफी पीते हुए शास्त्रीय संगीत सुनती है।","syl":["mu","sic"],"syn":["melody","harmony","tune","song","sound","composition","symphony","rhythm","beat","score"],"ant":["noise","silence","discord","cacophony"],"rel":["song","melody","rhythm","tune","instrument","singer","concert","orchestra","beat","harmony"],"dif":"basic","fr":162,"ew":0.8,"it":"emotional","rp":"medium","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"general","spr":"subject","dl":["verb","adjective"],"co":["listen","play","love","classical","pop","rock","background","good","make","beautiful"],"st":["art","sound","emotion","culture","performance"],"cv":["art form use","background use","'face the music' (idiom)"],"su":["subject","object"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    # ── SET 3: words 163-230 ────────────────────────────────────────────────
    {"w":"color","ph":"/ˈkʌlər/","pos":"noun","gr":"subject","rt":"color","fam":["colors","colored","colorful","colorless","discolor","multicolor","watercolor"],"pl":"colors","tn":["color","colors","colored","coloring"],"hi":"रंग","en":"the property of objects producing different sensations on the eye","ds":"A visual property produced by different wavelengths of light; a hue.","dd":"'Color' (American English; 'colour' in British English) refers to the visual property of objects as perceived by light reflection. Primary colors are red, yellow, and blue (traditional) or red, green, and blue (light). As a verb 'color' means to add color to. Metaphorically it means to influence ('colored by bias').","ex":"She chose a bright yellow color to paint her bedroom walls.","exh":"उसने अपने बेडरूम की दीवारें रंगने के लिए चमकीला पीला रंग चुना।","syl":["col","or"],"syn":["hue","shade","tint","tone","pigment","dye","tincture","complexion","coloring","chroma"],"ant":["colorless","transparent","white","black","monochrome"],"rel":["hue","shade","tint","pigment","dye","paint","bright","vivid","spectrum","rainbow"],"dif":"basic","fr":163,"ew":0.3,"it":"descriptive","rp":"medium","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"general","spr":"subject","dl":["verb","adjective"],"co":["bright","dark","light","natural","favorite","red","blue","green","yellow","beautiful"],"st":["visual property","hue","identity","influence","art"],"cv":["visual hue use","verb use (add color)","metaphorical use (influence)"],"su":["subject","object"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"feel","ph":"/fiːl/","pos":"verb","gr":"predicate","rt":"feel","fam":["feels","felt","feeling","feelings","heartfelt","unfelt","touchy-feely"],"pl":"","tn":["feel","feels","felt","feeling"],"hi":"महसूस करना/छूना","en":"to experience an emotion; to perceive by touch","ds":"To be aware of an emotion or physical sensation.","dd":"'Feel' means to experience emotion ('I feel happy'), to perceive by touch ('feel the texture'), to think or believe ('I feel that...'), and to seem ('it feels cold'). Its irregular past tense is 'felt'. The noun 'feeling' refers to an emotion or sensation. 'Feel like' means to want or to seem.","ex":"She felt a sense of pride when she finished the difficult course.","exh":"जब उसने कठिन पाठ्यक्रम पूरा किया तो उसे गर्व की अनुभूति हुई।","syl":["feel"],"syn":["sense","experience","perceive","touch","notice","believe","think","seem","appear","sense"],"ant":["ignore","be numb to","be indifferent"],"rel":["sense","experience","emotion","touch","perceive","think","believe","notice","understand"],"dif":"basic","fr":164,"ew":0.7,"it":"emotional","rp":"high","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"general","spr":"verb","dl":["subject","adjective","object","clause"],"co":["good","bad","like","free","happy","sad","better","worse","ready","comfortable"],"st":["emotion","sensation","perception","opinion"],"cv":["emotion use","touch use","opinion use","linking verb use"],"su":["predicate"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"move","ph":"/muːv/","pos":"verb","gr":"predicate","rt":"move","fam":["moves","moved","moving","movement","mover","moveable","remove","unmoved","commute","motivation"],"pl":"","tn":["move","moves","moved","moving"],"hi":"हिलना/चलना/स्थानांतरित होना","en":"to change position; to affect emotionally","ds":"To go from one place to another; to affect someone emotionally.","dd":"'Move' means to change position ('the car moved'), to transfer ('move to a new city'), to affect emotionally ('the story moved her'), to make a formal proposal ('move a motion'), and as a noun means a strategic action in a game. Many phrasal verbs: 'move on', 'move in', 'move out'.","ex":"She was deeply moved by the heartfelt performance of the singer.","exh":"वह गायक के हार्दिक प्रदर्शन से गहराई से प्रभावित हुई।","syl":["move"],"syn":["shift","transfer","travel","go","relocate","stir","affect","transport","advance","proceed"],"ant":["stay","stop","remain","stand still","be unmoved","halt"],"rel":["go","travel","transfer","shift","advance","proceed","affect","touch","change","progress"],"dif":"basic","fr":165,"ew":0.4,"it":"action","rp":"medium","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"action","spr":"verb","dl":["subject","object","destination"],"co":["on","in","out","away","forward","ahead","quickly","slowly","deeply","freely"],"st":["motion","relocation","emotion","progress"],"cv":["physical motion use","relocation use","emotional use","chess/game move"],"su":["predicate"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"play","ph":"/pleɪ/","pos":"verb","gr":"predicate","rt":"play","fam":["plays","played","playing","player","playground","replay","gameplay","sportsplay","wordplay"],"pl":"","tn":["play","plays","played","playing"],"hi":"खेलना/नाटक","en":"to engage in activities for enjoyment; to perform in a sport","ds":"To engage in games or activities for enjoyment; to perform music or a role.","dd":"'Play' means to engage in games ('play chess'), perform music ('play the guitar'), act a role ('play a character'), and operate a device ('play a video'). As a noun it refers to a theatrical performance ('a Shakespeare play'). Many expressions: 'fair play', 'play safe', 'play a part', 'wordplay'.","ex":"The children love to play outside in the park after school.","exh":"बच्चे स्कूल के बाद पार्क में बाहर खेलना पसंद करते हैं।","syl":["play"],"syn":["game","sport","perform","act","engage","have fun","frolic","amuse","theater"],"ant":["work","study","stop","quit","idle","rest"],"rel":["game","sport","fun","performance","act","music","theater","enjoy","compete","practice"],"dif":"basic","fr":166,"ew":0.6,"it":"action","rp":"medium","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"action","spr":"verb","dl":["subject","game/instrument","with"],"co":["games","music","sport","role","safe","along","around","fair","hard","with","the"],"st":["recreation","performance","sport","music","theater"],"cv":["game use","music performance use","theater use","operate device use"],"su":["predicate"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","informal"]},
    {"w":"night","ph":"/naɪt/","pos":"noun","gr":"subject","rt":"night","fam":["nights","nightly","nighttime","midnight","overnight","fortnight","goodnight","nightmare","nightfall"],"pl":"nights","tn":[],"hi":"रात","en":"the period of darkness between sunset and sunrise","ds":"The period of darkness each day between sunset and sunrise.","dd":"'Night' refers to the period of darkness from dusk to dawn. As an adverb ('nights') it means regularly at nighttime. Many compounds: 'nightmare', 'midnight', 'overnight', 'fortnight' (two weeks, from 'fourteen nights'). Common idioms: 'good night', 'night owl', 'night shift', 'stay the night'.","ex":"She worked late into the night to finish her important report.","exh":"उसने अपनी महत्वपूर्ण रिपोर्ट पूरी करने के लिए रात देर तक काम किया।","syl":["night"],"syn":["evening","darkness","dark","nighttime","dusk","nightfall","midnight","after dark","p.m."],"ant":["day","daytime","morning","daylight","dawn","sunrise","noon","afternoon"],"rel":["day","evening","midnight","dark","dream","sleep","moon","stars","rest","quiet"],"dif":"basic","fr":167,"ew":0.3,"it":"informational","rp":"medium","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"time","spr":"subject","dl":["verb","adjective"],"co":["last","all","late","good","the","long","dark","quiet","cold","peaceful"],"st":["darkness","time","rest","mystery","sleep"],"cv":["time period use","'goodnight' (farewell)","'overnight' compound use"],"su":["subject","object"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"far","ph":"/fɑːr/","pos":"adverb","gr":"modifier","rt":"far","fam":["farther","farthest","further","furthermore","farewell","far-reaching","faraway","so far","far-off"],"pl":"","tn":[],"hi":"दूर","en":"at or to a great distance; much or by a long way","ds":"At a great distance in space or time; to a considerable degree.","dd":"'Far' as an adverb means 'to or at a great distance' ('how far?', 'far away'), 'to a great extent' ('far better'), and 'a long time in the past or future' ('far back'). As an adjective 'far' means distant ('the far side'). 'Farther/further' are comparative forms; 'farthest/furthest' are superlatives.","ex":"She traveled far from home to pursue her dream of studying abroad.","exh":"उसने विदेश में पढ़ाई के अपने सपने को पूरा करने के लिए घर से बहुत दूर यात्रा की।","syl":["far"],"syn":["distant","remote","afar","away","yonder","long way off","a great distance","considerably"],"ant":["near","close","here","nearby","beside","adjacent","proximate"],"rel":["distant","away","remote","beyond","deep","wide","apart","long","extend","reach"],"dif":"basic","fr":168,"ew":0.0,"it":"descriptive","rp":"medium","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"place","spr":"modifier","dl":["verb","adjective","place noun"],"co":["so","how","too","by","thus","very","as","away","better","more","wide"],"st":["distance","extent","degree","futurity"],"cv":["distance adverb use","degree adverb use","adjective use (far side)"],"su":["modifier"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"eye","ph":"/aɪ/","pos":"noun","gr":"subject","rt":"eye","fam":["eyes","eyed","eyeing","eyebrow","eyelid","eyelash","eyeball","eyesight","eyewitness","overview"],"pl":"eyes","tn":[],"hi":"आँख","en":"the organ of sight; visual attention","ds":"The organ used for seeing; attention or observation.","dd":"'Eye' primarily refers to the organ of vision. As a verb it means to look at carefully ('she eyed the situation'). Many idioms: 'eye contact', 'eye-catching', 'keep an eye on', 'see eye to eye', 'bird's-eye view', 'in the public eye'. The plural 'eyes' can mean watchful attention.","ex":"She has a good eye for detail and rarely makes mistakes.","exh":"उसकी विस्तार पर अच्छी नजर है और वह शायद ही कभी गलती करती है।","syl":["eye"],"syn":["sight","gaze","orb","vision","observation","watch","scrutiny","attention","look","perception"],"ant":["blindness","inattention","disregard"],"rel":["sight","see","vision","watch","look","observe","gaze","focus","notice","view"],"dif":"basic","fr":169,"ew":0.2,"it":"informational","rp":"medium","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"person","spr":"subject","dl":["verb","adjective"],"co":["the","her","his","bright","sharp","good","blue","green","catch","keep","contact"],"st":["vision","organ","observation","attention"],"cv":["body part use","attention use","'eye for' (talent for something)"],"su":["subject","object"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"question","ph":"/ˈkwɛstʃən/","pos":"noun","gr":"subject","rt":"question","fam":["questions","questioned","questioning","questionnaire","unquestionable","questionable"],"pl":"questions","tn":["question","questions","questioned","questioning"],"hi":"प्रश्न/सवाल","en":"a sentence asking for information; to ask or doubt","ds":"A statement used to obtain information; to ask or express doubt.","dd":"'Question' as a noun is a sentence requesting information ('ask a question'), a matter being considered ('the question of climate'), and a doubt ('no question of guilt'). As a verb it means to ask ('the police questioned him') and to doubt ('I question whether it's true'). 'Question mark' is the ? punctuation.","ex":"She raised an interesting question during the morning team meeting.","exh":"उसने सुबह की टीम बैठक के दौरान एक दिलचस्प सवाल उठाया।","syl":["ques","tion"],"syn":["inquiry","query","interrogation","problem","issue","matter","doubt","challenge","topic","point"],"ant":["answer","reply","response","solution","certainty"],"rel":["answer","problem","issue","topic","debate","matter","ask","inquiry","challenge"],"dif":"basic","fr":170,"ew":0.3,"it":"informational","rp":"high","cs":"any","dc":"question","td":"general","spr":"subject","dl":["verb","adjective"],"co":["good","important","interesting","difficult","key","open","ask","answer","raise","debate"],"st":["inquiry","information","doubt","matter","interrogation"],"cv":["interrogative sentence use","verb use (interrogate)","doubt use"],"su":["subject","object"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"again","ph":"/əˈɡɛn/","pos":"adverb","gr":"modifier","rt":"again","fam":["against","yet again","once again","time and again"],"pl":"","tn":[],"hi":"फिर से","en":"another time; returning to a previous state","ds":"One more time; returning to a previous state or activity.","dd":"'Again' means 'one more time' or 'returning to a previous state' ('start again', 'she's healthy again'). Combined with 'never' it means 'not at any future time' ('never again'). 'Once again' emphasizes repetition. 'Again and again' means repeatedly. It commonly follows the verb it modifies.","ex":"She tried the difficult recipe again and it turned out perfect.","exh":"उसने मुश्किल रेसिपी फिर से आजमाई और यह बिल्कुल सही बनी।","syl":["a","gain"],"syn":["once more","another time","anew","afresh","over","over again","in return","additionally"],"ant":["never again","not anymore","only once","for the first time"],"rel":["once","more","repeat","return","redo","recur","another","over","back","fresh"],"dif":"basic","fr":171,"ew":0.1,"it":"informational","rp":"high","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"general","spr":"modifier","dl":["verb"],"co":["try","once","never","start","do","say","come","go","think","then","there"],"st":["repetition","return","continuation"],"cv":["repetition use","return to state use","'once again' emphasis use"],"su":["modifier"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"try","ph":"/traɪ/","pos":"verb","gr":"predicate","rt":"try","fam":["tries","tried","trying","trial","tryout","retry","enterprise","country"],"pl":"","tn":["try","tries","tried","trying"],"hi":"कोशिश करना","en":"to make an effort to do something","ds":"To make an effort or attempt to do something.","dd":"'Try' means to make an effort ('try your best'), to test ('try a new method'), to sample ('try the food'), and in legal terms to bring a case before a judge ('try a case'). The idiom 'try on' means to test clothing. 'Tried and tested' means proven to work.","ex":"She always tries her best no matter how challenging the task is.","exh":"वह हमेशा अपना सर्वश्रेष्ठ प्रयास करती है चाहे काम कितना भी चुनौतीपूर्ण हो।","syl":["try"],"syn":["attempt","endeavor","strive","aim","effort","test","experiment","seek","have a go","essay"],"ant":["give up","quit","surrender","succeed without effort","not bother"],"rel":["attempt","effort","test","experiment","aim","strive","practice","persist","manage","achieve"],"dif":"basic","fr":172,"ew":0.3,"it":"action","rp":"high","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"action","spr":"verb","dl":["subject","infinitive","object"],"co":["to","again","hard","your best","out","on","always","never","please","just"],"st":["effort","attempt","testing","persistence"],"cv":["effort use","test/sample use","legal use"],"su":["predicate"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"tell","ph":"/tɛl/","pos":"verb","gr":"predicate","rt":"tell","fam":["tells","told","telling","teller","retell","storytelling","telltale","forecast"],"pl":"","tn":["tell","tells","told","telling"],"hi":"बताना/कहना","en":"to communicate information; to instruct","ds":"To communicate information or give instructions to someone.","dd":"'Tell' means to communicate ('tell a story'), to instruct ('tell someone to do'), to distinguish ('tell the difference'), and to reveal ('time will tell'). Its irregular past tense is 'told'. Contrasts with 'say' (direct quotation focus) and 'speak' (skill/language focus). 'Tell off' means to reprimand.","ex":"She told her students the importance of reading every single day.","exh":"उसने अपने छात्रों को हर एक दिन पढ़ने के महत्व के बारे में बताया।","syl":["tell"],"syn":["inform","say","communicate","narrate","report","reveal","describe","explain","instruct","order"],"ant":["hide","conceal","keep secret","withhold","stay silent"],"rel":["say","speak","inform","explain","narrate","instruct","reveal","report","announce","confess"],"dif":"basic","fr":173,"ew":0.1,"it":"action","rp":"high","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"action","spr":"verb","dl":["subject","object","indirect object","clause"],"co":["me","you","him","her","them","us","the truth","story","time","what","how","whether"],"st":["communication","information","narration","instruction"],"cv":["communication use","narration use","distinction use ('can you tell?')"],"su":["predicate"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"boy","ph":"/bɔɪ/","pos":"noun","gr":"subject","rt":"boy","fam":["boys","boyhood","boyish","tomboy","boyfriend","newsboy","playboy","old boy","boy scout"],"pl":"boys","tn":[],"hi":"लड़का","en":"a male child or young man","ds":"A male child; a son; a young man.","dd":"'Boy' refers to a male child ('a young boy'), a son ('that's my boy'), an informal term for a man in certain contexts ('the boys at work'), and a servant or subordinate in older usage (now considered offensive). 'Boyfriend' means a romantic male partner. 'Old boy' refers to a former student.","ex":"The boy carefully built a tower of colorful wooden blocks.","exh":"लड़के ने ध्यान से रंगीन लकड़ी के ब्लॉकों का एक टॉवर बनाया।","syl":["boy"],"syn":["male child","lad","youth","youngster","kid","son","young man","junior"],"ant":["girl","woman","female child"],"rel":["child","son","man","youth","lad","friend","teenager","youth","young","male"],"dif":"basic","fr":174,"ew":0.2,"it":"informational","rp":"medium","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"person","spr":"subject","dl":["verb","adjective"],"co":["young","little","old","good","bad","the","my","her","their","small","school"],"st":["male","youth","child","son","person"],"cv":["male child use","informal man use","'boy scout' use"],"su":["subject","object"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","informal"]},
    {"w":"follow","ph":"/ˈfɒloʊ/","pos":"verb","gr":"predicate","rt":"follow","fam":["follows","followed","following","follower","follow-up","unfollow","following"],"pl":"","tn":["follow","follows","followed","following"],"hi":"अनुसरण करना/पीछे चलना","en":"to come or go after; to obey or subscribe to","ds":"To go after someone; to obey instructions; to understand.","dd":"'Follow' means to go after ('follow the path'), to come after in sequence ('spring follows winter'), to obey ('follow orders'), to understand ('can you follow?'), and to subscribe to ('follow on social media'). Many phrasal verbs: 'follow up', 'follow through', 'follow along'.","ex":"She decided to follow her passion for art despite others' doubts.","exh":"उसने दूसरों के संदेह के बावजूद कला के प्रति अपने जुनून का अनुसरण करने का फैसला किया।","syl":["fol","low"],"syn":["trail","pursue","obey","succeed","subscribe","come after","track","accompany","adhere to","heed"],"ant":["lead","precede","disobey","ignore","go before","resist","unsubscribe"],"rel":["lead","trail","pursue","obey","succeed","track","adhere","understand","subscribe","accompany"],"dif":"basic","fr":175,"ew":0.2,"it":"action","rp":"high","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"action","spr":"verb","dl":["subject","object","through/up"],"co":["me","the","rules","up","through","along","your","lead","path","order","dream"],"st":["pursuit","obedience","succession","understanding","social media"],"cv":["physical following use","obey use","succeed in sequence use","social media use"],"su":["predicate"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"room","ph":"/ruːm/","pos":"noun","gr":"subject","rt":"room","fam":["rooms","roomy","bedroom","bathroom","classroom","living room","dining room","roommate","elbow room"],"pl":"rooms","tn":[],"hi":"कमरा/जगह","en":"a part of a building enclosed by walls; space","ds":"An enclosed area within a building; available space.","dd":"'Room' refers to an enclosed space in a building ('the living room'), available space or scope ('room to grow', 'room for improvement'), and can mean a lodging or accommodation ('rent a room'). Many compounds: 'bedroom', 'bathroom', 'classroom'. 'Make room' means to create space.","ex":"She arranged the furniture to make the small room look bigger.","exh":"उसने छोटे कमरे को बड़ा दिखाने के लिए फर्नीचर व्यवस्थित किया।","syl":["room"],"syn":["chamber","space","apartment","compartment","area","hall","zone","scope","opportunity","capacity"],"ant":["corridor","outside","cramped space","no space"],"rel":["house","space","hall","kitchen","bedroom","office","floor","wall","ceiling","window"],"dif":"basic","fr":176,"ew":0.2,"it":"informational","rp":"medium","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"place","spr":"subject","dl":["verb","adjective","preposition"],"co":["the","a","living","bed","bath","class","my","small","big","enough","more"],"st":["space","enclosure","accommodation","opportunity"],"cv":["physical room use","space use ('no room')","opportunity use ('room to grow')"],"su":["subject","object"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"close","ph":"/kloʊz/","pos":"verb","gr":"predicate","rt":"close","fam":["closes","closed","closing","closure","disclose","enclose","foreclose","closest","closely","closeness"],"pl":"","tn":["close","closes","closed","closing"],"hi":"बंद करना/पास","en":"to shut; to end; to be near","ds":"To shut something; to bring to an end; near in distance or relationship.","dd":"'Close' as a verb (/kloʊz/) means to shut ('close the door'), to end ('close a meeting'), or to narrow a gap ('close the distance'). As an adjective (/kloʊs/) it means near in distance ('a close call'), intimate ('a close friend'), or careful ('close attention'). Note the different pronunciation for verb vs. adjective.","ex":"She closed the laptop and went to enjoy the sunny afternoon outside.","exh":"उसने लैपटॉप बंद किया और धूप भरी दोपहर का आनंद लेने बाहर गई।","syl":["close"],"syn":["shut","seal","end","finish","terminate","near","adjacent","intimate","thorough","careful"],"ant":["open","unlock","start","begin","distant","far","remote","casual","superficial"],"rel":["open","shut","seal","end","near","adjacent","finish","complete","intimate","attentive"],"dif":"basic","fr":177,"ew":0.2,"it":"action","rp":"medium","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"action","spr":"verb","dl":["subject","object","preposition"],"co":["the","door","window","eyes","down","off","up","call","friend","match","relationship"],"st":["closure","proximity","intimacy","careful attention"],"cv":["shut use","end use","near adjective use","'close call' (near miss)"],"su":["predicate","modifier"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"point","ph":"/pɔɪnt/","pos":"noun","gr":"subject","rt":"point","fam":["points","pointed","pointing","pointer","pointless","viewpoint","standpoint","counterpoint","flashpoint"],"pl":"points","tn":["point","points","pointed","pointing"],"hi":"बात/बिंदु/इशारा करना","en":"a specific fact, idea, or location; to indicate direction","ds":"A specific fact, idea, or location; to direct attention toward something.","dd":"'Point' as a noun means a specific place ('point on a map'), a fact or idea ('make a point'), a score unit ('three points'), a purpose ('what's the point?'), and the sharp tip of something. As a verb it means to direct toward ('point at'). Many compounds: 'viewpoint', 'standpoint', 'checkpoint'.","ex":"She made an excellent point during the discussion about education policy.","exh":"उसने शिक्षा नीति पर चर्चा के दौरान एक बेहतरीन बात कही।","syl":["point"],"syn":["spot","location","fact","argument","idea","tip","purpose","aim","score","direct","indicate"],"ant":["vague area","irrelevance","pointless","blunt","miss the point"],"rel":["place","location","idea","fact","tip","aim","purpose","purpose","score","argument"],"dif":"basic","fr":178,"ew":0.1,"it":"informational","rp":"high","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"general","spr":"subject","dl":["verb","adjective","preposition"],"co":["the","good","main","key","at this","to the","make a","of view","score","sharp"],"st":["location","argument","purpose","tip","score"],"cv":["location use","argument use","purpose use ('what's the point?')","verb use (indicate)"],"su":["subject","object"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"city","ph":"/ˈsɪti/","pos":"noun","gr":"subject","rt":"city","fam":["cities","citywide","city-state","inner city","metropolitan","urban","citizen"],"pl":"cities","tn":[],"hi":"शहर","en":"a large town; a major urban area","ds":"A large permanent settlement; a major urban center.","dd":"'City' refers to a large urban settlement, typically with its own government ('the city of London'). It is larger than a town and smaller than a metropolis, though definitions vary by country. 'City' often implies density, culture, commerce, and opportunity. 'Inner city' refers to older central districts.","ex":"She moved to the big city to find better career opportunities.","exh":"वह बेहतर करियर के अवसर ढूंढने के लिए बड़े शहर में चली गई।","syl":["cit","y"],"syn":["town","urban area","metropolis","municipality","capital","center","borough","urban center"],"ant":["countryside","rural area","village","wilderness","outskirts","suburb"],"rel":["town","village","district","area","urban","street","building","center","capital"],"dif":"basic","fr":179,"ew":0.2,"it":"informational","rp":"medium","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"place","spr":"subject","dl":["verb","adjective"],"co":["big","major","new","the","small","inner","old","home","busy","capital","nearby"],"st":["urban area","settlement","culture","opportunity"],"cv":["city use","'inner city' use","'city hall' use"],"su":["subject","object"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"five","ph":"/faɪv/","pos":"numeral","gr":"modifier","rt":"five","fam":["fifth","fifteen","fifty","fiver","five-star","five-year","five-day"],"pl":"","tn":[],"hi":"पाँच","en":"the number 5","ds":"The number 5; one more than four.","dd":"'Five' is the cardinal number 5. The ordinal form is 'fifth'. 'High five' is a celebratory gesture. 'Take five' is an idiom meaning 'take a short break'. 'Nine to five' refers to standard office hours. 'Fifteen' and 'fifty' are derived from 'five'.","ex":"She needs to buy five fresh vegetables from the market today.","exh":"उसे आज बाजार से पाँच ताजी सब्जियाँ खरीदनी हैं।","syl":["five"],"syn":["quintet","fivesome","quintuple","V"],"ant":["one","two","three","four","six"],"rel":["four","six","fifth","fifteen","fifty","five-star","five-day","quintuple"],"dif":"basic","fr":180,"ew":0.0,"it":"informational","rp":"medium","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"general","spr":"modifier","dl":["noun"],"co":["of","the","days","years","times","minutes","take","high","need","about"],"st":["number","quantity","fifth","quintuple"],"cv":["counting use","ordinal (fifth)","'high five' idiom"],"su":["modifier","subject"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"every","ph":"/ˈɛvri/","pos":"determiner","gr":"modifier","rt":"every","fam":["everyone","everything","everywhere","everyday","every day","everybody","forever"],"pl":"","tn":[],"hi":"हर/प्रत्येक","en":"each individual of a group; all members","ds":"Each individual one of all the members of a group.","dd":"'Every' indicates all members of a group individually ('every student'). It always takes a singular noun and verb ('every person is'). Contrasts with 'all' (collective). 'Every other' means alternate. 'Every now and then' means occasionally. 'Everyday' (adjective) means ordinary; 'every day' (adverb) means each day.","ex":"She exercises for thirty minutes every morning before going to work.","exh":"वह काम पर जाने से पहले हर सुबह तीस मिनट व्यायाम करती है।","syl":["ev","ery"],"syn":["each","all","any","each and every","without exception","apiece","per","individual"],"ant":["no","none","some","not all","few","neither","neither"],"rel":["each","all","any","whole","total","complete","individual","any one","each one"],"dif":"basic","fr":181,"ew":0.0,"it":"informational","rp":"high","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"general","spr":"modifier","dl":["noun"],"co":["day","week","year","morning","time","student","person","night","single","one"],"st":["totality","regularity","individual","universal"],"cv":["individual reference use","'every other' (alternate)","'every now and then' (occasionally)"],"su":["modifier","determiner"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"sit","ph":"/sɪt/","pos":"verb","gr":"predicate","rt":"sit","fam":["sits","sat","sitting","sitter","babysitter","sit-in","downside"],"pl":"","tn":["sit","sits","sat","sitting"],"hi":"बैठना","en":"to rest on one's buttocks; to be located","ds":"To rest in a seated position; to be in a specified position.","dd":"'Sit' means to be in a seated position ('sit on a chair'), to be located ('the town sits in a valley'), and in formal contexts to be in session ('parliament sits tomorrow'). Its irregular past tense is 'sat'. Phrasal verbs: 'sit down', 'sit up', 'sit in for', 'sit on'.","ex":"She sat quietly by the window and read her favorite book.","exh":"वह खिड़की के पास चुपचाप बैठ गई और अपनी पसंदीदा किताब पढ़ने लगी।","syl":["sit"],"syn":["seat oneself","be seated","rest","perch","settle","crouch","squat","occupy","be located"],"ant":["stand","lie","rise","get up","leave"],"rel":["stand","lie","rest","settle","place","seat","chair","bench","table","down"],"dif":"basic","fr":182,"ew":0.0,"it":"action","rp":"medium","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"action","spr":"verb","dl":["subject","place","preposition"],"co":["down","up","still","quietly","together","back","at","here","there","in","beside"],"st":["seated position","location","session","resting"],"cv":["seated posture use","location use","formal session use"],"su":["predicate"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","informal"]},
    {"w":"air","ph":"/ɛr/","pos":"noun","gr":"subject","rt":"air","fam":["airy","airtight","aircraft","airline","airfield","airbase","airport","airflow","airborne","fresh air"],"pl":"","tn":[],"hi":"हवा/वायु","en":"the invisible gaseous substance around the Earth","ds":"The mixture of gases that surrounds the Earth; the open space above ground.","dd":"'Air' refers to the gaseous atmosphere surrounding Earth, primarily nitrogen and oxygen. It means the open space above ('up in the air'), appearance or manner ('an air of confidence'), broadcasting ('on air'), and social manner ('airs and graces'). As a verb it means to ventilate or broadcast.","ex":"She opened the windows to let some fresh air into the room.","exh":"उसने कमरे में ताजी हवा आने देने के लिए खिड़कियाँ खोलीं।","syl":["air"],"syn":["atmosphere","wind","breeze","sky","space","oxygen","environment","aura","manner","feeling"],"ant":["water","earth","vacuum","sealed space"],"rel":["breath","wind","sky","atmosphere","oxygen","cloud","breeze","space","open","fresh"],"dif":"basic","fr":183,"ew":0.2,"it":"informational","rp":"medium","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"general","spr":"subject","dl":["verb","adjective"],"co":["fresh","clean","cold","open","on","in the","pure","quality","pollution","outdoor"],"st":["atmosphere","breathing","space","manner","broadcasting"],"cv":["atmosphere use","'in the air' (uncertain)","'on air' (broadcasting)"],"su":["subject","object"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"knew","ph":"/njuː/","pos":"verb","gr":"predicate","rt":"know","fam":["know","knows","known","knowing","knowledge","knowledgeable","unknown","foreknowledge"],"pl":"","tn":[],"hi":"जानता था","en":"past tense of know","ds":"The past tense of 'know': to have had knowledge of something.","dd":"'Knew' is the past tense of 'know', indicating past knowledge or awareness ('she knew the answer'). It can express past familiarity ('I knew her years ago'), past realization ('I knew it!'), and past acknowledgment ('we knew the risks'). The past participle is 'known'. 'Unknown' and 'well-known' are derived forms.","ex":"She knew the answer before the teacher finished asking the question.","exh":"शिक्षक ने प्रश्न पूछना समाप्त करने से पहले ही वह उत्तर जानती थी।","syl":["knew"],"syn":["was aware of","understood","recognized","realized","was familiar with","had knowledge of"],"ant":["ignored","was unaware","didn't know","was ignorant of"],"rel":["know","understand","recognize","realize","learn","discover","remember","find","see"],"dif":"basic","fr":184,"ew":0.1,"it":"informational","rp":"medium","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"general","spr":"verb","dl":["subject","object","clause"],"co":["I","she","he","we","they","already","always","never","well","that","it","what"],"st":["past knowledge","past familiarity","past realization"],"cv":["past knowledge use","past familiarity use","'I knew it!' exclamation"],"su":["predicate"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"six","ph":"/sɪks/","pos":"numeral","gr":"modifier","rt":"six","fam":["sixth","sixty","sixteen","sixfold","six-pack","half a dozen"],"pl":"","tn":[],"hi":"छह","en":"the number 6","ds":"The number 6; one more than five.","dd":"'Six' is the cardinal number 6. Ordinal: 'sixth'. Common idioms: 'six of one and half a dozen of the other' (equally balanced), 'at sixes and sevens' (in disarray), 'six-pack' (a set of six), 'sixth sense' (intuition beyond the five senses).","ex":"She planted six different kinds of flowers in her garden.","exh":"उसने अपने बगीचे में छह विभिन्न प्रकार के फूल लगाए।","syl":["six"],"syn":["half-dozen","sextet","sextuple","VI"],"ant":["one","two","three","four","five","seven"],"rel":["five","seven","sixth","sixty","sixteen","dozen","hexagon","hexagonal"],"dif":"basic","fr":185,"ew":0.0,"it":"informational","rp":"medium","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"general","spr":"modifier","dl":["noun"],"co":["of","the","days","years","months","weeks","hours","people","o'clock","sense"],"st":["number","quantity","sixth","hexagonal"],"cv":["counting use","ordinal (sixth)","'sixth sense' idiom"],"su":["modifier","subject"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"seven","ph":"/ˈsɛvən/","pos":"numeral","gr":"modifier","rt":"seven","fam":["seventh","seventy","seventeen","seven-day","the seven seas"],"pl":"","tn":[],"hi":"सात","en":"the number 7","ds":"The number 7; one more than six.","dd":"'Seven' is the cardinal number 7. Ordinal: 'seventh'. Seven has strong cultural significance: 'Seven Wonders of the World', 'seven deadly sins', 'seven days of the week'. 'Seventh heaven' means perfect happiness. 'Seventy' and 'seventeen' are derived from 'seven'.","ex":"She finished reading all seven chapters before going to sleep.","exh":"सोने जाने से पहले उसने सभी सात अध्याय पढ़ लिए।","syl":["sev","en"],"syn":["septet","sevenfold","VII","7"],"ant":["one","two","three","four","five","six","eight"],"rel":["six","eight","seventh","seventy","seventeen","week","days","wonder","deadly"],"dif":"basic","fr":186,"ew":0.0,"it":"informational","rp":"medium","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"general","spr":"modifier","dl":["noun"],"co":["of","the","days","years","weeks","deadly","seas","wonders","chapters","hours"],"st":["number","quantity","seventh","seven deadly sins"],"cv":["counting use","ordinal (seventh)","'seventh heaven' idiom"],"su":["modifier","subject"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"eight","ph":"/eɪt/","pos":"numeral","gr":"modifier","rt":"eight","fam":["eighth","eighty","eighteen","eight-day","one-eight","eightfold"],"pl":"","tn":[],"hi":"आठ","en":"the number 8","ds":"The number 8; one more than seven.","dd":"'Eight' is the cardinal number 8. Ordinal: 'eighth'. 'Figure eight' is the numeral 8 shape used in skating. 'Behind the eight ball' means in a difficult position (from pool/billiards). 'Eighty' and 'eighteen' are derived from 'eight'. Octagon and octave are related to the Latin/Greek equivalent.","ex":"She finished all eight tasks on her to-do list before noon.","exh":"उसने दोपहर से पहले अपनी टू-डू सूची के सभी आठ काम पूरे किए।","syl":["eight"],"syn":["octet","eightfold","VIII","8"],"ant":["one","two","three","four","five","six","seven","nine"],"rel":["seven","nine","eighth","eighty","eighteen","octagon","octave","behind the eight ball"],"dif":"basic","fr":187,"ew":0.0,"it":"informational","rp":"medium","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"general","spr":"modifier","dl":["noun"],"co":["of","the","days","years","hours","items","tasks","people","over","under"],"st":["number","quantity","eighth","eight-sided"],"cv":["counting use","ordinal (eighth)","figure-eight use"],"su":["modifier","subject"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"children","ph":"/ˈtʃɪldrən/","pos":"noun","gr":"subject","rt":"child","fam":["child","childhood","childish","childlike","grandchildren","stepchildren"],"pl":"","tn":[],"hi":"बच्चे","en":"plural of child; young people","ds":"Young people in general; plural of 'child'.","dd":"'Children' is the irregular plural of 'child'. It refers to young people generally or one's own sons and daughters. 'Childhood' is the period of being a child. 'Childish' means immature; 'childlike' means innocently simple. Many compound words begin with 'child': 'childcare', 'childbirth', 'child-proof'.","ex":"The children laughed and played happily in the school playground.","exh":"बच्चे स्कूल के खेल के मैदान में खुशी से हँसे और खेले।","syl":["chil","dren"],"syn":["kids","youngsters","youth","young ones","offspring","juniors","little ones","sons and daughters"],"ant":["adults","grown-ups","elders","seniors","parents"],"rel":["child","baby","toddler","teenager","youth","school","play","family","parent","grow"],"dif":"basic","fr":188,"ew":0.5,"it":"informational","rp":"medium","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"person","spr":"subject","dl":["verb","adjective"],"co":["the","young","small","many","few","her","his","their","school","love","teach"],"st":["youth","offspring","next generation","family","innocence"],"cv":["young people use","offspring use","'the children' (collective)"],"su":["subject","object"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"begin","ph":"/bɪˈɡɪn/","pos":"verb","gr":"predicate","rt":"begin","fam":["begins","began","begun","beginning","beginner","onset"],"pl":"","tn":["begin","begins","began","begun","beginning"],"hi":"शुरू करना","en":"to start; to come into existence","ds":"To start something; to take the first step.","dd":"'Begin' means to start ('begin a project'). Its irregular past tense is 'began' and past participle 'begun'. It is slightly more formal than 'start'. Can be followed by a gerund or infinitive with little meaning difference ('begin to work' or 'begin working'). 'Beginning' as a noun means the start.","ex":"She began her presentation by thanking everyone for attending.","exh":"उसने उपस्थित सभी लोगों का धन्यवाद करते हुए अपनी प्रस्तुति शुरू की।","syl":["be","gin"],"syn":["start","commence","initiate","open","launch","embark on","set out","get underway","kick off"],"ant":["end","finish","stop","conclude","complete","terminate","close","cease"],"rel":["start","open","launch","initiate","create","arise","originate","open","start off"],"dif":"basic","fr":189,"ew":0.2,"it":"action","rp":"high","cs":"opening","dc":"statement","td":"general","spr":"verb","dl":["subject","infinitive","gerund"],"co":["to","with","a","the","again","well","by","as","new","journey","fresh"],"st":["start","initiation","origin","first step"],"cv":["start use","'to begin with' (firstly)","'begin with' (start with)"],"su":["predicate"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"young","ph":"/jʌŋ/","pos":"adjective","gr":"modifier","rt":"young","fam":["younger","youngest","youngster","youth","youthful","young-at-heart"],"pl":"","tn":[],"hi":"युवा/छोटा (उम्र में)","en":"having lived for a short time; not old","ds":"Having lived for a relatively short time; not yet old.","dd":"'Young' describes living beings or things that have existed for a short time ('a young child', 'a young company'). As a noun 'the young' refers to young people. 'Young at heart' means feeling young despite age. 'Youngster' means a young person.","ex":"She has always supported young people who want to study abroad.","exh":"उसने हमेशा उन युवा लोगों का समर्थन किया है जो विदेश में पढ़ना चाहते हैं।","syl":["young"],"syn":["youthful","juvenile","immature","new","fresh","junior","early","budding","adolescent"],"ant":["old","elderly","mature","aged","senior","ancient","experienced"],"rel":["age","youth","childhood","adolescent","fresh","new","immature","generation","energy"],"dif":"basic","fr":190,"ew":0.3,"it":"descriptive","rp":"medium","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"person","spr":"modifier","dl":["noun"],"co":["very","too","so","quite","heart","people","child","man","woman","adult","generation"],"st":["age","youth","potential","freshness","inexperience"],"cv":["age adjective","'the young' (noun)","'young at heart' idiom"],"su":["modifier"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"leave","ph":"/liːv/","pos":"verb","gr":"predicate","rt":"leave","fam":["leaves","left","leaving","leftover","leave-taking","overleave"],"pl":"","tn":["leave","leaves","left","leaving"],"hi":"छोड़ना/जाना/छुट्टी","en":"to go away from; to cause to remain; to allow","ds":"To go away from a place; to allow something to remain.","dd":"'Leave' means to go away from ('leave the house'), to cause to remain ('leave it there'), to allow ('leave me alone'), to bequeath ('leave money in a will'), and as a noun 'leave' means an authorized absence ('sick leave', 'on leave'). Its irregular past tense is 'left'.","ex":"She left the meeting early because she had another appointment.","exh":"उसके एक और मुलाकात होने के कारण वह बैठक जल्दी छोड़ गई।","syl":["leave"],"syn":["depart","go away","exit","abandon","forsake","quit","permit","allow","remain","bequeath"],"ant":["arrive","stay","come","remain","return","keep","bring"],"rel":["go","depart","exit","abandon","give up","permit","allow","remain","stay","return"],"dif":"basic","fr":191,"ew":0.3,"it":"action","rp":"high","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"action","spr":"verb","dl":["subject","object","destination","place"],"co":["the","home","work","alone","behind","out","for","early","a note","a message","sick"],"st":["departure","abandonment","allowance","bequest","authorized absence"],"cv":["departure use","allow to remain use","permit use","noun use (authorized absence)"],"su":["predicate"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"land","ph":"/lænd/","pos":"noun","gr":"subject","rt":"land","fam":["lands","landed","landing","landlord","landmark","landscape","landlocked","mainland","homeland","farmland"],"pl":"lands","tn":["land","lands","landed","landing"],"hi":"भूमि/जमीन/उतरना","en":"the solid surface of the Earth; a country; to arrive on ground","ds":"The solid surface of the earth; a country or territory; to arrive on the ground.","dd":"'Land' as a noun refers to the solid ground of the earth, as opposed to water ('on land'), a country or territory ('a distant land'), agricultural ground ('farm land'). As a verb it means to arrive on the ground ('the plane landed'), to bring a fish onto land ('land a catch'), or to obtain ('land a job').","ex":"The plane landed safely at the airport after a long flight.","exh":"एक लंबी उड़ान के बाद विमान हवाई अड्डे पर सुरक्षित उतरा।","syl":["land"],"syn":["ground","earth","terrain","territory","country","nation","soil","field","region","alight"],"ant":["sea","water","ocean","depart","take off","air"],"rel":["ground","earth","country","territory","field","farm","soil","shore","arrive","region"],"dif":"basic","fr":192,"ew":0.2,"it":"informational","rp":"medium","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"place","spr":"subject","dl":["verb","adjective","preposition"],"co":["the","dry","foreign","native","promised","new","on","in","fertile","arid","home"],"st":["terrain","territory","country","agriculture","arrival"],"cv":["solid ground use","country/territory use","verb use (arrive)","'land a job' idiom"],"su":["subject","object"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"school","ph":"/skuːl/","pos":"noun","gr":"subject","rt":"school","fam":["schools","schooling","schooled","schoolboy","schoolgirl","preschool","schoolwork","school-age","schoolmate"],"pl":"schools","tn":[],"hi":"विद्यालय/स्कूल","en":"an institution for education; a group sharing a style","ds":"An institution where people learn; a period of education.","dd":"'School' refers to an educational institution ('attend school'), the period of being in school ('during school'), and a group sharing a method or style ('the Flemish school of painting'). 'School of thought' refers to a group with a shared viewpoint. As a verb 'school' means to educate or train.","ex":"She teaches mathematics at a highly regarded secondary school.","exh":"वह एक अत्यधिक प्रतिष्ठित माध्यमिक विद्यालय में गणित पढ़ाती है।","syl":["school"],"syn":["educational institution","academy","college","university","institute","education","learning","training"],"ant":["home","vacation","holiday","ignorance","uneducated"],"rel":["education","learning","teacher","student","class","study","college","university","book"],"dif":"basic","fr":193,"ew":0.4,"it":"informational","rp":"high","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"place","spr":"subject","dl":["verb","adjective"],"co":["the","my","high","primary","local","new","old","nearby","public","private"],"st":["education","institution","learning","group style"],"cv":["educational institution use","'school of thought' use","verb use (educate)"],"su":["subject","object"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"grow","ph":"/ɡroʊ/","pos":"verb","gr":"predicate","rt":"grow","fam":["grows","grew","grown","growing","growth","outgrow","overgrow","grown-up","grower","regrowth"],"pl":"","tn":["grow","grows","grew","grown","growing"],"hi":"उगाना/बढ़ना","en":"to increase in size; to develop; to cultivate","ds":"To increase in size or amount; to develop; to cultivate plants.","dd":"'Grow' means to increase in size ('the tree grew'), to develop ('grow as a person'), to cultivate ('grow vegetables'), and to become ('grow tired'). Its irregular past tense is 'grew' and past participle 'grown'. 'Grow up' means to become an adult. 'Grown-up' means an adult or mature person.","ex":"She grows fresh vegetables in her backyard garden every summer.","exh":"वह हर गर्मियों में अपने पिछवाड़े के बगीचे में ताजी सब्जियाँ उगाती है।","syl":["grow"],"syn":["expand","increase","develop","evolve","cultivate","mature","enlarge","flourish","thrive","extend"],"ant":["shrink","decrease","reduce","wither","die","decline","contract"],"rel":["develop","increase","expand","mature","learn","improve","evolve","flourish","grow up"],"dif":"basic","fr":194,"ew":0.3,"it":"action","rp":"medium","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"action","spr":"verb","dl":["subject","object","adjective"],"co":["up","bigger","larger","stronger","older","fast","slowly","well","crops","vegetables"],"st":["growth","development","cultivation","maturation"],"cv":["size increase use","cultivation use","maturation use","'grow up' (become adult)"],"su":["predicate"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"study","ph":"/ˈstʌdi/","pos":"verb","gr":"predicate","rt":"study","fam":["studies","studied","studying","student","studious","studio","study room"],"pl":"","tn":["study","studies","studied","studying"],"hi":"अध्ययन करना/पढ़ाई","en":"to devote time and attention to learning","ds":"To apply the mind to learning about a subject or skill.","dd":"'Study' as a verb means to learn ('study medicine'), to observe ('study the stars'), and to analyze ('study the data'). As a noun it is the act of learning, a research report ('a study shows'), or a room for working. 'Studies' often refers to academic subjects. 'Studious' means diligent in study.","ex":"She studied hard for three months before taking her final exams.","exh":"उसने अपनी अंतिम परीक्षाएँ देने से पहले तीन महीने तक कड़ी मेहनत से पढ़ाई की।","syl":["stu","dy"],"syn":["learn","research","examine","investigate","read","review","analyze","observe","prepare","consider"],"ant":["ignore","play","relax","neglect","be idle","avoid"],"rel":["learn","read","research","practice","review","prepare","analyze","education","exam"],"dif":"basic","fr":195,"ew":0.3,"it":"action","rp":"high","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"action","spr":"verb","dl":["subject","object"],"co":["hard","well","carefully","for","at","medicine","law","science","English","math"],"st":["learning","research","analysis","academic","observation"],"cv":["learn use","research use","room use","'a study shows' use"],"su":["predicate"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"learn","ph":"/lɜːrn/","pos":"verb","gr":"predicate","rt":"learn","fam":["learns","learned","learnt","learning","learner","relearn","unlearn","well-learned","lifelong learning"],"pl":"","tn":["learn","learns","learned","learning"],"hi":"सीखना","en":"to gain knowledge or skill through study or experience","ds":"To gain knowledge or a skill through experience or study.","dd":"'Learn' means to acquire knowledge ('learn a language'), to find out ('learn the truth'), and to memorize ('learn a poem by heart'). Both 'learned' and 'learnt' are acceptable past tenses; 'learned' is preferred in American English, 'learnt' in British English. 'Lifelong learning' means continuing to learn throughout life.","ex":"She has always loved to learn new skills in her free time.","exh":"उसे हमेशा अपने खाली समय में नए कौशल सीखना पसंद रहा है।","syl":["learn"],"syn":["acquire","gain","study","master","discover","pick up","absorb","understand","memorize","become aware"],"ant":["forget","unlearn","ignore","teach","instruct","be ignorant"],"rel":["study","teach","understand","skill","knowledge","improve","practice","grow","develop"],"dif":"basic","fr":196,"ew":0.5,"it":"action","rp":"high","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"action","spr":"verb","dl":["subject","object","language","from","how to"],"co":["how","to","from","by","a","new","quickly","well","together","lesson","skill"],"st":["knowledge acquisition","skill development","discovery","education"],"cv":["knowledge acquisition use","skill learning use","'learn a lesson' use"],"su":["predicate"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"plant","ph":"/plænt/","pos":"noun","gr":"subject","rt":"plant","fam":["plants","planted","planting","planter","replant","transplant","houseplant","plantation","plantlife"],"pl":"plants","tn":["plant","plants","planted","planting"],"hi":"पौधा/संयंत्र/लगाना","en":"a living organism with roots, stem, and leaves; a factory; to put in the ground","ds":"A living organism that grows in soil; a factory; to put into the ground.","dd":"'Plant' as a noun refers to a living organism ('a plant in the garden'), a factory or industrial facility ('a manufacturing plant'), or something deliberately placed ('a plant in the audience'). As a verb it means to put seeds or plants in the ground, to place deliberately, or to set up an installation.","ex":"She planted several flowering plants along the front garden path.","exh":"उसने सामने के बगीचे के रास्ते के किनारे कई फूलों के पौधे लगाए।","syl":["plant"],"syn":["vegetation","organism","bush","herb","shrub","tree","factory","facility","sow","seed"],"ant":["uproot","remove","harvest","pull out"],"rel":["tree","flower","grow","garden","seed","root","leaf","nature","factory","agriculture"],"dif":"basic","fr":197,"ew":0.3,"it":"informational","rp":"medium","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"general","spr":"subject","dl":["verb","adjective"],"co":["the","a","flowering","tropical","herb","indoor","outdoor","seed","grow","water"],"st":["organism","vegetation","factory","deliberate placement"],"cv":["living organism use","factory use","verb use (plant seeds)","'plant evidence' use"],"su":["subject","object"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"sun","ph":"/sʌn/","pos":"noun","gr":"subject","rt":"sun","fam":["sunny","sunlight","sunrise","sunset","sunshine","sunflower","sunburn","sunscreen","sunbathe","sunglasses"],"pl":"","tn":[],"hi":"सूरज/सूर्य","en":"the star at the center of the solar system","ds":"The star at the center of our solar system that provides light and heat.","dd":"'Sun' refers to the star at the center of the solar system ('the Sun'), sunlight generally ('plenty of sun'), and as a verb means to expose to sunlight ('sun yourself on the beach'). Capitalized 'Sun' when referring specifically to Earth's star. Many compounds: 'sunrise', 'sunset', 'sunflower', 'sunshine'.","ex":"She loves sitting outside to enjoy the warmth of the morning sun.","exh":"वह सुबह की धूप की गर्माहट का आनंद लेने के लिए बाहर बैठना पसंद करती है।","syl":["sun"],"syn":["star","solar body","daystar","sunshine","sunlight","daylight","warmth","light","Sol"],"ant":["moon","darkness","shadow","night"],"rel":["moon","star","sky","light","warmth","heat","day","shine","brightness","solar"],"dif":"basic","fr":198,"ew":0.6,"it":"informational","rp":"medium","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"general","spr":"subject","dl":["verb","adjective"],"co":["the","bright","warm","morning","evening","shining","setting","rising","under","in the"],"st":["celestial body","warmth","light","energy","nature"],"cv":["star use","sunlight use","verb use (sun oneself)","metaphorical warmth use"],"su":["subject","object"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"light","ph":"/laɪt/","pos":"noun","gr":"subject","rt":"light","fam":["lights","lit","lighting","lighter","lighthouse","daylight","moonlight","sunlight","lightweight","enlighten"],"pl":"lights","tn":["light","lights","lit/lighted","lighting"],"hi":"प्रकाश/रोशनी/हल्का","en":"electromagnetic radiation visible to the eye; not heavy","ds":"The natural or artificial electromagnetic radiation visible to the human eye; not heavy.","dd":"'Light' as a noun refers to visible electromagnetic radiation ('sunlight'), a source of light ('a lamp'), knowledge ('shed light on'), and celebrity ('in the public light'). As an adjective it means 'not heavy' ('a light bag'), 'pale in color' ('light blue'), or 'not intense' ('a light meal'). As a verb it means to illuminate or ignite.","ex":"She turned on the light and started reading her book carefully.","exh":"उसने लाइट जलाई और ध्यान से अपनी किताब पढ़ने लगी।","syl":["light"],"syn":["illumination","glow","brightness","radiance","lamp","torch","pale","not heavy","trivial","gentle"],"ant":["dark","darkness","heavy","shade","dim","gloom","serious","extinguish","weighty"],"rel":["sun","glow","lamp","bright","shine","see","day","clear","pale","easy","weight"],"dif":"basic","fr":199,"ew":0.4,"it":"informational","rp":"medium","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"general","spr":"subject","dl":["verb","adjective"],"co":["the","sun","moon","bright","green","red","candle","natural","shine","morning"],"st":["illumination","visibility","knowledge","weight (not heavy)","color (pale)"],"cv":["electromagnetic radiation use","lamp use","'shed light on' idiom","adjective use (not heavy)"],"su":["subject","object","modifier"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
    {"w":"voice","ph":"/vɔɪs/","pos":"noun","gr":"subject","rt":"voice","fam":["voices","voiced","voicing","voiceless","spokesman","vocal","vocalist","voicemail","voice-over"],"pl":"voices","tn":["voice","voices","voiced","voicing"],"hi":"आवाज़/स्वर","en":"the sound produced in a person's throat when speaking","ds":"The sound produced when speaking or singing; an expressed opinion.","dd":"'Voice' refers to the sound produced in speech or singing ('a beautiful voice'), an expressed opinion ('give voice to'), in grammar the relationship between verb and subject (active/passive voice), and in music the individual melodic part. As a verb it means to express or articulate ('voice an opinion').","ex":"She has a beautiful voice and performs at local concerts regularly.","exh":"उसकी एक सुंदर आवाज़ है और वह नियमित रूप से स्थानीय संगीत कार्यक्रमों में प्रस्तुति देती है।","syl":["voice"],"syn":["sound","tone","expression","speech","utterance","opinion","vote","vocal","singer","say"],"ant":["silence","muteness","voicelessness","wordlessness","mute"],"rel":["sound","speak","sing","express","opinion","tone","language","music","communicate"],"dif":"basic","fr":200,"ew":0.5,"it":"informational","rp":"medium","cs":"any","dc":"statement","td":"general","spr":"subject","dl":["verb","adjective"],"co":["a","the","beautiful","soft","loud","clear","strong","raise","lower","my","her"],"st":["speech sound","opinion expression","grammar","music"],"cv":["speech sound use","opinion use","grammar voice use","'voice over' use"],"su":["subject","object"],"wuc":["daily conversation","writing","formal","informal"]},
